  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't just touch, release! Peritoneal pain speaks volumes.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe question describes migratory right iliac fossa pain, a classic presentation of acute appendicitis. Rebound tenderness, also known as Blumberg sign, is a critical physical exam finding indicating peritoneal irritation, which is highly suggestive of appendicitis in this clinical context.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nRebound tenderness is elicited by slowly pressing deeply into the right lower quadrant and then quickly releasing the pressure. Pain upon release, rather than on palpation, signifies inflammation of the parietal peritoneum. This is a more specific sign of peritoneal irritation than simple tenderness, as the rapid recoil of the abdominal wall causes the inflamed peritoneal surfaces to rub against each other, eliciting sharp pain. Its presence strongly supports a diagnosis of acute appendicitis.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Tenderness right iliac fossa) (Incorrect): While tenderness in the RIF is expected in appendicitis, it is a less specific sign than rebound tenderness, which directly indicates peritoneal inflammation.\nOption C (Which is the safest method of drainage of appendicular abscess?) (Incorrect): This is a question about management, not a physical exam finding or a diagnostic sign for the initial presentation of migratory RIF pain.\nOption D (Intraperitoneal drainage) (Incorrect): This describes a surgical intervention for an abscess, not a diagnostic sign for appendicitis. Furthermore, percutaneous drainage is often preferred for appendicular abscesses when feasible.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Sign | Description | Significance in Appendicitis |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Blumberg Sign** (Rebound Tenderness) | Pain upon rapid release of deep palpation | Indicates parietal peritoneal irritation/inflammation |\n| **Rovsing's Sign** | Palpation of left iliac fossa causes pain in right iliac fossa | Referred pain due to stretching of peritoneum |\n| **Psoas Sign** | Pain on passive extension of right hip or active flexion against resistance | Suggests retrocecal appendix irritating the psoas muscle |\n| **Obturator Sign** | Pain on passive internal rotation of flexed right hip | Suggests pelvic appendix irritating the obturator internus muscle |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Blumberg means bad peritoneum.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT scan, findings include a dilated appendix (>6mm diameter), periappendiceal fat stranding, appendicolith, and possibly a pericecal fluid collection. Intraoperatively, a hyperemic, edematous, and often purulent appendix will be seen, sometimes with surrounding inflammatory exudate or frank perforation.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nWorld Society of Emergency Surgery (WSES) Guidelines for the Management of Acute Appendicitis (2020). These guidelines recommend clinical evaluation combined with imaging (ultrasound or CT) for diagnosis, and emphasize the role of physical examination findings like rebound tenderness in guiding management.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Tenderness right iliac fossa | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Rebound tenderness | ✅ Correct |\n| C | Which is the safest method of drainage of appendicular abscess? | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Intraperitoneal drainage | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) Rebound tenderness** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Chapter: Appendix** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Specialty: General Surgery**\n",
  "verified_answer": "B"
