  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When the appendix screams, listen closely and act swiftly.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Acute appendicitis. This classic presentation of right lower quadrant pain, specifically at McBurney's point, accompanied by fever greater than 38.5°C, is highly suggestive of acute appendicitis in children.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nAcute appendicitis is inflammation of the vermiform appendix, typically due to luminal obstruction by a fecalith, lymphoid hyperplasia, or foreign body. This obstruction leads to increased intraluminal pressure, venous congestion, ischemia, and bacterial overgrowth, causing inflammation and pain. McBurney's point, located one-third of the way from the anterior superior iliac spine to the umbilicus, is the classic site of maximal tenderness due to the appendix's anatomical position. Fever, particularly above 38.5°C, indicates a significant inflammatory response.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption C (Incorrect): Acute Meckel’s diverticulitis can cause right lower quadrant pain, but it is less common than appendicitis and often presents with painless rectal bleeding or obstruction. While inflammation can occur, McBurney's point tenderness is not its classic presentation.\nOption D (Incorrect): Acute mesenteric lymphadenitis is inflammation of the mesenteric lymph nodes, often viral, and can mimic appendicitis. However, it typically presents with more diffuse abdominal pain, less localized tenderness at McBurney's point, and often a history of recent upper respiratory infection. High fever is less specific to this condition compared to appendicitis.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Condition | Key Features | Diagnostic Clues |\n|---|---|---|\n| Acute Appendicitis | Periumbilical pain migrating to RLQ, McBurney's tenderness, fever, anorexia, nausea/vomiting | Alvarado score, US/CT showing dilated appendix (>6mm), appendicolith |\n| Acute Meckel's Diverticulitis | RLQ pain, often painless rectal bleeding (children), obstruction | Technetium-99m pertechnetate scan (Meckel's scan) |\n| Acute Mesenteric Lymphadenitis | Diffuse abdominal pain, often post-viral, less localized tenderness, cervical lymphadenopathy | US/CT showing enlarged mesenteric lymph nodes, normal appendix |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: McBurney's point + fever = Appendicitis until proven otherwise.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound or CT, an inflamed appendix appears as a non-compressible, blind-ending tubular structure originating from the cecum, with a diameter greater than 6mm, often with surrounding fat stranding and sometimes an appendicolith. Intraoperatively, the appendix will be erythematous, edematous, and potentially purulent or perforated.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nWorld Society of Emergency Surgery (WSES) Guidelines for the Management of Acute Appendicitis (2020) recommends ultrasound as the initial imaging modality for suspected appendicitis in children, followed by CT if ultrasound is inconclusive.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Pain at McBurney’s point and a temperature greater than 38.5°C in children  | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Acute appendicitis | ✅ Correct |\n| C | Acute Meckel’s diverticulitis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Acute mesenteric lymphadenitis | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) Acute appendicitis** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Chapter: Appendix** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Specialty: General Surgery**\n",
  "verified_answer": "B"
