  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Melanoma in the eye? Think choroid, adult, liver.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe most common primary intraocular tumor in adults is malignant melanoma, specifically choroidal melanoma. This verdict is correct because choroidal melanoma accounts for the vast majority of primary ocular malignancies in adults, originating from melanocytes in the uveal tract.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nChoroidal melanoma arises from melanocytes within the choroid, the vascular layer of the uvea. Its incidence increases with age, and it is distinct from cutaneous melanoma in its genetic profile and metastatic patterns. The tumor typically grows within the eye, often presenting with visual symptoms or being discovered incidentally during routine examination. Early detection is crucial for prognosis, as metastasis, particularly to the liver, is a significant concern.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Retinoblastoma is the most common primary intraocular malignancy in *childhood*, not adulthood.\nOption B (Incorrect): Retinal gliomas are extremely rare primary tumors of the retina; optic nerve gliomas are more common but still not the most common adult ocular tumor.\nOption D (Incorrect): Choroidal sarcoma is a very rare tumor; malignant melanoma is by far the most common primary choroidal malignancy.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Choroidal Melanoma | Retinoblastoma | Ocular Metastasis |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Age Group** | Adults (most common primary) | Children (most common primary) | Any age (often adults) |\n| **Origin** | Melanocytes in choroid | Retinal photoreceptor precursors | Distant primary tumor (e.g., breast, lung) |\n| **Incidence** | 5-7 cases/million/year | 1 in 15,000-20,000 live births | Most common *intraocular tumor* overall |\n| **Prognosis** | Depends on size, location, metastasis; liver is common site | Excellent with early treatment; genetic counseling important | Depends on primary tumor and extent of metastasis |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Choroidal melanoma is the adult's primary ocular tumor; retinoblastoma is the child's.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn B-scan ultrasonography, choroidal melanoma typically appears as a dome-shaped or mushroom-shaped lesion with low to medium internal reflectivity and choroidal excavation. Intraoperatively, depending on the treatment (e.g., enucleation), the globe would reveal a pigmented mass within the choroid, often with associated retinal detachment.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Academy of Ophthalmology (AAO) Preferred Practice Pattern for Uveal Melanoma (latest edition, e.g., 2023-2024). It recommends comprehensive ophthalmic examination, imaging (ultrasound, OCT, angiography), and consideration of biopsy for diagnosis, with treatment options including brachytherapy, enucleation, or proton beam radiation.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Retinoblastoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Retinal glioma | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Malignant melanoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Choroidal sarcoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: ?) Deep vein thrombosis** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Competency 2500**\n"
