  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Retinal detachment: Time is vision. Don't delay, refer today!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nRetinal detachment is a critical ophthalmological emergency requiring prompt surgical intervention to preserve vision. It occurs when the neurosensory retina separates from the underlying retinal pigment epithelium, leading to photoreceptor dysfunction and potential permanent vision loss.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe retina, a light-sensitive tissue, relies on its attachment to the retinal pigment epithelium for metabolic support. Detachment disrupts this vital connection, causing ischemia and degeneration of photoreceptors. Surgical repair aims to re-appose the retina, often involving vitrectomy, scleral buckling, or pneumatic retinopexy, to restore anatomical integrity and prevent irreversible vision loss.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Metastasis) (Incorrect): While malignant melanoma can metastasize, metastasis itself is not a primary ophthalmological emergency like retinal detachment.\nOption B (Hepatocellular carcinoma) (Incorrect): Hepatocellular carcinoma is a primary liver malignancy and bears no direct relation to the pathophysiology or treatment of retinal detachment.\nOption C (The following facts are true regarding the anatomy of the ear except) (Incorrect): This is a question stem about ear anatomy, entirely unrelated to retinal detachment.\nOption D (Infection of the middle ear and mastoid can spread to cranial cavity) (Incorrect): This statement describes a complication of otitis media, which is not relevant to the diagnosis or management of retinal detachment.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Type of Retinal Detachment | Cause | Key Feature | Treatment |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Rhegmatogenous | Retinal break/tear | Vitreous traction, fluid accumulation | Vitrectomy, scleral buckle, pneumatic retinopexy |\n| Tractional | Fibrovascular proliferation | Vitreous membranes pull on retina | Vitrectomy to release traction |\n| Exudative | Subretinal fluid accumulation | No retinal break, fluid from choroid | Treat underlying cause (e.g., inflammation, tumor) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Acute, painless vision loss with floaters/flashes demands urgent ophthalmology consult for retinal detachment.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn fundoscopy, a detached retina appears as a gray, undulating membrane, often with a visible tear (rhegmatogenous). Intraoperatively, vitrectomy clears vitreous opacities, allowing re-attachment.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Academy of Ophthalmology (AAO) Preferred Practice Pattern for Retinal Detachment (latest year). Recommends urgent surgical repair for rhegmatogenous retinal detachment.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Metastasis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Hepatocellular carcinoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | The following facts are true regarding the anatomy of the ear except | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Infection of the middle ear and mastoid can spread to cranial cavity | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: ?) Retinal detachment** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Competency 2500**\n"
