  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Red eye? Think pink eye first, then panic later.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe verdict is correct: Conjunctivitis is indeed the most common cause of acute red eye. This condition involves inflammation of the conjunctiva, the transparent membrane lining the eyelid and covering the white part of the eye, making it highly susceptible to external irritants and pathogens.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe conjunctiva is a highly vascularized and exposed mucous membrane, making it prone to inflammation from a wide array of causes including viral, bacterial, and allergic agents. Its superficial location means that inflammation readily manifests as diffuse redness due to vasodilation of the superficial conjunctival vessels. This constant exposure to the environment and rich blood supply contribute to its high incidence as the primary cause of acute red eye, often presenting with symptoms like itching, burning, and discharge.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Acute glaucoma): Incorrect. Acute angle-closure glaucoma is a serious ophthalmic emergency causing red eye, pain, and vision loss, but it is significantly less common than conjunctivitis.\nOption A (Uveitis): Incorrect. Uveitis, inflammation of the uveal tract, can cause red eye and pain, but it is also less common than conjunctivitis and often more severe.\nOption B (Scleritis): Incorrect. Scleritis is a rare, severe, and painful inflammation of the sclera, often associated with systemic autoimmune diseases, making it far less common than conjunctivitis.\nOption C (The causes of central retinal vein thrombosis are the following except): Incorrect. This is a malformed option and not a cause of acute red eye; it appears to be a partial question stem from another context.\nOption D (Diabetes mellitus): Incorrect. Diabetes mellitus is a systemic disease with ocular complications, but it is not a direct or common cause of acute red eye itself.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Condition | Redness Pattern | Pain | Vision | Pupil | Discharge | Incidence |\n|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|\n| Conjunctivitis | Diffuse, peripheral | Mild grittiness/itch | Normal | Normal | Watery/Purulent | Very Common |\n| Acute Glaucoma | Ciliary flush, limbal | Severe, sudden | Markedly decreased | Mid-dilated, fixed | None | Uncommon |\n| Uveitis | Ciliary flush | Moderate to severe | Decreased | Small, irregular | None | Less Common |\n| Scleritis | Deep, localized/diffuse | Severe, boring | Normal to decreased | Normal | None | Rare |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: When in doubt about acute red eye, think conjunctivitis first.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nImaging is typically not required for conjunctivitis. On slit-lamp examination, diffuse conjunctival injection, papillae or follicles, and varying degrees of discharge would be observed.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Academy of Ophthalmology (AAO) Preferred Practice Pattern for Conjunctivitis (2023). It recommends clinical diagnosis and often supportive care, reserving antibiotics for bacterial cases.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Acute glaucoma\tB. Uveitis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | C. Conjunctivitis\tD. Scleritis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | The causes of central retinal vein thrombosis are the following except | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Diabetes mellitus | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: ?) B) Conjunctivitis** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Competency 2500**\n"
