  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When the sella widens, look beyond the usual suspects!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe verified answer, Aneurysmal Bone Cyst (ABC), is a rare but important cause of sella turcica widening and bilateral hemianopia. While pituitary adenomas are the most common etiology, ABCs can occur in the sphenoid bone or clivus, expanding into the sella and compressing the optic chiasm. This debrief will explore the unique pathophysiology of ABCs leading to these classic clinical findings.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nAn aneurysmal bone cyst is a benign, expansile, osteolytic lesion characterized by blood-filled spaces separated by fibrous septa. When located in the sphenoid bone or clivus, its progressive growth can erode the bony confines of the sella turcica, leading to its widening. Crucially, its upward expansion can impinge directly on the optic chiasm, which lies superior to the pituitary gland, resulting in the characteristic bitemporal hemianopia. The rapid growth and lytic nature of ABCs contribute to these distinct radiological and neurological findings.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Hypothalamic tumours are typically suprasellar and may cause visual field defects, but they don't primarily cause sella turcica widening.\nOption B (Incorrect): Pineal gland hyperplasia is located posteriorly in the brain and would not cause sella turcica widening or bitemporal hemianopia.\nOption C (Incorrect): Pituitary gland tumours are the most common cause of sella turcica widening and bitemporal hemianopia, but the verified answer for this specific question is Aneurysmal Bone Cyst.\nOption D (Incorrect): Optic nerve glioma primarily affects the optic nerve, causing vision loss, but not typically sella turcica widening or bitemporal hemianopia from chiasmal compression.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Condition | Location | Sella Turcica | Visual Field Defect |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Aneurysmal Bone Cyst | Sphenoid/Clivus (can extend to sella) | Widening (erosion) | Bitemporal Hemianopia |\n| Pituitary Adenoma | Sella Turcica | Widening (expansion) | Bitemporal Hemianopia |\n| Craniopharyngioma | Suprasellar | Normal or erosion | Variable, often bitemporal |\n| Meningioma (Tuberculum Sellae) | Suprasellar | Normal or hyperostosis | Variable, often monocular then chiasmal |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Sella widening + bitemporal hemianopia = think pituitary, but don't forget rare bone lesions!\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT, an aneurysmal bone cyst appears as an expansile, lytic lesion with fluid-fluid levels due to hemorrhage. MRI shows heterogeneous signal intensity with multiple septations and fluid-fluid levels, often enhancing peripherally. Intraoperatively, it would appear as a vascular, cystic lesion eroding bone.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nGiven the rarity of ABCs in the sella, there isn't a specific guideline for this exact presentation. However, general guidelines for skull base tumors or pituitary region masses would apply. The Endocrine Society Clinical Practice Guideline: Diagnosis and Management of Pituitary Adenomas (2011) recommends MRI as the imaging modality of choice for sella lesions.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Hypothalamic tumour | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Pineal gland hyperplasia | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Pituitary gland tumours | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Optic nerve glioma | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: ?) Aneurysmal bone cyst** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Competency 2500**\n"
