  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Bariatric surgery isn't about sobriety; it's about health, not just size.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe question asks to identify the factor that is NOT an indication for bariatric surgery. While the provided 'VERIFIED ANSWER' was irrelevant, option D, 'Non-alcoholic,' is correctly identified as the exception, as it is not a criterion for surgical intervention.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nBariatric surgery indications are well-established, primarily focusing on Body Mass Index (BMI) thresholds and the presence of obesity-related comorbidities. A BMI greater than 40 kg/m² is a standalone indication, while a BMI greater than 35 kg/m² requires at least one significant comorbidity like type 2 diabetes or severe sleep apnea. These criteria ensure that surgery is offered to patients who stand to gain the most health benefit and for whom non-surgical interventions have proven insufficient, reflecting a multidisciplinary approach to patient selection.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): 'Except' is part of the question stem, indicating that the task is to find the non-indication, not an answer option itself.\nOption B (Incorrect): BMI more than 40 kg/m² is a primary and absolute indication for bariatric surgery, even in the absence of comorbidities.\nOption C (Incorrect): While not a standalone indication, a history of sustained obesity (e.g., for 5 years) and documented failed attempts at non-surgical weight loss are typically prerequisites for bariatric surgery, demonstrating the chronicity of the condition and the need for intervention.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Category | Example | Relevance |\n|---|---|---|\n| Absolute Indication | BMI > 40 kg/m² | Primary criterion for surgery, regardless of comorbidities |\n| Relative Indication | BMI > 35 kg/m² with T2DM | Requires significant comorbidity for surgical consideration |\n| Pre-requisite/Context | Obesity for >5 years, failed non-surgical weight loss | Demonstrates chronicity and need for intervention |\n| Irrelevant Factor | Non-alcoholic status | Not a criterion for surgery; active alcoholism is a contraindication |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Bariatric surgery indications hinge on BMI, comorbidities, and failed conservative management.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nPre-operative imaging, such as abdominal ultrasound or CT, frequently reveals hepatomegaly and fatty infiltration of the liver, which can influence surgical planning and intraoperative technique.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Society for Metabolic and Bariatric Surgery (ASMBS) and International Federation for the Surgery of Obesity and Metabolic Disorders (IFSO) Guidelines (2022) recommend bariatric surgery for individuals with BMI ≥ 40 kg/m² or BMI ≥ 35 kg/m² with at least one obesity-related comorbidity.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | except | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | BMI more than 40 | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Obesity for last 5 years | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Non-alcoholic | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: ?) Antibiotics** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Competency 2500**\n"
