  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 GERD surgery wraps the esophagus, not removes the stomach.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Billroth II gastrectomy. This procedure is primarily indicated for gastric outlet obstruction, peptic ulcer disease complications, or gastric malignancy, not for the treatment of gastroesophageal reflux disease (GERD). The other options are all recognized surgical interventions for GERD.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nSurgical management of GERD aims to restore the competence of the lower esophageal sphincter (LES) and eliminate reflux. Procedures like Nissen, Belsey, and Hill achieve this by creating a fundoplication or gastropexy that reinforces the LES and prevents gastric contents from refluxing into the esophagus. This involves anatomical reconstruction of the esophagogastric junction, often incorporating the diaphragmatic crura, to create a high-pressure zone.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Nissen fundoplication is a 360-degree wrap of the gastric fundus around the distal esophagus, widely considered the gold standard for GERD surgery. \nOption B (Incorrect): Belsey operation (Belsey Mark IV fundoplication) is a partial (270-degree) anterior fundoplication, an older but still recognized technique for GERD. \nOption C (Incorrect): Hill procedure (posterior gastropexy) involves anchoring the lesser curvature of the stomach to the median arcuate ligament and reconstructing the gastroesophageal valve, another established GERD surgery.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Surgical Procedure | Type of Wrap/Fixation | Primary Indication | Key Feature |\n|--------------------|-----------------------|--------------------|-------------|\n| Nissen Fundoplication | 360-degree fundoplication | GERD | Most common, effective for severe reflux |\n| Belsey Mark IV | 270-degree anterior fundoplication | GERD | Less dysphagia risk than Nissen, older technique |\n| Hill Procedure | Posterior gastropexy | GERD | Fixes stomach to median arcuate ligament |\n| Billroth II Gastrectomy | Gastric resection with gastrojejunostomy | PUD, Gastric Cancer | Not for GERD; can cause bile reflux |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Fundoplications fix reflux; gastrectomies fix ulcers or cancer.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIntraoperatively, a fundoplication involves mobilizing the gastric fundus and wrapping it around the esophagus. On a postoperative upper GI series, a well-formed fundoplication will appear as a smooth, symmetric indentation around the distal esophagus, with no free reflux of contrast.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nThe 2022 American College of Gastroenterology (ACG) Clinical Guideline for the Diagnosis and Management of Gastroesophageal Reflux Disease recommends fundoplication for carefully selected patients with GERD refractory to medical therapy.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Nissen fundoplication | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Belsey operation | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Hill procedure | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Billroth II gastrectomy | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: ?) Diverticulo-esophagostomy. (endoscopic)** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Competency 2500**\n"
