  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Smooth muscle, smooth sailing: Leiomyoma leads the benign pack.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe verdict is ACCEPT. The most common benign tumor of the esophagus is a leiomyoma, which arises from the smooth muscle layer of the esophageal wall. Understanding its prevalence and origin is key for diagnosis and management.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nLeiomyomas are typically slow-growing, intramural lesions originating from the muscularis propria. They are often asymptomatic, discovered incidentally, but can cause dysphagia, pain, or bleeding if large enough. Their submucosal location makes them amenable to endoscopic or surgical enucleation, preserving esophageal function. They are distinct from malignant lesions by their well-circumscribed, non-invasive nature.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Fibromas are benign fibrous tumors but are exceedingly rare in the esophagus compared to leiomyomas. \nOption B (Incorrect): Lipomas are benign fatty tumors, also very rare in the esophagus, typically found in the submucosa. \nOption D (Incorrect): Haemangiomas are benign vascular tumors, extremely uncommon in the esophagus and usually present with bleeding.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Benign Esophageal Tumor | Origin Tissue | Relative Frequency | Key Feature |\n| :--------------------- | :------------ | :----------------- | :---------- |\n| Leiomyoma              | Smooth muscle | Most common        | Intramural, often asymptomatic |\n| Lipoma                 | Adipose tissue| Rare               | Submucosal, soft |\n| Fibroma                | Fibrous tissue| Very rare          | Firm, sessile or pedunculated |\n| Hemangioma             | Vascular tissue| Extremely rare     | Prone to bleeding |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Leiomyoma: the smooth muscle king of benign esophageal tumors.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn endoscopy, a leiomyoma appears as a smooth, firm, submucosal bulge with normal overlying mucosa. EUS typically shows a hypoechoic, homogeneous lesion originating from the muscularis propria. Intraoperatively, it's a well-circumscribed, firm, encapsulated mass that can be enucleated from the esophageal wall.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nSAGES Clinical Spotlight Review: Surgical Management of Esophageal Leiomyoma (2017) recommends minimally invasive enucleation for symptomatic or growing lesions, emphasizing preservation of esophageal integrity.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Fibroma | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Lipoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Leiomyoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Haemangioma | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: ?) Lower segment opens into trachea** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Competency 2500**\n"
