  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Airway invasion: a critical determinant for esophageal cancer surgery.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe verdict is that 'Look for tracheobronchial involvement' is the correct answer. Bronchoscopy is a crucial diagnostic tool in the staging of esophageal carcinoma, specifically to assess the extent of local invasion into the adjacent airway.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe esophagus lies in close anatomical proximity to the trachea and main bronchi. Carcinoma of the esophagus, particularly in the mid and upper thoracic segments, can directly invade these structures. Bronchoscopy allows for direct visualization of the tracheobronchial tree to detect signs of extrinsic compression, mucosal irregularity, or frank invasion (T4a/T4b disease). This assessment is critical for determining resectability and guiding treatment decisions, as significant airway involvement often contraindicates surgical resection or necessitates complex multidisciplinary approaches like definitive chemoradiation.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Assess fitness for general anaesthesia is primarily evaluated by an anesthesiologist through patient history, physical exam, and cardiac/pulmonary function tests, not by bronchoscopy for cancer staging.\nOption B (Incorrect): Obtain specimen for culture and sensitivity is performed for suspected infections, not for the primary staging of esophageal carcinoma. While biopsies can be taken during bronchoscopy, their purpose in this context is to confirm invasion, not for culture.\nOption C (Incorrect): Detect lymph node metastasis is primarily achieved through imaging modalities like CT, PET-CT, and endoscopic ultrasound with fine-needle aspiration (EUS-FNA). Bronchoscopy can identify direct invasion of the airway by adjacent lymph nodes, but it is not the primary tool for detecting lymph node metastasis throughout the mediastinum.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Staging Modality | Primary Purpose | Key Findings in Esophageal Cancer |\n|---|---|---|\n| CT Chest/Abd/Pelvis | Distant metastasis, regional lymph nodes | Organ metastasis, nodal enlargement |\n| PET-CT | Distant metastasis, metabolically active lesions | Hypermetabolic foci, occult mets |\n| EUS with FNA | T and N staging, local invasion | Depth of invasion, periesophageal lymph nodes |\n| Bronchoscopy | Tracheobronchial invasion (T4a/T4b) | Mucosal irregularity, extrinsic compression, fistula |\n| Laparoscopy/Thoracoscopy | Peritoneal/pleural metastasis, resectability | Direct visualization of metastatic disease, ascites/effusion |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Bronchoscopy in esophageal cancer assesses airway invasion for resectability.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn bronchoscopy, look for loss of normal tracheal rings, mucosal edema, erythema, friability, or a mass protruding into the lumen. In the OR, direct tumor adherence or invasion into the trachea or main bronchus makes R0 resection difficult or impossible.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for Esophageal and Esophagogastric Junction Cancers (2024). Recommends bronchoscopy for tumors at or above the carina or with suspected airway involvement based on other imaging.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Assess fitness for general anaesthesia | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Obtain specimen for culture and sensitivity | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Detect lymph node metastasis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Look for tracheobronchial involvement | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: ?) Gas shadow under left dome of diaphragm** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Competency 2500**\n"
