  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When the scope causes the crisis, it's iatrogenic.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe verified answer, \"Iatrogenic,\" is correct because a perforation caused by a fiberoptic scope is, by definition, an adverse event resulting directly from a medical procedure. This term accurately describes any injury or illness induced by medical examination or treatment.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nIatrogenic injury refers to any complication or adverse effect that is a direct consequence of medical intervention. In the context of endoscopy, this includes perforations, bleeding, or infections that occur during or immediately after the procedure. Understanding this term is crucial for patient safety, risk assessment, and appropriate management of procedural complications, distinguishing them from spontaneous conditions or underlying disease processes. The mechanism involves direct mechanical trauma from the scope or instruments, often in areas of anatomical vulnerability or pre-existing pathology.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Boerhaave’s syndrome): Incorrect. Boerhaave's syndrome is a spontaneous esophageal rupture, typically due to forceful vomiting, not an iatrogenic cause.\nOption B (Regarding Tylosis the following are true except): Incorrect. This is an incomplete sentence and refers to a genetic condition (Tylosis), completely unrelated to the cause of a scope perforation.\nOption C (It is an autosomal dominant disease): Incorrect. This describes a genetic inheritance pattern, likely pertaining to Tylosis, and has no relevance to a scope-induced perforation.\nOption D (Associated with palmar and plantar hyperkeratosis): Incorrect. This is a clinical manifestation, likely of Tylosis, and is irrelevant to the etiology of a scope perforation.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Condition | Cause | Mechanism | Management |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Iatrogenic Perforation | Endoscopic procedure | Direct mechanical trauma by scope/instruments | Surgical repair, endoscopic closure, or conservative management depending on size/location |\n| Boerhaave's Syndrome | Forceful vomiting/retching | Sudden, severe increase in intraesophageal pressure | Urgent surgical repair, drainage, antibiotics |\n| Mallory-Weiss Tear | Forceful vomiting/retching | Longitudinal mucosal tear at gastroesophageal junction | Supportive care, endoscopic hemostasis if bleeding persists |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Any complication directly caused by a medical procedure is iatrogenic.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT scan, look for pneumomediastinum, pleural effusion, subcutaneous emphysema, or contrast extravasation on an esophagram. Intraoperatively, direct visualization of the defect and leakage of luminal contents confirms the diagnosis.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Society for Gastrointestinal Endoscopy (ASGE) Guidelines on Adverse Events of Endoscopy (2020). Recommends prompt recognition and appropriate management strategies for endoscopic complications, including perforation, to optimize patient outcomes.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Boerhaave’s syndrome | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Regarding Tylosis the following are true except | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | It is an autosomal dominant disease | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Associated with palmar and plantar hyperkeratosis | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: ?) Iatrogenic** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Competency 2500**\n"
