  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Ulcers: when acid wins, surgery might begin.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe provided answer, \"Peptic ulceration,\" refers to mucosal breaks in the gastrointestinal tract, typically in the stomach or duodenum, caused by acid and pepsin. This condition is a common cause of upper gastrointestinal bleeding and abdominal pain, often requiring medical or surgical management.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nPeptic ulcer disease arises from an imbalance between aggressive factors (acid, pepsin, H. pylori, NSAIDs) and protective factors (mucus, bicarbonate, prostaglandins, mucosal blood flow). Surgical intervention, though less common now, is reserved for complications like perforation, obstruction, or intractable bleeding. Understanding the pathophysiology of acid secretion and mucosal defense is crucial for both medical and surgical management.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Achalasia cardia) (Incorrect): Achalasia is an esophageal motility disorder characterized by impaired lower esophageal sphincter relaxation and absent peristalsis, unrelated to peptic ulceration.\nOption B (Mallory–Weis syndrome) (Incorrect): Mallory-Weiss syndrome involves longitudinal mucosal tears at the gastroesophageal junction, typically from forceful vomiting, distinct from peptic ulceration.\nOption C (Chronic alcoholism) (Incorrect): While chronic alcoholism can contribute to gastritis and GI bleeding, it is a broad condition and not directly synonymous with or the primary mechanism of peptic ulceration itself.\nOption D (Endoluminal ultrasound) (Incorrect): Endoluminal ultrasound is a diagnostic imaging modality used for staging GI cancers or evaluating submucosal lesions, not a disease entity like peptic ulceration.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Gastric Ulcer | Duodenal Ulcer | Stress Ulcer |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Location | Lesser curvature, antrum | Duodenal bulb (D1) | Fundus, body of stomach |\n| Pain | Worse with food | Better with food, worse at night | Often asymptomatic until complication |\n| Etiology | H. pylori, NSAIDs, bile reflux | H. pylori, NSAIDs | Severe physiological stress (sepsis, trauma, burns) |\n| Malignancy Risk | Higher (biopsy recommended) | Very low | None |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Perforated peptic ulcer requires emergent surgical repair.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn plain upright chest X-ray, free air under the diaphragm indicates a perforated viscus, often a perforated peptic ulcer. Intraoperatively, a Graham patch (omentum over the perforation) is a common repair.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Gastroenterology (ACG) Guideline for the Management of Peptic Ulcer Disease (2017). It recommends H. pylori eradication and NSAID cessation as primary treatments.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Achalasia cardia | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Mallory–Weis syndrome | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Chronic alcoholism | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Endoluminal ultrasound | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: ?) Peptic ulceration** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Competency 2500**\n"
