  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When in doubt, biopsy it out!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nAn endoscopic biopsy is the definitive method for diagnosing adenocarcinoma, as it provides tissue for histological examination. This allows for microscopic confirmation of malignant cells, which is crucial for accurate staging and treatment planning.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nEndoscopic biopsy involves direct visualization of suspicious lesions within the gastrointestinal tract, allowing for targeted tissue acquisition. This minimally invasive procedure provides crucial histological evidence, differentiating benign from malignant processes and characterizing tumor type, grade, and depth of invasion. The ability to obtain tissue samples is paramount for confirming adenocarcinoma and guiding subsequent oncologic management.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Cricopharyngeal myotomy is a surgical procedure to treat dysphagia, not a diagnostic finding from a biopsy.\nOption B (Incorrect): Primary peristalsis refers to normal esophageal motility, a physiological process, not a histological diagnosis.\nOption C (Incorrect): Corkscrew esophagus is a radiographic finding associated with diffuse esophageal spasm, a motility disorder, not a histological diagnosis.\nOption D (Incorrect): Monilial esophagitis is an inflammatory condition caused by Candida, which can be diagnosed by biopsy, but the verified answer specifically states 'Adenocarcinoma histologically'.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Condition | Primary Diagnostic Method | Key Finding |\n|---|---|---|\n| Esophageal Adenocarcinoma | Endoscopic Biopsy | Malignant glandular cells |\n| Diffuse Esophageal Spasm | Barium Swallow / Manometry | Corkscrew esophagus / Uncoordinated contractions |\n| Monilial Esophagitis | Endoscopy with Biopsy/Brushings | White plaques, fungal hyphae |\n| Achalasia | Manometry / Barium Swallow | Aperistalsis, impaired LES relaxation / Bird's beak |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Biopsy is king for definitive cancer diagnosis.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn endoscopy, adenocarcinoma often appears as an irregular, friable, nodular, or ulcerated mass, typically in the distal esophagus or GE junction. Biopsies are taken from these suspicious areas.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for Esophageal and Esophagogastric Junction Cancers (2024). Recommends endoscopic biopsy for definitive diagnosis and staging.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Cricopharyngeal myotomy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Primary peristalsis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Corkscrew esophagus | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Monilial esophagitis | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: ?) Adenocarcinoma histologically** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Competency 2500**\n"
