  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Pancreatic cancer with ascites: advanced, aggressive, ominous.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe verdict is ACCEPT. Pancreatic carcinoma can lead to ascites, particularly malignant ascites due to peritoneal dissemination or portal vein thrombosis. This finding typically indicates advanced, often unresectable, disease.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nMalignant ascites in pancreatic cancer primarily arises from peritoneal carcinomatosis, where cancer cells implant on the peritoneal surface, leading to increased capillary permeability and fluid accumulation. Other mechanisms include lymphatic obstruction by tumor cells or portal hypertension secondary to tumor invasion of the portal vein. The presence of ascites in pancreatic cancer is a significant prognostic indicator, often signaling widespread metastatic disease and a poor prognosis.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Cystic fibrosis): Incorrect. While cystic fibrosis is a known risk factor for pancreatic carcinoma, it is not a direct manifestation or complication of the carcinoma itself.\nOption B (What is the treatment of choice for annular pancreas?): Incorrect. This is a question about a completely different congenital anomaly, not a manifestation or treatment of pancreatic carcinoma.\nOption C (Resection of annular pancreas): Incorrect. This is a surgical treatment for annular pancreas, a condition unrelated to pancreatic carcinoma or its complications.\nOption D (Duodenoduodenostomy): Incorrect. This is a surgical procedure, often used for annular pancreas or duodenal obstruction, and is not a direct manifestation or treatment of pancreatic carcinoma.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Malignant Ascites (Pancreatic Cancer) | Cirrhotic Ascites | Cardiac Ascites |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Cause** | Peritoneal carcinomatosis, lymphatic obstruction, portal vein invasion | Portal hypertension due to liver cirrhosis | Right heart failure, systemic venous congestion |\n| **Fluid Analysis** | High protein (>2.5 g/dL), high LDH, positive cytology | Low SAAG (>1.1 g/dL), low protein | High protein, often transudative |\n| **Treatment** | Palliative chemotherapy, paracentesis, shunts | Diuretics, paracentesis, TIPS | Diuretics, heart failure management |\n| **Prognosis** | Poor, indicates advanced disease | Variable, depends on liver function | Variable, depends on heart function |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Malignant ascites in pancreatic cancer signals advanced, often unresectable disease.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT, malignant ascites appears as free fluid in the peritoneal cavity, often accompanied by peritoneal nodularity, omental caking, or liver metastases. Intraoperatively, diffuse peritoneal implants and a large volume of straw-colored or hemorrhagic fluid would be observed.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for Pancreatic Adenocarcinoma (2023). These guidelines address the diagnosis, staging, and management of pancreatic cancer, including palliative care for complications like ascites.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Cystic fibrosis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | What is the treatment of choice for annular pancreas? | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Resection of annular pancreas | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Duodenoduodenostomy | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: ?) Ascites** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Competency 2500**\n"
