  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't wash away your chances with outdated lavage.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe verdict, \"Continuous peritoneal lavage,\" refers to a historical or specific intervention involving washing the peritoneal cavity. While once considered for conditions like severe acute pancreatitis or peritonitis, its widespread use has largely been superseded by other treatments due to limited efficacy and potential complications.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe rationale behind continuous peritoneal lavage was to remove inflammatory mediators, toxins, and necrotic debris from the peritoneal cavity, theoretically reducing systemic inflammatory response syndrome (SIRS) and organ failure in conditions like severe acute pancreatitis or diffuse peritonitis. This mechanical washout aimed to break the cycle of inflammation, offering a potential benefit in critically ill patients.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): \"Enucleation of islet cell tumor\" is a surgical procedure for pancreatic neuroendocrine tumors and is unrelated to peritoneal lavage.\nOption B (Incorrect): \"All of the following changes are seen in acute pancreatitis\" is an incomplete statement and part of a different question stem.\nOption C (Incorrect): \"except\" is a conjunction and not a valid option.\nOption D (Incorrect): \"Raised serum amylase\" is a diagnostic marker for acute pancreatitis, not an intervention, and is unrelated to peritoneal lavage. The provided options are entirely disconnected from the verified answer.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Intervention | Primary Indication | Current Role | Key Consideration |\n| :----------- | :----------------- | :----------- | :----------------- |\n| **Continuous Peritoneal Lavage** | Severe acute pancreatitis, diffuse peritonitis (historical) | Limited, largely abandoned for routine use | Risk of infection, fluid/electrolyte imbalance, no proven mortality benefit |\n| **Percutaneous Drainage** | Infected pancreatic necrosis, intra-abdominal abscesses | First-line for localized collections | Minimally invasive, avoids open surgery |\n| **Open Necrosectomy** | Infected pancreatic necrosis unresponsive to drainage | Reserved for specific cases, often delayed | High morbidity/mortality, \"step-up\" approach preferred |\n| **Laparoscopic Lavage** | Perforated diverticulitis (selected cases) | Controversial, potential alternative to resection in specific scenarios | Avoids stoma, but risk of ongoing leak/abscess |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Peritoneal lavage: a historical concept, rarely a modern solution.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIntraoperatively, continuous peritoneal lavage involves placing multiple drains (e.g., Tenckhoff catheters) into the peritoneal cavity for inflow and outflow of dialysate fluid, often seen as clear or blood-tinged fluid returning. Imaging (CT) might show diffuse fluid collections and the presence of these catheters.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nThe 2012 Atlanta Classification and the 2019 American College of Gastroenterology (ACG) Guidelines for the Management of Acute Pancreatitis. These guidelines do not recommend routine continuous peritoneal lavage for acute pancreatitis due to lack of proven benefit and potential complications.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Enucleation of islet cell tumor | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | All of the following changes are seen in acute pancreatitis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | except | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Raised serum amylase | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: ?) Continuous peritoneal lavage** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Competency 2500**\n"
