  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Strep throat today, heart valve trouble tomorrow.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe verified answer, 'Which is the most common cardiac valve affected by rheumatic fever?', implicitly points to the mitral valve as the primary target. This is a fundamental concept in understanding the long-term sequelae of Group A Streptococcus infections.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nRheumatic fever is an autoimmune inflammatory response to Group A Streptococcus pharyngitis, primarily affecting the heart, joints, brain, and skin. The mitral valve is most commonly affected due to its unique anatomical and hemodynamic stresses, leading to inflammation, scarring, and subsequent valvular dysfunction (stenosis or regurgitation), a condition known as rheumatic heart disease. This understanding is crucial for prevention and management.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): 'Can be very painful' - This statement is too general and unrelated to the specific cardiac pathology of rheumatic fever.\nOption B (Incorrect): 'Can become malignant' - Rheumatic heart disease does not lead to malignancy; it causes structural damage to the heart valves.\nOption C (Incorrect): 'What is the most dangerous space infection in the hand?' - This is a question, not an answer, and is entirely unrelated to cardiac pathology or rheumatic fever.\nOption D (Incorrect): 'Mid palmar space infection' - This is a hand infection and bears no relevance to cardiac valves or rheumatic fever.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Rheumatic Fever | Infective Endocarditis | Aortic Stenosis |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Etiology | Group A Strep | Bacterial/Fungal | Calcific degeneration |\n| Valve Most Affected | Mitral | Mitral (IVDU: Tricuspid) | Aortic |\n| Pathophysiology | Autoimmune inflammation | Microbial colonization | Progressive calcification |\n| Key Complication | Rheumatic Heart Disease | Embolism, valve destruction | Heart failure, syncope |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Mitral valve is the MVP of rheumatic heart disease.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nEchocardiography would reveal thickened, calcified mitral valve leaflets with restricted motion (stenosis) or prolapse/incomplete coaptation (regurgitation), often with commissural fusion.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Heart Association (AHA) 2015 Guidelines for the Diagnosis and Management of Rheumatic Fever. They emphasize prompt diagnosis and antibiotic treatment of streptococcal pharyngitis to prevent rheumatic fever and its cardiac complications.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Can be very painful | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Can become malignant | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | What is the most dangerous space infection in the hand? | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Mid palmar space infection | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: ?) Which is the most common cardiac valve affected by rheumatic fever?** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Competency 2500**\n"
