  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Listen closely, a murmur's tale can save a life.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is 'Systolic murmur'. This finding is a critical auscultatory sign in cardiac examination, indicating turbulent blood flow during ventricular systole, often due to valvular dysfunction or structural heart disease.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nA systolic murmur arises from conditions such as aortic stenosis, mitral regurgitation, or ventricular septal defects. During systole, the ventricles contract; if the aortic valve is narrowed, blood flow is obstructed, creating a harsh ejection murmur. Conversely, if the mitral valve fails to close completely, blood regurgitates into the left atrium, producing a holosystolic murmur. Understanding the timing, location, radiation, and quality of these murmurs is fundamental for accurate diagnosis and guiding appropriate surgical or interventional management.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): This option presents a question about surgical history, not a clinical finding related to cardiac auscultation.\nOption B (Incorrect): Walter Lillehei was a pioneering cardiac surgeon, not an auscultatory finding or a type of heart sound.\nOption C (Incorrect): Denton Cooley was a renowned cardiac surgeon, not a clinical sign like a murmur.\nOption D (Incorrect): Michael DeBakey was a legendary cardiovascular surgeon, not a term describing a heart sound.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Murmur Type | Timing | Common Causes | Surgical Relevance |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Aortic Stenosis | Ejection Systolic | Calcific degeneration, congenital bicuspid valve | Aortic valve replacement (SAVR/TAVR) |\n| Mitral Regurgitation | Holosystolic | Myxomatous degeneration, ischemic heart disease | Mitral valve repair/replacement |\n| Ventricular Septal Defect | Holosystolic | Congenital defect | VSD patch closure |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Systolic murmurs demand investigation; timing and location guide diagnosis.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nEchocardiography is the primary imaging modality, revealing valvular morphology, chamber dimensions, and flow dynamics. Intraoperatively, direct visualization confirms valvular pathology and guides repair or replacement.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\n2020 ACC/AHA Guideline for the Management of Patients With Valvular Heart Disease: Recommends echocardiography for initial murmur evaluation and defines indications for surgical intervention based on severity and symptoms.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Who was the first surgeon to develop a heart lung machine for open heart su | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Walter Lillehei | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Denton Cooley | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Michael DeBakey | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: ?) Systolic murmur** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Competency 2500**\n"
