  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't forget the belly button; it can hide a stone!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe verified answer correctly identifies the primary composition of an umbolith. An umbolith, also known as an omphalith, is a concretion found within the umbilicus, often presenting as a hard, dark mass.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nUmboliths form due to the accumulation of desquamated keratinocytes, sebum, and other cellular debris within the deep folds of the umbilicus. Over time, this material can inspissate (thicken and harden) and calcify, leading to the formation of a stone-like structure. This process is exacerbated by poor hygiene, deep umbilical folds, and obesity, which can hinder proper cleaning and promote debris retention.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Ovary and uterus are female reproductive organs and have no direct relation to the formation or composition of an umbolith.\nOption B (Incorrect): \"What is an umbolith?\" is a question, not an answer describing its composition or nature.\nOption C (Incorrect): Calcification in the umbilicus describes the *appearance* and *location* of an umbolith, but not its fundamental *composition* of inspissated desquamated epithelium. While umboliths often calcify, their primary building blocks are cellular debris.\nOption D (Incorrect): A gallstone is a concretion formed in the gallbladder, primarily composed of cholesterol or bilirubin. It is distinct in origin and composition from an umbolith and does not present at the umbilicus unless there is a rare fistula, which is not the definition of an umbolith.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Umbolith (Omphalith) | Gallstone (Cholelith) | Renal Stone (Nephrolith) |\n| :--------------- | :----------------------------------- | :----------------------------------- | :----------------------------------- |\n| **Location** | Umbilicus | Gallbladder/Bile Ducts | Kidney/Urinary Tract |\n| **Composition** | Inspissated desquamated epithelium, sebum, keratin, calcified | Cholesterol, bilirubin, calcium salts | Calcium oxalate, calcium phosphate, uric acid, struvite, cystine |\n| **Etiology** | Poor hygiene, deep umbilical folds, debris accumulation | Bile supersaturation, stasis, dysmotility | Metabolic disorders, dehydration, infection, anatomical abnormalities |\n| **Clinical Pres.** | Umbilical mass, discharge, infection, pain | Biliary colic, cholecystitis, jaundice, pancreatitis | Flank pain, hematuria, infection, obstruction |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Umbolith = umbilical stone of skin debris.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT, an umbolith appears as a dense, calcified or semi-calcified mass within the umbilical canal, often surrounded by inflammatory changes if infected. Intraoperatively, it is a hard, dark, often foul-smelling concretion within the umbilical pit.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNo specific surgical society guideline exists solely for umboliths. Management typically follows general surgical principles for skin and soft tissue lesions, as outlined in standard surgical textbooks or general recommendations from organizations like the American College of Surgeons (ACS) for wound care and infection control.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Ovary and uterus | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | What is an umbolith? | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Calcification in the umbilicus | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Gallstone presenting at the umbilicus | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: ?) Inspissated desquamated epithelium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Competency 2500**\n"
