  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Meckel's: Bleed, obstruct, inflame, but rarely malign.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe verdict is that malignant change is *not* a common complication of Meckel's diverticulum, unlike intussusception, volvulus, or peptic ulceration. Meckel's diverticulum is a true diverticulum, a remnant of the omphalomesenteric duct, and while it can contain ectopic gastric or pancreatic tissue, malignant transformation is exceedingly rare.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nMeckel's diverticulum is the most common congenital anomaly of the gastrointestinal tract, occurring in approximately 2% of the population. Its complications arise primarily from the presence of ectopic gastric mucosa (leading to peptic ulceration, bleeding, or perforation) or its anatomical structure (acting as a lead point for intussusception, causing volvulus around its mesentery, or leading to obstruction). While carcinoid tumors have been reported in Meckel's diverticulum, primary adenocarcinoma or other common GI malignancies are exceptionally rare, making malignant change an unlikely complication compared to the others.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Intussusception) (Incorrect as the answer, but a true complication): Intussusception is a common complication where the diverticulum acts as a lead point for telescoping of the bowel.\nOption B (Intestinal volvulus) (Incorrect as the answer, but a true complication): Volvulus can occur around the fibrous band connecting the diverticulum to the umbilicus or its own mesentery, leading to bowel obstruction.\nOption C (Peptic ulceration) (Incorrect as the answer, but a true complication): Ectopic gastric mucosa within the diverticulum can secrete acid, causing ulceration, bleeding, or perforation in the adjacent ileum or within the diverticulum itself.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Complication Type | Mechanism | Clinical Presentation | Management |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Bleeding** | Ectopic gastric mucosa with acid secretion causing ulceration | Painless rectal bleeding (melena or hematochezia), anemia | Resection of diverticulum, sometimes adjacent ileum |\n| **Obstruction** | Intussusception (diverticulum as lead point), volvulus, incarceration in hernia | Abdominal pain, vomiting, distension, obstipation | Surgical reduction or resection |\n| **Diverticulitis** | Inflammation of the diverticulum, similar to appendicitis | Right lower quadrant pain, fever, leukocytosis | Surgical resection |\n| **Malignancy** | Extremely rare (e.g., carcinoid, adenocarcinoma) | Variable, often incidental finding or late-stage symptoms | Surgical resection, oncologic management |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Meckel's complications are the 2s: 2% prevalence, 2 feet from ileocecal valve, 2 inches long, 2 types of ectopic tissue, symptomatic by age 2.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn Technetium-99m pertechnetate scan (Meckel's scan), ectopic gastric mucosa in the diverticulum will show increased uptake. Intraoperatively, a Meckel's diverticulum appears as an outpouching on the antimesenteric border of the ileum, typically 10-100 cm proximal to the ileocecal valve. It may have a mesentery or a fibrous cord extending to the umbilicus.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nThere are no specific society guidelines solely dedicated to Meckel's diverticulum management. General surgical principles apply, often guided by consensus from pediatric surgical societies like the American Pediatric Surgical Association (APSA).\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Associated with diverticulosis of colon | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Complications of Meckel’s diverticulum include all of the following except | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Intussusception\tB. Intestinal volvulus | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | C. Peptic ulceration\tD. Malignant change | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: ?) D) Malignant change** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Competency 2500**\n"
