  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Cut with the grain, not against it, for a strong abdominal wall.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe question asks for the statement that is *false* regarding burst abdomen (fascial dehiscence). The correct answer, C, states that burst abdomen is more common in transverse muscle-cutting incisions. This statement is incorrect because transverse incisions are generally associated with a *lower* risk of dehiscence compared to vertical incisions.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nBurst abdomen, or fascial dehiscence, is a serious complication where the abdominal fascial layers separate. The biomechanics of wound healing and abdominal wall tension are critical. Vertical incisions, particularly midline laparotomies, cut across the natural collagen fibers and muscle pull of the abdominal wall, leading to higher tension on the suture line. This increased tension, especially with post-operative straining, significantly elevates the risk of dehiscence. In contrast, transverse incisions, when properly placed, tend to follow Langer's lines and the direction of muscle fibers, distributing tension more evenly and resulting in a stronger, more stable closure with a lower incidence of burst abdomen.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Vertical incisions are more prone. This statement is TRUE. Midline vertical incisions are biomechanically weaker and experience greater tension, making them more susceptible to dehiscence.\nOption B (Incorrect): Coughing, vomiting and distension after surgery are predisposing. This statement is TRUE. These actions acutely increase intra-abdominal pressure, placing excessive strain on the healing fascial closure and increasing the risk of dehiscence.\nOption D (Incorrect): Hypoproteinemia and malignant disease are some of the factors. This statement is TRUE. Hypoproteinemia impairs collagen synthesis and wound healing, while malignant disease often indicates a catabolic state, malnutrition, and impaired immune function, all of which compromise wound integrity.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Vertical Incision (e.g., Midline) | Transverse Incision (e.g., Pfannenstiel, Subcostal) |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Burst Abdomen Risk** | Higher | Lower |\n| **Wound Strength** | Weaker due to cutting across collagen fibers | Stronger, follows Langer's lines and muscle fibers |\n| **Cosmesis** | Often less aesthetic, prone to wider scars | Generally more aesthetic, scars hidden or follow natural creases |\n| **Exposure** | Excellent for general abdominal cavity | Good for specific regions, can be extended |\n| **Pain** | Often higher post-op pain | Generally lower post-op pain |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Vertical incisions = higher tension = higher dehiscence risk.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIntraoperatively, a burst abdomen presents as visible separation of the fascial layers, often with protrusion of intra-abdominal contents (evisceration) through the wound. On physical exam, a 'gush' of serosanguinous fluid from the wound may precede overt dehiscence.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Surgeons (ACS) Strong for Surgeons Guidelines (ongoing updates): Recommends careful attention to suture technique (e.g., small bites, short stitch length, continuous closure) and appropriate suture material to minimize dehiscence risk, especially in high-risk patients and vertical incisions.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Vertical incisions are more prone | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Coughing, vomiting and distension after surgery are predisposing | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | More common in transverse muscle cutting incisions | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Hypoproteinemia and malignant disease are some of the factors | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: ?) C) More common in transverse muscle cutting incisions** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Competency 2500**\n"
