  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't let a sudden infraumbilical bulge bleed your diagnosis dry!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe verified answer, \"Rupture of inferior epigastric artery,\" is correct. A sudden, painful swelling below the umbilicus in a pregnant woman strongly suggests a rectus sheath hematoma, most commonly caused by a rupture of the inferior epigastric artery due to increased intra-abdominal pressure and vascular fragility during pregnancy.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe inferior epigastric artery runs within the rectus sheath. During pregnancy, increased intra-abdominal pressure from uterine growth, coughing, or straining, combined with increased vascularity and potential vessel fragility, can lead to shearing forces on these vessels. A rupture results in a rectus sheath hematoma, presenting as a sudden, often painful, and expanding mass below the umbilicus. This acute onset and localized swelling are classic for a vascular event rather than a gradual process or a different anatomical pathology.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Twisted ovarian cyst) (Incorrect): While possible in pregnancy, a twisted ovarian cyst typically presents with acute, severe, colicky pelvic pain, often with nausea/vomiting, and is usually not described as a sudden, localized infraumbilical swelling.\nOption B (Appendicular mass) (Incorrect): An appendicular mass results from complicated appendicitis, usually presenting with right lower quadrant pain, fever, and inflammatory signs, with a more gradual onset than a sudden swelling below the umbilicus.\nOption C (Spigelian hernia) (Incorrect): A Spigelian hernia is a protrusion through the Spigelian fascia, usually lateral to the rectus muscle. While it can present as a swelling, the \"suddenly\" and the context of pregnancy making vessels fragile points more towards a bleeding event (hematoma) rather than a primary hernia presentation.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Condition | Key Presentation | Diagnostic Clue | Management |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Rectus Sheath Hematoma | Sudden, painful, non-reducible infraumbilical mass; often ecchymosis | History of anticoagulation, trauma, coughing, pregnancy; US/CT shows hematoma | Conservative (most); embolization/surgery for active bleed/expansion |\n| Spigelian Hernia | Intermittent or constant infraumbilical/lateral abdominal bulge; often reducible | Palpable defect lateral to rectus; US/CT shows bowel/omentum in defect | Surgical repair |\n| Twisted Ovarian Cyst | Acute, severe, colicky pelvic pain; nausea/vomiting, often unilateral | US shows enlarged, edematous ovary with absent Doppler flow | Surgical detorsion/oophorectomy |\n| Appendicitis (in pregnancy) | Periumbilical pain migrating to RLQ; fever, anorexia, guarding (may be atypical) | Graded compression US or MRI is preferred; elevated WBC | Appendectomy (often laparoscopic) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Sudden infraumbilical mass + pregnancy = think rectus sheath hematoma.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound or CT, a rectus sheath hematoma appears as a well-defined, often crescent-shaped, hypoechoic (US) or hyperdense (CT) collection within the rectus sheath, displacing the rectus muscle. Active extravasation may be seen on CT angiography. Intraoperatively, a large hematoma within the rectus sheath with active bleeding from the inferior epigastric artery or its branches would be found.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nACOG Practice Bulletin No. 197: Abdominal Pain in Pregnancy (2018) recommends appropriate imaging (ultrasound, MRI, or CT with shielding) for diagnosis of acute abdominal pain in pregnancy, which would include evaluation for rectus sheath hematoma.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Twisted ovarian cyst | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Appendicular mass | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Spigelian hernia | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Rupture of inferior epigastric artery | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: ?) Rupture of inferior artery** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Competency 2500**\n"
