  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Desmoid tumors: They're aggressive neighbors, not world travelers.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe verified answer correctly identifies that desmoid tumors, despite their aggressive local nature, do not metastasize to distant organs. This key characteristic distinguishes them from true sarcomas and other malignant soft tissue tumors.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nDesmoid tumors, also known as aggressive fibromatosis, are benign mesenchymal neoplasms originating from fibroblasts. While they exhibit infiltrative growth and a high propensity for local recurrence, their defining characteristic is the absence of metastatic potential. Histologically, they lack the cellular atypia and mitotic activity typically seen in malignant tumors, despite their aggressive clinical behavior. Their local invasiveness can lead to significant morbidity, but they are not a cause of death through distant spread.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Desmoid tumors show a female predominance, particularly in women of reproductive age, often associated with pregnancy or estrogen exposure.\nOption B (Incorrect): Desmoid tumors frequently arise in areas of trauma or surgical scars, especially in the abdominal wall following surgery or childbirth.\nOption D (Incorrect): Abdominal wall desmoids are common, and the rectus abdominis muscle, often below the umbilicus, is a frequent site, particularly in multiparous women.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Desmoid Tumor | Soft Tissue Sarcoma |\n|---|---|---|\n| Malignant Potential | Locally aggressive, non-metastatic | Malignant, metastatic |\n| Histology | Benign-appearing fibroblasts | Atypical/malignant cells |\n| Treatment | Surgery, systemic therapy (NSAIDs, anti-estrogens, chemotherapy) | Surgery, radiation, chemotherapy |\n| Prognosis | Recurrence common, but not fatal from metastasis | Can be fatal due to metastasis |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Desmoid tumors are locally aggressive, but never metastasize.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn MRI, desmoid tumors typically appear as infiltrative masses, often T1 isointense to muscle and T2 variable (hypo- to hyperintense) with heterogeneous enhancement. Intraoperatively, they are firm, poorly circumscribed, and can infiltrate surrounding muscle and fascia.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for Soft Tissue Sarcoma (2023): Recommends a multidisciplinary approach for desmoid tumors, including observation, surgery, radiation, and systemic therapies.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Most cases occurs in women | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Can occur in old abdominal operative scars | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Spreads to distant organs as metastasis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Most common site is below the umbilicus | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: ?) C) Spreads to distant organs as metastasis** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Competency 2500**\n"
