  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Femoral hernias: Female, Fatal, Below the ligament.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe verified answer correctly states that femoral hernias are more common in females than males. This predilection is primarily due to anatomical differences in the female pelvis, which is generally wider and shallower, leading to a relatively larger femoral canal.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe femoral canal is a potential space within the femoral sheath, medial to the femoral vein, through which a femoral hernia protrudes. Its boundaries are the inguinal ligament superiorly, the pectineal ligament (Cooper's ligament) posteriorly, the lacunar ligament (Gimbernat's ligament) medially, and the femoral vein laterally. The wider female pelvis creates a broader femoral ring, increasing the likelihood of abdominal contents herniating through this defect. This anatomical predisposition, combined with factors like increased intra-abdominal pressure (e.g., pregnancy), contributes to the higher incidence in women.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): The most common hernia in females is the inguinal hernia, not the femoral hernia.\nOption B (Incorrect): The most common hernia in males is the inguinal hernia.\nOption D (Incorrect): This statement is factually incorrect; femoral hernias are more common in females than males.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Hernia Type | Sex Predilection | Key Feature |\n|---|---|---|\n| Inguinal | Males > Females | Most common overall, above inguinal ligament |\n| Femoral | Females > Males | High risk of strangulation, below inguinal ligament |\n| Umbilical | Infants (often resolve), Adults (obesity, pregnancy) | Through umbilical ring |\n| Incisional | Equal | Occurs at previous surgical site |\n| Spigelian | Equal | Through linea semilunaris, often difficult to diagnose |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Femoral hernias: Female, Fatal (high strangulation risk), Below inguinal ligament.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT or ultrasound, a femoral hernia appears as a sac inferior to the inguinal ligament and medial to the femoral vein. Intraoperatively, the hernia sac is identified emerging through the femoral canal, often requiring careful dissection due to its proximity to the femoral vein and high risk of incarceration/strangulation.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nThe European Hernia Society (EHS) Guidelines for Treatment of Inguinal Hernia in Adults (2023) recommend surgical repair for all diagnosed femoral hernias due to their high risk of strangulation, often favoring mesh repair.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Most common hernia in females | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Most common hernia in males | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | More common in females than males | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | More common in males than females | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: ?) C) More common in females than males** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Competency 2500**\n"
