  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Gut pain after eating? Think clogged pipes, not just indigestion.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nMesenteric vascular obstruction is the correct answer. Abdominal angina is a classic symptom of chronic mesenteric ischemia, which occurs when blood flow to the intestines is insufficient to meet metabolic demands, particularly after a meal.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nAbdominal angina, also known as intestinal angina, is characterized by post-prandial abdominal pain due to ischemia of the bowel. This occurs because digestion requires a significant increase in mesenteric blood flow (post-prandial hyperemia). If the mesenteric arteries are significantly obstructed, typically by atherosclerosis, they cannot adequately supply this increased demand, leading to ischemic pain. The superior mesenteric artery (SMA) is most commonly involved, and symptoms often include a 'fear of food' and subsequent weight loss.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Malignant stricture): Incorrect. A malignant stricture causes mechanical obstruction and pain, but not ischemic pain (angina) due to vascular insufficiency.\nOption B (Benign stricture): Incorrect. Similar to malignant strictures, benign strictures cause mechanical obstruction and pain, not ischemic pain from compromised blood supply.\nOption D (Faecal impaction): Incorrect. Faecal impaction causes constipation, abdominal discomfort, and potential mechanical obstruction, but does not lead to ischemic abdominal angina.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Condition | Cause | Key Symptom | Urgency |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Abdominal Angina (Chronic Mesenteric Ischemia) | Atherosclerotic occlusion of ≥2 mesenteric arteries | Post-prandial abdominal pain, 'fear of food,' weight loss | Elective/Urgent |\n| Acute Mesenteric Ischemia | Embolism, thrombosis, non-occlusive mesenteric ischemia | Severe abdominal pain out of proportion to exam, bloody stools | Emergency |\n| Intestinal Obstruction (e.g., stricture) | Mechanical blockage (tumor, adhesions, stricture) | Colicky abdominal pain, distension, vomiting, obstipation | Urgent/Emergency |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Post-prandial pain + weight loss = mesenteric ischemia until proven otherwise.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nCT angiography (CTA) is the gold standard, revealing significant stenosis or occlusion of the celiac, SMA, or IMA. Intraoperatively, one might observe pale, non-viable bowel or palpable atherosclerotic plaques in mesenteric vessels.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nSociety for Vascular Surgery (SVS) Clinical Practice Guidelines for the Management of Chronic Mesenteric Ischemia (2021): Recommends revascularization for symptomatic chronic mesenteric ischemia.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Malignant stricture | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Benign stricture | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Mesentric vascular obstruction | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Faecal impaction | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: ?) Mesenteric vascular obstruction** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Competency 2500**\n"
