  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 A rogue gallstone can cause a rare, but memorable, obstruction!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is B) Gallstone ileus. This condition represents a rare cause of mechanical small bowel obstruction, occurring when a large gallstone erodes through a cholecystoenteric fistula and becomes impacted in the intestinal lumen.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nGallstone ileus is a fascinating pathology involving a sequence of events: chronic cholecystitis leads to inflammation, fistula formation (most commonly cholecystoduodenal), and subsequent migration of a large gallstone into the small bowel. The stone typically obstructs at the terminal ileum, the narrowest part of the small intestine, leading to classic signs of mechanical obstruction. Its rarity stems from the specific conditions required for fistula formation and stone migration.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Adhesive obstruction is the most common cause of small bowel obstruction, accounting for 60-80% of cases, especially in patients with prior abdominal surgery.\nOption C (Incorrect): Benign strictures, often due to Crohn's disease, radiation enteritis, or NSAID use, are a significant but less common cause of obstruction than adhesions, yet still more frequent than gallstone ileus.\nOption D (Incorrect): Malignant strictures, arising from primary bowel cancers or metastatic disease, are a common cause of obstruction, particularly in older populations, making them far more prevalent than gallstone ileus.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Cause of SBO | Relative Frequency | Key Features |\n| :----------- | :----------------- | :----------- |\n| Adhesive Obstruction | Most Common (60-80%) | History of abdominal surgery, often partial or complete obstruction. |\n| Malignant Stricture | Common (10-20%) | Progressive symptoms, weight loss, often in older patients, primary or metastatic cancer. |\n| Benign Stricture | Less Common (5-10%) | History of Crohn's, radiation, ischemia, NSAID use; chronic or acute obstruction. |\n| Gallstone Ileus | Rarest (<1%) | Elderly patient, pneumobilia, ectopic gallstone, cholecystoenteric fistula. |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Gallstone ileus is rare, but consider Rigler's triad in elderly SBO.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT scan, look for Rigler's triad: pneumobilia (air in the biliary tree), ectopic gallstone (often in the ileum), and small bowel obstruction. Intraoperatively, a dilated small bowel proximal to an impacted gallstone will be found, often with evidence of a cholecystoenteric fistula.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nWorld Society of Emergency Surgery (WSES) guidelines for the management of small bowel obstruction (2017). These guidelines recommend early diagnosis, conservative management for uncomplicated cases, and surgical intervention for complicated SBO or specific etiologies like gallstone ileus.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Adhesive obstruction | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Gallstone ileus | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Benign stricture | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Malignant stricture | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: ?) B) Gallstone ileus** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Competency 2500**\n"
