  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When bowel looks bad, it usually is.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe verdict is ACCEPT. The correct answer, \"Pressure rings persists,\" is indeed the feature that indicates non-viable bowel, making it the correct \"except\" feature in the question. Persistent pressure rings signify ischemic damage and edema, preventing the bowel from returning to its normal contour.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nViable bowel possesses several key characteristics reflecting adequate blood supply and functional integrity. These include a healthy pink color, visible arterial pulsations in the mesentery, active peristalsis, and a shiny, glistening serosal surface. The ability of bowel to \"bounce back\" and lose any temporary indentations (like pressure rings from handling) is a sign of good tissue turgor and perfusion. When bowel is ischemic, it loses its elasticity, becomes edematous, and these pressure marks persist, indicating irreversible damage.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Presence of arterial pulsation in the mesentery is a direct sign of adequate blood flow, which is essential for bowel viability.\nOption C (Incorrect): Peristalsis indicates functional smooth muscle activity, a hallmark of healthy, viable bowel.\nOption D (Incorrect): A shiny serosa surface reflects good hydration and perfusion of the bowel wall, indicating viability. A dull, edematous, or discolored serosa suggests ischemia.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Viable Bowel | Non-Viable Bowel |\n|---|---|---|\n| Color | Pink/Red | Dusky, Gray, Black |\n| Peristalsis | Present | Absent |\n| Mesenteric Pulsations | Present | Absent |\n| Serosa | Shiny, Glistening | Dull, Edematous |\n| Bleeding from cut edge | Present | Absent |\n| Pressure Rings | Disappear | Persist |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: When in doubt, resect. Better safe than sorry with bowel viability.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIntraoperatively, non-viable bowel appears dusky, gray, or black, lacks peristalsis, has no palpable mesenteric pulsations, and its serosa is dull and edematous. Pressure marks from instruments will persist. On CT, signs of bowel ischemia include bowel wall thickening, pneumatosis intestinalis, portomesenteric venous gas, and lack of mural enhancement.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nWorld Society of Emergency Surgery (WSES) guidelines for the management of acute mesenteric ischemia in adults (2017). These guidelines emphasize the importance of intraoperative assessment of bowel viability, recommending resection of clearly necrotic segments and second-look laparotomy for equivocal cases.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | except | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Presence of arterial pulsation in the mesentery | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Presence of peristalsis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Shiny serosa surface | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: ?) Pressure rings persists** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Competency 2500**\n"
