  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Hyaluronidase: Not your adhesion prevention hero.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe verified answer, \"Hyaluronidase installation in the peritoneal cavity,\" is correct because it is NOT a recognized or effective method for preventing recurrent intestinal obstruction due to adhesions. Adhesions are fibrous bands that form after peritoneal injury, and their prevention relies on minimizing trauma, using barrier agents, or specific surgical techniques, not enzymatic degradation of hyaluronic acid.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nAdhesions result from an inflammatory process involving fibrin deposition and subsequent fibroblast proliferation, leading to fibrous band formation. While hyaluronic acid is a component of the extracellular matrix, direct installation of hyaluronidase into the peritoneal cavity is not an evidence-based strategy for adhesion prevention. In fact, it could potentially increase peritoneal permeability, promote bleeding, or exacerbate inflammation, thereby hindering rather than helping adhesion prevention. Effective strategies focus on reducing initial injury, separating injured surfaces, or modifying the healing process with physical barriers.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Repeat adhesiolysis) (Incorrect): Repeat adhesiolysis is a direct surgical treatment for recurrent adhesive small bowel obstruction (ASBO), aiming to free the obstructed bowel. It is a helpful procedure, though it carries its own risk of recurrence.\nOption C (Noble’s placation operation) (Incorrect): Noble's placation is a surgical procedure designed to prevent recurrent ASBO by suturing adjacent loops of small bowel together in a fixed, orderly fashion, thereby reducing the risk of kinking and volvulus.\nOption D (Insertion of Baker’s tube) (Incorrect): A Baker tube (long intestinal tube) can be inserted post-operatively to stent the small bowel, preventing kinking and reducing the risk of early recurrent obstruction, especially after extensive adhesiolysis.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Method | Description | Efficacy/Role |\n|---|---|---|\n| Adhesiolysis | Surgical division of fibrous bands causing obstruction | Primary treatment for ASBO; high recurrence risk |\n| Noble's Placation | Surgical plication of small bowel loops | Prevents kinking/volvulus, reduces recurrence |\n| Long Intestinal Tubes (e.g., Baker tube) | Stenting of bowel lumen post-op | Prevents early kinking/obstruction |\n| Hyaluronidase | Enzyme breaking down hyaluronic acid | No established role in adhesion prevention; not recommended |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Adhesion prevention focuses on barrier methods, not enzymatic degradation.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIntraoperatively, extensive adhesions appear as dense, avascular fibrous bands tethering bowel loops together, often causing angulation or kinking. During adhesiolysis, careful sharp and blunt dissection is crucial to free the bowel while minimizing serosal injury. On CT, ASBO typically shows dilated small bowel loops proximal to a transition point, often with collapsed distal bowel, without a clear mass or hernia.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nWorld Society of Emergency Surgery (WSES) guidelines for the management of adhesive small bowel obstruction (2017). These guidelines discuss surgical and non-surgical management of ASBO, including indications for adhesiolysis and strategies to prevent recurrence, but do not endorse hyaluronidase.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Recurrant intestinal obstruction due to adhesions, the following procedure  | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Repeat adhesiolysis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Noble’s placation operation | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Insertion of Baker’s tube | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: ?) Hyaluronidase installation in the peritoneal cavity** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Competency 2500**\n"
