  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When the colon looks like an apple core, cancer's at its core!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe verdict is ACCEPT. 'Apple-core appearance' is the classic radiographic sign of a constricting annular lesion, most commonly seen in colorectal carcinoma, due to circumferential tumor growth. This finding is critical for early diagnosis and intervention.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThis characteristic finding, also known as the 'napkin-ring sign,' is typically observed on barium enema studies or cross-sectional imaging like CT. The tumor infiltrates the bowel wall, causing a sharp, shelf-like constriction with overhanging edges and a narrow, irregular lumen. This appearance is highly suggestive of malignancy, prompting further investigation like colonoscopy and biopsy. Recognizing this distinct imaging pattern is crucial for surgical planning and improving patient outcomes in colorectal cancer.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption 'Soap bubble appearance' (Incorrect): This sign is typically associated with mucinous tumors (e.g., pseudomyxoma peritonei, mucinous ovarian carcinomas) or meconium ileus, representing mucin or gas-filled cysts, not a constricting bowel lesion. The provided options A, B, C, D are unrelated to the verified answer and are therefore not addressed.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Imaging Sign | Associated Condition | Description | Modality |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Apple-core sign | Colorectal Carcinoma | Annular constricting lesion with abrupt, shelf-like margins | Barium Enema, CT |\n| Soap bubble sign | Mucinous tumors, Meconium ileus | Multiple small, lucent areas within a mass or bowel lumen | CT, X-ray |\n| Target sign | Intussusception | Concentric rings of bowel within bowel | Ultrasound, CT |\n| Coffee bean sign | Sigmoid Volvulus | Dilated, inverted U-shaped loop of colon | X-ray |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Apple-core = colon cancer; Soap bubble = mucin/meconium. Don't confuse them!\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT, the apple-core sign manifests as circumferential wall thickening with luminal narrowing. Intraoperatively, a hard, fixed, annular mass would be palpable, often with proximal bowel dilation and distal collapse.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Cancer Society (ACS) 2023 Guidelines for Colorectal Cancer Screening: Recommends regular screening starting at age 45, emphasizing early detection of lesions that could manifest as an apple-core sign.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | The following are the potential sites for internal herniation | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | except | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Intersigmoid fossa | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Diaphragmatic hernia | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: ?) Apple-core appearance** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Competency 2500**\n"
