  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Clinical signs still matter, even with imaging.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nCope's method refers to a collection of clinical signs used historically and still relevant in the physical examination for diagnosing acute appendicitis. These signs help localize inflammation to the appendix and differentiate it from other abdominal pathologies.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nCope's method encompasses several key clinical maneuvers: the Psoas sign (pain on passive extension of the right hip, indicating irritation of the psoas muscle by a retrocecal appendix), the Obturator sign (pain on internal rotation of the flexed right hip, suggesting irritation of the obturator internus muscle by a pelvic appendix), and Rovsing's sign (palpation of the left lower quadrant causes pain in the right lower quadrant, due to referred pain from peritoneal irritation). These signs, when positive, increase the clinical suspicion for appendicitis, guiding further diagnostic steps or surgical intervention.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (C. Extramural causes D. Low residue diet): Incorrect. These options describe causes of intestinal issues or dietary factors, not diagnostic methods for appendicitis. \nOption B (A large number of gas-fluid levels on a plain X-ray abdomen is suggestive of): Incorrect. This describes a radiographic finding typically associated with intestinal obstruction, not a diagnostic method for appendicitis. \nOption C (High intestinal obstruction): Incorrect. This is a diagnosis, not a diagnostic method, and is unrelated to Cope's method. \nOption D (Low intestinal obstruction): Incorrect. Similar to C, this is a diagnosis and unrelated to Cope's method. The provided options are not relevant to the verified answer 'Cope's method'.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Sign | Description | Clinical Significance |\n|---|---|---|\n| Rovsing's Sign | Palpation of LLQ causes pain in RLQ | Suggests peritoneal irritation from appendicitis |\n| Psoas Sign | Pain on extension of right hip | Suggests retrocecal appendix irritating psoas muscle |\n| Obturator Sign | Pain on internal rotation of flexed right hip | Suggests pelvic appendix irritating obturator internus muscle |\n| McBurney's Point Tenderness | Tenderness at 1/3 distance from ASIS to umbilicus | Classic sign of appendicitis |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Cope's method: Psoas, Obturator, Rovsing signs for appendicitis.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT, an inflamed appendix appears as a dilated, non-compressible, fluid-filled tubular structure >6mm in diameter, often with surrounding fat stranding and appendicolith. Intraoperatively, the appendix will be erythematous, edematous, and potentially purulent or gangrenous.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Surgeons (ACS) and Society for Surgery of the Alimentary Tract (SSAT) Guidelines for the Management of Acute Appendicitis (2020). These guidelines emphasize clinical evaluation combined with imaging (ultrasound or CT) for diagnosis, and recommend appendectomy for confirmed cases.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | C. Extramural causes\tD. Low residue diet | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | A large number of gas-fluid levels on a plain X-ray abdomen is suggestive o | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | High intestinal obstruction | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Low intestinal obstruction | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: ?) Cope’s method** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Competency 2500**\n"
