  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Caecal obstruction: low, large, and potentially lethal.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe verdict is that caecal obstruction is classified as a low intestinal obstruction. This is correct because the caecum is part of the large intestine, and any obstruction distal to the ligament of Treitz is considered a low intestinal obstruction.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nIntestinal obstructions are broadly classified into high and low based on their anatomical location relative to the ligament of Treitz. High intestinal obstructions occur proximal to the ligament of Treitz, typically involving the duodenum or proximal jejunum. Low intestinal obstructions occur distal to the ligament of Treitz, encompassing the distal small bowel (ileum) and the entire large bowel. Caecal obstruction, by definition, involves the caecum, which is the beginning of the large intestine, thus placing it firmly in the category of a low intestinal obstruction.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Paralytic ileus is a functional obstruction characterized by impaired peristalsis, not an anatomical classification of a mechanical obstruction like caecal obstruction. \nOption B (Incorrect): This option introduces criteria for bowel non-viability, which is an assessment of a complication of obstruction, not a classification of the obstruction itself. \nOption C (Incorrect): Dark colour with 100% oxygen inhalation is a specific intraoperative criterion used to assess bowel viability, unrelated to the classification of caecal obstruction. \nOption D (Incorrect): Absence of arterial pulsations in the mesentery is another criterion for assessing bowel non-viability, not a classification of intestinal obstruction.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | High Intestinal Obstruction | Low Intestinal Obstruction | Large Bowel Obstruction |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Location | Proximal to Ligament of Treitz | Distal to Ligament of Treitz | Distal to Ileocecal Valve |\n| Examples | Duodenal, Proximal Jejunum | Ileal, Colonic (including Caecal) | Caecal, Sigmoid Volvulus, Colon Cancer |\n| Symptoms | Early vomiting, minimal distension | Late vomiting, significant distension | Marked distension, late vomiting, obstipation |\n| Fluid/Electrolyte | Early and severe imbalance | Later and less severe imbalance | Less severe initially, can lead to perforation |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Caecal obstruction is a large bowel obstruction, thus classified as low.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn plain film, look for a dilated caecum (often >9cm) and proximal colon, with collapsed distal colon if the obstruction is complete. CT scan will show the transition point, dilated proximal bowel, and often the underlying cause (e.g., mass, volvulus). Intraoperatively, the caecum will be distended and potentially ischemic.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Surgeons (ACS) Textbook of Surgery (e.g., Schwartz's Principles of Surgery, 11th Ed., 2019) - Provides comprehensive classification and management strategies for intestinal obstruction, including large bowel obstruction.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Paralytic ileus | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Bowel is considered nonviable on laparotomy, if it shows the following exce | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Dark colour with 100% oxygen inhalation | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Absence of arterial pulsations in the mesentery | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: ?) Low intestinal obstruction** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Competency 2500**\n"
