  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Coffee bean on X-ray, don't delay!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nACCEPT. The verified answer, \"sigmoid volvulus,\" correctly identifies a common and critical surgical emergency affecting the large bowel, particularly the sigmoid colon. This condition involves the twisting of a segment of the colon on its mesentery, leading to obstruction and potential ischemia.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nSigmoid volvulus typically occurs when a redundant sigmoid colon, often with a long mesentery, twists around its mesenteric axis. This anatomical predisposition, frequently exacerbated by chronic constipation or a high-fiber diet, creates a closed-loop obstruction. The twisting compromises both the lumen and the blood supply, leading to rapid distension, pain, and a high risk of ischemia and perforation if not promptly addressed. Surgical intervention, ranging from endoscopic detorsion to emergent sigmoid colectomy, is crucial to prevent life-threatening complications.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): This is a question about Hirschsprung's disease, not a condition or procedure related to sigmoid volvulus.\nOption B (Incorrect): Duhamel's is a pull-through procedure for Hirschsprung's disease, unrelated to sigmoid volvulus.\nOption C (Incorrect): Swenson's is a pull-through procedure for Hirschsprung's disease, unrelated to sigmoid volvulus.\nOption D (Incorrect): Soave's is a pull-through procedure for Hirschsprung's disease, unrelated to sigmoid volvulus.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Sigmoid Volvulus | Cecal Volvulus | Transverse Colon Volvulus |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Location | Sigmoid colon | Cecum/Ascending colon | Transverse colon |\n| X-ray sign | Coffee bean sign, omega loop | Kidney bean sign, comma sign | U-shaped loop |\n| Risk factors | Chronic constipation, high fiber diet, elderly | Incomplete cecal fixation, hypermobility | Rare, often congenital |\n| Treatment | Detorsion (endoscopic/surgical), sigmoid colectomy | Right hemicolectomy | Resection |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Coffee bean sign on X-ray points to sigmoid volvulus.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nAbdominal X-ray shows a large, distended, inverted U-shaped loop of colon (coffee bean sign) extending from the pelvis, often without haustra. CT scan confirms the \"whirl sign.\" Intraoperatively, a grossly distended, often dusky or gangrenous sigmoid colon twisted on its mesentery is seen.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Society of Colon and Rectal Surgeons (ASCRS) Clinical Practice Guidelines for the Management of Colonic Volvulus (2016). Recommends endoscopic detorsion for stable patients, followed by elective sigmoid colectomy. Urgent surgery for signs of peritonitis or ischemia.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Which is the most common operation done for Hirschsprung’s disease? | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Duhamel’s retrorectal pull-through | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Swenson’s endorectal pull-through | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Soave’s operation | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: ?) sigmoid volvulus** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Competency 2500**\n"
