  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Ascites: Drain the fluid, not the varices.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe question asks to identify a method that is NOT preferred in the treatment of ascites in cirrhosis of the liver. Endoscopic electric coagulation is used for variceal bleeding, not directly for the management of ascites itself.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nAscites in cirrhosis results from portal hypertension and splanchnic vasodilation, leading to fluid extravasation into the peritoneal cavity. Management focuses on reducing fluid retention and portal pressure. Endoscopic electric coagulation, while treating a complication of cirrhosis (variceal bleeding), does not address the underlying pathophysiology of ascites formation or directly remove peritoneal fluid.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Repeted aspiration) (Incorrect): Therapeutic paracentesis is a common and effective treatment for symptomatic or refractory ascites, providing rapid relief.\nOption C (Diuretics) (Incorrect): Diuretics, particularly spironolactone and furosemide, are cornerstone medical therapy for ascites by promoting renal sodium and water excretion.\nOption D (Low salt diet) (Incorrect): Dietary sodium restriction is fundamental in ascites management, reducing fluid retention and enhancing diuretic efficacy.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Treatment Modality | Indication for Ascites | Mechanism |\n|---|---|---|\n| Low Sodium Diet | First-line, all patients | Reduces fluid retention by limiting sodium intake |\n| Diuretics (Spironolactone/Furosemide) | First-line, symptomatic ascites | Blocks aldosterone, inhibits Na/Cl reabsorption |\n| Therapeutic Paracentesis | Large/refractory ascites, symptomatic relief | Direct removal of peritoneal fluid |\n| TIPS (Transjugular Intrahepatic Portosystemic Shunt) | Refractory ascites | Reduces portal pressure by shunting blood |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Ascites treatment targets fluid balance, not variceal bleeding.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound, ascites appears as anechoic fluid in the peritoneal cavity, often outlining bowel loops. Endoscopy would show esophageal or gastric varices, which might be treated with coagulation, but not ascites itself.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Association for the Study of Liver Diseases (AASLD) Practice Guidance 2021: The Management of Ascites in Cirrhosis. Recommends sodium restriction and diuretics as initial therapy, with paracentesis for large volume ascites.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | In the treatment of ascites in cirrhosis of the liver, one of the following | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Repeted aspiration | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Diuretics | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Low salt diet | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: ?) Hepatitis C** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Competency 2500**\n"
