  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Liver lesions: primary or secondary, always differentiate!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe verdict \"Carcinoma stomach\" is correct. While Hepatocellular Carcinoma (HCC) is a primary liver malignancy, gastric carcinoma frequently metastasizes to the liver, presenting as liver lesions that require differentiation from HCC. This highlights the importance of considering metastatic disease when evaluating liver masses.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nLiver metastases are far more common than primary liver cancers like HCC. Gastric carcinoma, due to its venous drainage via the portal system, commonly spreads to the liver. Differentiating between primary HCC and metastatic gastric carcinoma is crucial for treatment planning, as their management strategies differ significantly. Imaging characteristics, tumor markers (e.g., AFP for HCC, CEA for gastric mets), and biopsy are essential for accurate diagnosis.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Hemangioma of liver - This is the most common benign liver tumor and does not represent a malignant process or a source of metastasis.\nOption B (Incorrect): Secondaries liver - This is a general term for liver metastases, not a specific primary source. While correct in concept, \"Carcinoma stomach\" provides a specific, common primary source.\nOption C (Incorrect): Trauma - Liver trauma causes injury and hematoma, not a neoplastic lesion that would be confused with HCC or gastric carcinoma metastasis.\nOption D (Incorrect): What is the most common cause of Budd–Chiari syndrome? - This is a question, not an answer option, and Budd-Chiari syndrome is a vascular disorder of the liver, not a tumor type.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Hepatocellular Carcinoma (HCC) | Gastric Carcinoma Metastasis | Liver Hemangioma |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Origin** | Primary liver cancer | Secondary (metastatic) from stomach | Benign vascular tumor |\n| **Risk Factors** | Cirrhosis, Hep B/C, alcohol | H. pylori, diet, genetics | Congenital, hormonal |\n| **Tumor Marker** | Alpha-fetoprotein (AFP) | Carcinoembryonic antigen (CEA), CA 19-9 | None specific |\n| **Treatment** | Resection, ablation, transplant, TACE, systemic | Chemotherapy, palliative surgery, systemic | Observation, rarely embolization/resection |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Always consider metastatic disease when evaluating liver lesions.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT, gastric metastases often appear as multiple, hypodense lesions, sometimes with peripheral enhancement, distinct from the typical arterial enhancement and venous washout of HCC. Intraoperatively, metastases may appear as firm, pale nodules, whereas HCC can be more variable.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNational Comprehensive Cancer Network (NCCN) Guidelines for Gastric Cancer (2023). Recommends systemic therapy for metastatic gastric cancer, including liver metastases.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Hemangioma of liver | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Secodaries liver | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Trauma | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | What is the most common cause of Budd–Chiari syndrome? | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: ?) Carcinoma stomach** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Competency 2500**\n"
