  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Stop the bleed, don't just aspirate the mess.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe verified answer, \"Repeted aspiration,\" is correct because it is not a standard gross principle or technique used in the acute surgical management of liver trauma. Instead, liver trauma management focuses on hemorrhage control and parenchymal repair, not aspiration as a primary treatment.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nSurgical management of liver trauma prioritizes rapid control of bleeding and bile leaks. Key principles include perihepatic packing for temporary hemostasis, vascular control (e.g., Pringle maneuver) to reduce hepatic inflow, and direct repair or resection of damaged parenchyma. Repetitive aspiration is a technique for managing fluid collections or cysts, not a primary method for addressing acute traumatic liver injury itself. Its use in trauma is typically for diagnostic paracentesis or drainage of established collections, not as a gross principle for managing the injury.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nThe provided question and options are unrelated to the verified answer 'Repeted aspiration'. The verified answer implies a question about principles of liver trauma management where 'Repeted aspiration' is the incorrect or 'except' option. Therefore, the given options (A, B, C, D) cannot be addressed as incorrect for this specific verified answer.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Principle of Liver Trauma Management | Description |\n|---|---|\n| Perihepatic Packing | Temporary compression to control hemorrhage, often for damage control. |\n| Pringle Maneuver | Occlusion of the portal triad (hepatic artery, portal vein, bile duct) to reduce hepatic inflow and bleeding. |\n| Direct Repair/Resection | Suture repair of lacerations, debridement of devitalized tissue, or formal resection for severe injuries. |\n| Damage Control Surgery | Staged approach involving initial hemorrhage control, resuscitation, and delayed definitive repair. |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Liver trauma management is about hemorrhage control, not aspiration.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIntraoperatively, liver trauma presents as lacerations, hematomas, or active bleeding. Pre-operative CT scans would show the extent of injury, including lacerations, subcapsular hematomas, or active extravasation of contrast, guiding the need for intervention.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Association for the Surgery of Trauma (AAST) Liver Injury Scale (updated 2018). This scale guides non-operative vs. operative management strategies based on injury grade and patient stability.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Portal vein alone | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Hepatic artery alone | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Hepatic veins | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | The following gross principles are used in surgery of liver trauma except | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: ?) Repeted aspiration** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Competency 2500**\n"
