  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Targeted lung chemo: less systemic, more local punch!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe verdict is ACCEPT. Selective arterial chemotherapy, while most commonly associated with hepatic malignancies, can also be applied to other organs, including the lungs, for localized treatment of primary or metastatic tumors. This technique delivers high concentrations of chemotherapy directly to the tumor while minimizing systemic exposure.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nSelective arterial chemotherapy in the lungs involves cannulating a bronchial or pulmonary artery supplying the tumor. This allows for targeted delivery of chemotherapeutic agents, maximizing drug concentration at the tumor site and potentially improving response rates while reducing systemic toxicity. This approach is particularly considered for unresectable primary lung cancers or lung metastases from other primary sites, aiming for local control or downstaging. The rich vascular supply of lung tumors makes them amenable to this regional delivery method.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Hepatic artery embolization) (Incorrect): This is a specific type of selective arterial therapy (often chemoembolization, TACE) primarily used for liver tumors, not the lungs.\nOption B (Which is the most common etiology for hepatocellular carcinoma?) (Incorrect): This is a question, not an answer related to selective arterial chemotherapy or an organ.\nOption C (Alcohol) (Incorrect): Alcohol is an etiology for hepatocellular carcinoma, not an organ or a treatment method like selective arterial chemotherapy.\nOption D (Viral hepatitis) (Incorrect): Viral hepatitis (e.g., HBV, HCV) is another common etiology for hepatocellular carcinoma, not an organ or a treatment method.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Selective Arterial Chemoembolization (TACE) | Selective Arterial Chemotherapy (TAC) | Systemic Chemotherapy |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Primary Target Organ** | Liver (HCC, metastases) | Liver, Lungs, Extremities, Pelvis | Whole body |\n| **Mechanism** | Chemo + Embolization (ischemia) | Direct drug delivery to tumor | Systemic circulation |\n| **Goal** | Local control, downstaging, palliation | Local control, downstaging, palliation | Systemic disease control |\n| **Systemic Toxicity** | Lower | Lower | Higher |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Selective arterial chemotherapy targets tumors locally, minimizing systemic side effects.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn angiography during the procedure, a catheter is advanced into the specific bronchial or pulmonary artery supplying the lung tumor, which is identified by its characteristic tumor blush or neovascularity.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNational Comprehensive Cancer Network (NCCN) Guidelines for Non-Small Cell Lung Cancer (2023). While not a primary treatment, NCCN guidelines may mention regional therapies in specific contexts for advanced or recurrent disease.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Hepatic artery embolization | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Which is the most common etiology for hepatocellular carcinoma? | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Alcohol | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Viral hepatitis | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: ?) Lungs** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Competency 2500**\n"
