  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Neck lump? Think TB, especially if it's scrofula!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe answer \"Cervical\" is correct. Cervical lymph nodes are indeed the most frequently involved group in extrapulmonary tuberculosis, often presenting as scrofula. This makes it a critical diagnosis to consider in patients with persistent neck masses.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nTuberculosis typically spreads via lymphatic channels from a primary infection site, often pulmonary. The rich lymphatic drainage of the head and neck region, combined with the propensity of Mycobacterium tuberculosis to cause granulomatous inflammation, makes cervical lymph nodes particularly susceptible. This manifestation, known as scrofula, is characterized by painless, firm, matted lymphadenopathy that can progress to caseation, cold abscess formation, and draining sinuses if untreated. It is especially prevalent in children and immunocompromised individuals.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Mediastinal) (Incorrect): While mediastinal lymphadenopathy is very common in primary pulmonary TB, especially in children, it is typically an intrathoracic manifestation and not the most common overall extrapulmonary site presenting as a palpable mass.\nOption C (Axillary) (Incorrect): Axillary lymph node involvement in TB is less common than cervical and usually associated with a primary focus in the ipsilateral upper limb or breast.\nOption D (Inguinal) (Incorrect): Inguinal lymphadenopathy due to TB is also less frequent and typically linked to a primary infection in the lower limbs, perineum, or genitourinary tract.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Lymph Node Group | Common Association | Clinical Significance |\n|---|---|---|\n| Cervical (Scrofula) | Extrapulmonary TB, especially in children/immunocompromised | Most common palpable TB lymphadenopathy |\n| Mediastinal | Primary pulmonary TB | Often asymptomatic, can cause airway compression |\n| Mesenteric | Abdominal TB | Can mimic other abdominal pathologies, cause obstruction |\n| Axillary/Inguinal | Localized infection in limb/breast/genitourinary | Less common, requires local primary source investigation |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Scrofula is cervical TB lymphadenitis, the most common extrapulmonary TB presentation.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT or ultrasound, tuberculous lymph nodes often appear as enlarged, hypoechoic or low-attenuation masses with central necrosis (caseation) and peripheral rim enhancement after contrast. They can be matted together, forming a conglomerate mass, and may show calcifications in chronic cases. Intraoperatively, they are typically firm, often adherent to surrounding structures, and may contain thick, caseous material.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nCenters for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) 2020: \"Treatment for TB Disease.\" Recommends specific multi-drug regimens and durations for extrapulmonary TB, including lymph node involvement.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Mediastinal | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Cervical | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Axillary | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Inguinal | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: ?) B) Cervical** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Competency 2500**\n"
