  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Tarda: when your lymphatics decide to retire late.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe verified answer, Lymphedema tarda, is correct. This term specifically refers to primary lymphedema that manifests after the age of 35, distinguishing it from earlier onset forms of primary lymphedema.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nPrimary lymphedema results from congenital abnormalities in the lymphatic system, such as aplasia, hypoplasia, or obstruction of lymphatic vessels. Lymphedema tarda, specifically, is thought to be due to a more subtle or less severe lymphatic defect that only becomes clinically apparent later in life, often triggered by factors like minor trauma, infection, or hormonal changes that overwhelm the compromised lymphatic drainage capacity. The lymphatic system's crucial role in fluid balance and immune surveillance, when compromised, leads to protein-rich fluid accumulation and chronic tissue swelling.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Lymphedema precox refers to primary lymphedema that manifests between puberty and the age of 35.\nOption C (Incorrect): Lymphedema congenita refers to primary lymphedema that is present at birth or manifests within the first two years of life.\nOption D (Incorrect): Lymphedema senilia is not a recognized medical term for primary lymphedema; \"senile\" refers to old age, but the specific classification for late-onset primary lymphedema is \"tarda.\"\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Type | Onset Age | Characteristics |\n|---|---|---|\n| Lymphedema congenita | At birth or within 2 years | Often associated with genetic syndromes (e.g., Milroy's disease) |\n| Lymphedema precox | Puberty to 35 years | Most common form of primary lymphedema, often affecting lower limbs |\n| Lymphedema tarda | After 35 years | Less common, subtle lymphatic defect, often triggered by minor events |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: \"Tarda\" means late; \"precox\" means early; \"congenita\" means at birth.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nLymphoscintigraphy would show delayed or absent lymphatic flow and uptake in regional lymph nodes, indicating lymphatic dysfunction. MRI lymphangiography can visualize lymphatic vessel morphology and identify areas of aplasia or hypoplasia.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nInternational Society of Lymphology (ISL) Consensus Document on the Management of Lymphedema (2020). It provides a classification system for lymphedema, including primary lymphedema based on age of onset.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Lymphedema precox | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Lymphedema tarda | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Lymphedema congenita | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Lymphedema senilia | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: ?) B) Lymphedema tarda** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Competency 2500**\n"
