  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Mycosis Fungoides: When your skin's T-cells go rogue.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nMycosis fungoides is the correct answer. It is the most common form of cutaneous T-cell lymphoma (CTCL), a type of non-Hodgkin lymphoma that primarily affects the skin. This condition represents a malignant proliferation of T-lymphocytes with a predilection for the epidermis.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nMycosis fungoides is characterized by a slow, indolent progression from patches to plaques to tumors, often mimicking benign dermatoses in its early stages. The hallmark histological feature is epidermotropism, where atypical CD4+ T-lymphocytes infiltrate the epidermis, sometimes forming characteristic Pautrier microabscesses. Understanding this unique tropism for the skin is crucial for diagnosis and differentiates it from other lymphomas. The disease can eventually spread to lymph nodes, blood (Sézary syndrome), and internal organs, necessitating careful staging and management.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Lupus vulgaris is a chronic and progressive form of cutaneous tuberculosis, caused by Mycobacterium tuberculosis, not a lymphoma.\nOption B (Incorrect): Lupus erythematosus is a chronic autoimmune inflammatory disease that can affect the skin (e.g., malar rash, discoid lesions) but is not a neoplastic condition like lymphoma.\nOption D (Incorrect): Histoplasmosis is a fungal infection caused by Histoplasma capsulatum, which can present with cutaneous manifestations but is an infectious disease, not a lymphoma.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Condition | Etiology/Type | Key Feature/Organism | Primary Manifestation |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Mycosis Fungoides | Cutaneous T-cell Lymphoma | Epidermotropism, Pautrier microabscesses | Patches, plaques, tumors of skin |\n| Lupus Vulgaris | Cutaneous Tuberculosis | *Mycobacterium tuberculosis* | Chronic, progressive skin lesions (apple-jelly nodules) |\n| Lupus Erythematosus | Autoimmune Disease | Autoantibodies (e.g., ANA) | Malar rash, discoid lesions, systemic involvement |\n| Histoplasmosis | Fungal Infection | *Histoplasma capsulatum* | Pulmonary, disseminated, or cutaneous lesions |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Mycosis Fungoides: The skin's own T-cell lymphoma.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nEarly Mycosis Fungoides is diagnosed via skin biopsy, showing atypical cerebriform T-lymphocytes with epidermotropism. For advanced stages, CT or PET scans are used to assess lymph node and visceral involvement, guiding systemic therapy.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNational Comprehensive Cancer Network (NCCN) Guidelines for Mycosis Fungoides/Sézary Syndrome (2023) recommends staging based on TNMB classification and tailored treatment from skin-directed therapies to systemic agents.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Lupus vulgaris | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Lupus erithematosis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Mycosis fungoides | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Histoplasmosis | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: ?) C) Mycosis fungoides** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Competency 2500**\n"
