  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When lymphatics are born bad, it's primary; when they're broken, it's secondary.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is D) Lymphoedema precox. This is because Lymphoedema precox is a form of primary lymphedema, meaning it arises from congenital or developmental abnormalities of the lymphatic system, rather than an acquired external cause. The question specifically asks for causes of secondary lymphedema, implying an acquired etiology.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nLymphedema is broadly categorized into primary and secondary forms based on its etiology. Primary lymphedema, such as Lymphoedema precox, results from intrinsic defects in lymphatic development or function, often manifesting in adolescence or early adulthood. These defects can include aplasia, hypoplasia, or hyperplasia of lymphatic vessels, leading to impaired lymphatic drainage from birth. In contrast, secondary lymphedema is acquired due to damage or obstruction of previously normal lymphatic channels, typically from external factors like surgery, radiation, infection, or trauma.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Radioablation of metastatic lymph nodes is a common cause of secondary lymphedema. The energy used in radioablation can damage surrounding lymphatic vessels and nodes, impairing drainage.\nOption C (Incorrect): Block dissection of lymph nodes, a surgical procedure to remove regional lymph nodes, is a well-established and frequent cause of secondary lymphedema due to the direct transection and removal of lymphatic channels.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Primary Lymphedema | Secondary Lymphedema |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Etiology** | Congenital/developmental lymphatic abnormalities | Acquired damage/obstruction to previously normal lymphatics |\n| **Onset** | Often at birth, childhood, or adolescence (e.g., precox) | Any age, typically after an inciting event |\n| **Examples** | Milroy's disease, Meige's disease, Lymphoedema precox | Post-mastectomy lymphedema, filariasis, radiation-induced |\n| **Pathophysiology** | Intrinsic lymphatic dysfunction (aplasia, hypoplasia) | Extrinsic damage (surgery, radiation, infection, trauma, malignancy) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Primary lymphedema is *born* with it; secondary lymphedema *gets* it.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nLymphoscintigraphy is the gold standard for diagnosing lymphedema, showing delayed or absent lymphatic flow. Intraoperatively, indocyanine green (ICG) lymphography can visualize lymphatic channels and areas of impaired flow, guiding lymphaticovenous anastomosis (LVA) procedures.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nInternational Society of Lymphology (ISL) Consensus Document on the Management of Lymphedema (2021). It provides a comprehensive staging and treatment algorithm for both primary and secondary lymphedema.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | except | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Radioablation of metastatic lymph nodes | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Block dissection of lymph nodes | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Lymphoedema precox | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: ?) D) Lymphoedema precox** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Competency 2500**\n"
