  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Staging laparotomy: A historical deep dive, now mostly PET/CT.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe verdict is ACCEPT. The question implicitly asks what procedure is NOT typically associated with or performed during a staging laparotomy. Amputation, the surgical removal of a limb, is entirely unrelated to the abdominal exploration and biopsies characteristic of a staging laparotomy.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nA staging laparotomy is an invasive surgical procedure historically performed for certain cancers, most notably Hodgkin's lymphoma, to precisely determine the extent of disease. It involves a systematic exploration of the abdominal cavity, including splenectomy, liver and bone marrow biopsies, and extensive sampling of lymph nodes (e.g., para-aortic, celiac, iliac). The primary goal is to identify occult disease in abdominal organs or lymph nodes that might not be detected by non-invasive imaging. Amputation, in contrast, is the surgical removal of a limb or part of a limb, typically indicated for severe trauma, infection, peripheral vascular disease, or unresectable tumors of the extremity, and plays no role in the abdominal staging of cancer.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): This appears to be the stem of a different question regarding Hodgkin's lymphoma features, not an option for the implied question about staging laparotomy. \nOption B (Incorrect): This refers to a clinical feature of Hodgkin's lymphoma (bimodal age presentation), not a procedure or indication related to staging laparotomy. \nOption C (Incorrect): This refers to a clinical feature of Hodgkin's lymphoma (spread from central to peripheral lymph nodes), not a procedure or indication related to staging laparotomy. \nOption D (Incorrect): This refers to a clinical feature of Hodgkin's lymphoma (involvement of organs outside the lymphatic system), not a procedure or indication related to staging laparotomy.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Staging Laparotomy | Modern Staging (e.g., PET/CT) | Amputation |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Purpose | Surgical assessment of abdominal disease extent | Non-invasive assessment of systemic disease extent | Removal of diseased/damaged limb |\n| Modality | Invasive surgery, direct visualization, biopsy | Imaging (metabolic and anatomical) | Invasive surgery |\n| Risks | Surgical complications (e.g., infection, bleeding, anesthesia) | Radiation exposure, contrast reactions | Surgical complications, phantom limb pain |\n| Current Use | Largely superseded for Hodgkin's; still used for some ovarian cancers | Standard for most cancers | Trauma, infection, vascular disease, tumors |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Staging laparotomy for Hodgkin's is largely historical, replaced by PET/CT.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nDuring a staging laparotomy, one would intraoperatively visualize and biopsy lymph nodes (celiac, para-aortic, iliac), perform splenectomy, and take wedge/needle biopsies of the liver. On modern imaging, a PET/CT would show metabolically active lesions, guiding non-invasive staging.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for Hodgkin Lymphoma (2023): Recommend PET/CT for staging, largely replacing staging laparotomy for this disease.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | The following are the clinical features of Hodgkin’s lymphoma except | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Bimodal presentation | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Centripetal lymph node involvement | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Extralymphatic organ involvement | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: ?) Amputation** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Competency 2500**\n"
