  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Lymphoma is cancer; filariasis is worms.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe question asks to identify the option that is NOT a feature of Non-Hodgkin's lymphoma (NHL). The correct answer, Filariasis, is a parasitic infection and not a characteristic manifestation of NHL, making it the appropriate exception. NHL is a diverse group of lymphoid malignancies with varied presentations.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nNon-Hodgkin's lymphoma is characterized by its potential for widespread, non-contiguous lymphadenopathy and frequent extranodal involvement. Epitrochlear lymph node enlargement, while less common than cervical or axillary, can occur in NHL, particularly in aggressive subtypes or those with diffuse involvement. Furthermore, the gastrointestinal tract is one of the most common sites for extranodal NHL, presenting as primary GI lymphoma or secondary involvement. Filariasis, conversely, is a parasitic disease caused by nematodes that obstruct lymphatic vessels, leading to lymphedema and lymphadenopathy, but it is fundamentally distinct from a neoplastic process.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption C (Incorrect): Epitrochlear lymph node enlargement is a known feature of Non-Hodgkin's lymphoma, especially in diffuse or aggressive forms, making it a correct feature, not an exception.\nOption D (Incorrect): Involvement of the gastrointestinal tract is a common extranodal manifestation of Non-Hodgkin's lymphoma, particularly MALT lymphoma or diffuse large B-cell lymphoma, making it a correct feature, not an exception.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Non-Hodgkin's Lymphoma | Hodgkin's Lymphoma | Filariasis |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Etiology | Malignant lymphocyte proliferation | Malignant B-cells (Reed-Sternberg cells) | Parasitic infection (nematodes) |\n| Lymphadenopathy | Often widespread, non-contiguous, extranodal | Contiguous spread, often mediastinal/cervical | Lymphatic obstruction, lymphedema |\n| Extranodal Involvement | Common (GI, skin, CNS, bone marrow) | Less common | Rare, but can cause chyluria, hydrocele |\n| Epitrochlear Nodes | Can be involved | Rarely involved | Can cause inguinal/femoral lymphadenopathy |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: NHL is the great mimicker; think extranodal involvement.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT, NHL often presents as bulky lymphadenopathy, sometimes with extranodal masses in the GI tract (e.g., gastric wall thickening), liver, or spleen. Filariasis might show dilated lymphatic vessels and calcified worms on imaging.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for B-Cell Lymphomas (2023). Recommends comprehensive staging, risk stratification, and histology-specific treatment approaches.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | The following are the features of Non-Hodgkin’s lymphoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | except | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Epitrochlear lymph ndoe enlargement | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | May involve gastrointestinal tract | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: ?) Filariasis** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Competency 2500**\n"
