  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Stiff neck after head trauma? Think CSF, think bleed, think fast!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe verdict is ACCEPT. \"Neck stiffness\" is a critical sign that can accompany a middle cranial fossa fracture, often indicating meningeal irritation due to CSF leak or intracranial hemorrhage. This symptom warrants immediate investigation for potential complications.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nMiddle cranial fossa fractures frequently involve the temporal bone, sphenoid bone, and parts of the parietal bone. A fracture extending into the petrous portion of the temporal bone can lead to CSF otorrhea or rhinorrhea. If CSF leaks into the subarachnoid space or if there's an associated subarachnoid hemorrhage, it can irritate the meninges, leading to nuchal rigidity or neck stiffness. This is a crucial indicator of potential meningitis or significant intracranial injury requiring prompt diagnosis and management.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Posterior cranial fracture): Incorrect. This describes a fracture in a different anatomical region of the skull, not a symptom or complication of a middle cranial fossa fracture.\nOption B (Blow-out fracture): Incorrect. This refers specifically to a fracture of the orbital floor or medial wall, which is distinct from a middle cranial fossa fracture and not a symptom.\nOption C (Which fracture of the skull causes caroticocavernous fistula?): Incorrect. This is a question itself, not a symptom, and while a middle cranial fossa fracture (e.g., sphenoid bone) can cause a caroticocavernous fistula, \"neck stiffness\" is the verified answer, not this specific complication or question.\nOption D (Fracture of occipital bone): Incorrect. This describes a fracture in the posterior part of the skull, not a symptom or a middle cranial fossa fracture itself.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Fracture Type | Common Location | Key Symptom/Sign | Potential Complication |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Middle Cranial Fossa | Temporal, Sphenoid | Neck stiffness (meningeal irritation) | CSF leak, Meningitis, Carotid injury |\n| Anterior Cranial Fossa | Frontal, Ethmoid | Raccoon eyes, CSF rhinorrhea | Anosmia, Meningitis |\n| Posterior Cranial Fossa | Occipital, Petrous | Battle's sign, CSF otorrhea | Cranial nerve palsies, Vertebral artery injury |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Neck stiffness post-head trauma demands CSF leak or hemorrhage exclusion.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT scan, look for fracture lines extending into the petrous temporal bone or sphenoid sinus, pneumocephalus, or fluid levels in sinuses. Intraoperatively, CSF leakage may be visualized.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nBrain Trauma Foundation Guidelines (2019) for the Management of Severe Traumatic Brain Injury. They recommend prompt imaging and management of complications like CSF leaks.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Posterior cranial fracture | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Blow-out fracture | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Which fracture of the skull causes caroticocavernous fistula? | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Fracture of occipital bone | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: ?) Neck stiffness** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Competency 2500**\n"
