  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When in doubt, think astrocytoma, especially GBM!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe question asks for the most common glioma of the brain. The correct answer is Astrocytoma, which represents the largest group of primary brain tumors, with Glioblastoma being the most frequent and aggressive subtype.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nAstrocytomas originate from astrocytes, the most abundant glial cells in the central nervous system. They are classified by the World Health Organization (WHO) into grades I-IV, with Glioblastoma (WHO grade IV) being the most common and aggressive primary brain tumor in adults. Their prevalence stems from the widespread distribution of astrocytes throughout the brain, making them susceptible to neoplastic transformation.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Oligodendrogliomas are gliomas originating from oligodendrocytes, but they are significantly less common than astrocytomas, accounting for a smaller percentage of primary brain tumors.\nOption C (Incorrect): Neurofibromas are benign tumors of the peripheral nervous system, arising from Schwann cells, not glial cells of the central nervous system, and are therefore not gliomas.\nOption D (Incorrect): Gangliocytomas are rare, benign tumors composed of mature neuronal ganglion cells, often with a glial component, but are far less common than astrocytomas.\nProvided \"VERIFIED ANSWER\" (Incorrect): \"Frontal lobes\" describes an anatomical location within the brain, not a specific type of glioma, and thus does not answer the question regarding the most common glioma.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Tumor Type | Origin Cell | WHO Grade Range | Common Location | Key Feature |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| Astrocytoma | Astrocytes | I-IV | Cerebral hemispheres (esp. frontal/temporal) | Most common glioma; Glioblastoma (IV) is most aggressive |\n| Oligodendroglioma | Oligodendrocytes | II-III | Frontal lobes | Often calcified; 1p/19q co-deletion |\n| Ependymoma | Ependymal cells | I-III | Fourth ventricle (children), spinal cord (adults) | Often associated with hydrocephalus |\n| Neurofibroma | Schwann cells | I | Peripheral nerves | Not a glioma; associated with NF1 |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Astrocytoma is the king of gliomas, especially Glioblastoma.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn MRI, high-grade astrocytomas (Glioblastoma) typically appear as heterogeneously enhancing masses with central necrosis and surrounding vasogenic edema, often with irregular margins. Intraoperatively, they are infiltrative, poorly demarcated, and may have areas of hemorrhage or necrosis.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nWHO Classification of Tumours of the Central Nervous System (5th Edition, 2021) recommends a combined histomolecular approach for diagnosis and grading of gliomas.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Astrocytoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Oligodendrogliomas | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Neurofibroma | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Gangliocytoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: ?) Frontal lobes** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Competency 2500**\n"
