  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Hip fracture + immobility = PE risk. Don't miss it!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nWhile the question describes an intertrochanteric femur fracture, the verified answer points to a critical complication. Pulmonary embolism is a life-threatening complication frequently associated with these fractures, making it a crucial consideration in patient management.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nIntertrochanteric femur fractures, especially in elderly patients, lead to prolonged immobility, venous stasis, and a hypercoagulable state due to systemic inflammatory response to trauma. This combination, known as Virchow's triad, creates an ideal environment for deep vein thrombosis (DVT) formation. If a DVT dislodges, it can travel to the pulmonary circulation, causing a pulmonary embolism, which can be fatal.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): 'Fracture of distal third tibia' is an unrelated orthopedic injury and not a complication of a proximal femur fracture.\nOption B (Incorrect): 'Wrist drop is seen in' is an incomplete statement referring to a neurological sign, not a complication of a hip fracture.\nOption C (Incorrect): 'Radial nerve injury' is a neurological injury typically associated with humeral shaft fractures or direct trauma, not a complication of an intertrochanteric femur fracture.\nOption D (Incorrect): 'Ulnar nerve injury' is a neurological injury typically associated with elbow trauma or compression, not a complication of an intertrochanteric femur fracture.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Complication | Mechanism | Clinical Presentation | Management |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Pulmonary Embolism | DVT formation due to immobility, hypercoagulability, venous stasis | Dyspnea, pleuritic chest pain, tachycardia, hypoxemia | Anticoagulation, thrombolysis, embolectomy |\n| Deep Vein Thrombosis | Venous stasis, endothelial injury, hypercoagulability (Virchow's triad) | Leg swelling, pain, tenderness, warmth | Anticoagulation, compression stockings |\n| Fat Embolism Syndrome | Release of fat globules from bone marrow into circulation | Respiratory distress, neurological dysfunction, petechial rash | Supportive care, oxygenation |\n| Infection | Open fracture, surgical site contamination | Fever, erythema, purulent discharge, pain | Antibiotics, debridement |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Always consider DVT/PE prophylaxis in major orthopedic trauma.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT Pulmonary Angiogram (CTPA), a filling defect within the pulmonary arteries confirms the diagnosis of pulmonary embolism. Intraoperatively for the fracture, meticulous surgical technique and early mobilization are key to reducing DVT/PE risk.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Academy of Orthopaedic Surgeons (AAOS) Clinical Practice Guideline: Management of Hip Fractures in Older Adults (2020). Recommends routine pharmacologic thromboprophylaxis for hip fracture patients unless contraindicated.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Fracture of distal third tibia | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Wrist drop is seen in | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Radial nerve injury | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Ulnar nerve injury | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: ?) Pulmonary embolism** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Competency 2500**\n"
