  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Medial condyle: posteriorly displaced, surgically embraced.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer, 'Posterior', refers to the common displacement direction of a medial condyle fracture of the humerus. These fractures, particularly in children, often involve a rotational component leading to this specific posterior and distal displacement pattern.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nMedial condyle fractures are intra-articular injuries, typically involving the trochlea. The primary mechanism often involves a valgus stress combined with the strong pull of the common flexor origin and pronator teres muscles attached to the medial epicondyle fragment. This muscular pull, coupled with the initial injury force, results in the characteristic posterior and often distal displacement and rotation of the fracture fragment. Accurate reduction and stable fixation are paramount to restore articular congruity and prevent elbow instability or deformity.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Monteggia fracture): Incorrect. A Monteggia fracture is a specific forearm injury involving an ulnar fracture with associated radial head dislocation, unrelated to a humeral condyle fracture.\nOption B (Which of the following deformities is commonly seen in tubercular arthritis of hip joint?): Incorrect. This is a complete question about hip pathology, not an option for a medial condyle fracture.\nOption C (Flexion, abduction and internal rotation): Incorrect. This describes a specific deformity of the hip joint, not a displacement pattern of an elbow condyle fracture.\nOption D (Flexion, abduction and external rotation): Incorrect. This also describes a specific deformity of the hip joint, not a displacement pattern of an elbow condyle fracture.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Fracture Type           | Common Displacement      | Key Feature/Concern                               |\n|------------------------|--------------------------|---------------------------------------------------|\n| Medial Condyle Humerus | Posterior and distal     | Pull of common flexor origin; intra-articular     |\n| Lateral Condyle Humerus| Lateral and proximal     | Pull of common extensor origin; intra-articular   |\n| Supracondylar Humerus  | Posterior (extension type)| High risk of neurovascular injury; common in kids |\n| Monteggia Fracture     | Radial head dislocation  | Ulnar shaft fracture; forearm instability         |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Medial condyle fractures: think posterior displacement.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn X-ray, oblique views are crucial to assess displacement. CT scan provides the best detail for articular involvement and fragment rotation. Intraoperatively, the fragment is often rotated and displaced posteriorly, requiring careful manipulation for anatomical reduction.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAAOS Clinical Practice Guidelines for Pediatric Elbow Fractures (various years): Recommends surgical fixation for displaced medial condyle fractures to ensure anatomical reduction and stability.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Monteggia fracture | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Which of the following deformities is commonly seen in tubercular arthritis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Flexion, abduction and internal rotation | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Flexion, abduction and external rotation | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: ?) Posterior** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Competency 2500**\n"
