  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Brace for years, not months, to beat clubfoot relapse.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe Denis Browne splint, or more commonly a foot abduction brace (FAB), is a critical component of the Ponseti method for clubfoot treatment. Option D correctly outlines the duration and intensity of its use, which is essential for maintaining the corrected position and preventing relapse.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe Ponseti method, a highly successful non-surgical approach for idiopathic clubfoot, relies on two main phases: serial manipulation and casting, followed by a prolonged bracing period. The foot abduction brace works by maintaining the foot in abduction and dorsiflexion, counteracting the forces that lead to relapse. The initial phase of nearly full-time wear (23 hours/day) is crucial until the child begins walking, typically around 3-4 months after cast removal or until 12-18 months of age. Subsequently, nighttime and naptime wear until age four to five years is vital because the ligaments and capsule continue to mature and stabilize, and the risk of relapse remains significant without consistent bracing.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): The Denis Browne splint is used *after* the correction phase, not between serial manipulation sessions. Serial casting is used during manipulation.\nOption B (Incorrect): Six months of bracing is insufficient. Relapse rates are very high if bracing is discontinued this early, as the foot structures are not yet stable.\nOption C (Incorrect): Nine months of bracing is also insufficient. The long-term nature of clubfoot relapse prevention necessitates bracing for several years, not just months.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Phase of Treatment | Method | Duration/Purpose |\n|---|---|---|\n| Initial Correction | Ponseti Method (serial casting) | Weekly casts for 5-7 weeks to achieve correction |\n| Tenotomy | Achilles tenotomy | Often performed after casting to correct residual equinus |\n| Maintenance (Initial) | Foot Abduction Brace (e.g., Denis Browne) | 23 hours/day until walking age (approx. 3-4 months post-cast removal, or 12-18 months total) |\n| Maintenance (Long-term) | Foot Abduction Brace (e.g., Denis Browne) | Nighttime/naptime until 4-5 years of age to prevent relapse |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Ponseti success hinges on strict bracing adherence.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn X-rays, assess the talonavicular coverage angle and talocalcaneal angle to confirm correction. Intraoperatively, after tenotomy, ensure full dorsiflexion and abduction are achievable before casting or bracing.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Academy of Orthopaedic Surgeons (AAOS) Clinical Practice Guideline for the Treatment of Idiopathic Clubfoot (2019). Recommends the Ponseti method with subsequent bracing.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Between each session of serial manipulation | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | After complete correction of the deformity till six months of age | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | After complete correction of the deformity till nine months of age | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | After complete correction of the deformity for 23 hours a day till walking  | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: ?) Muscular dystrophy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Competency 2500**\n"
