  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Drain the pseudocyst, relieve the pain, endoscopically!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe verified answer, Endoscopic cystogastrostomy, is a minimally invasive procedure primarily used to drain symptomatic pancreatic pseudocysts. It involves creating an anastomosis between the pseudocyst and the stomach lumen to allow internal drainage.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nEndoscopic cystogastrostomy is performed by placing a stent (usually double pigtail or fully covered self-expanding metal stent) through the gastric wall into the pseudocyst under endoscopic and often EUS guidance. This creates a durable fistula, allowing the pseudocyst fluid to drain into the stomach, thereby relieving symptoms like pain, gastric outlet obstruction, or biliary obstruction. Its advantages include being less invasive than surgical cystogastrostomy, faster recovery, and avoidance of external pancreatic fistula.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nThe provided question 'Bile duct stones' is incorrect as Endoscopic cystogastrostomy is a procedure for pancreatic pseudocysts, not bile duct stones. Bile duct stones are typically managed with ERCP, cholecystectomy, or choledocholithotomy. \nOption A (Incorrect): Hyperparathyroidism is a metabolic disorder, unrelated to the treatment of pancreatic pseudocysts. \nOption B (Incorrect): Hyperthyroidism is an endocrine disorder, unrelated to the treatment of pancreatic pseudocysts. \nOption C (Incorrect): This is a question about Ranson score for pancreatitis severity, not a treatment option or a diagnosis. It is irrelevant to Endoscopic cystogastrostomy. \nOption D (Incorrect): White blood cell count is a laboratory parameter, not a treatment or a diagnosis. It is irrelevant to Endoscopic cystogastrostomy.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Condition | Treatment Modality | Key Feature |\n|---|---|---|\n| Pancreatic Pseudocyst | Endoscopic Cystogastrostomy | Internal drainage into stomach/duodenum |\n| Bile Duct Stones | ERCP with Sphincterotomy & Stone Extraction | Endoscopic removal from common bile duct |\n| Acute Pancreatitis | Supportive Care | Fluid resuscitation, pain control, nutrition |\n| Chronic Pancreatitis | Pain management, enzyme replacement | May require surgical/endoscopic drainage for ductal obstruction |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Pseudocyst + symptoms = drainage, often endoscopic cystogastrostomy.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT or MRI, a pancreatic pseudocyst appears as a well-defined, encapsulated fluid collection, typically adjacent to the pancreas. During endoscopy, a bulge in the gastric or duodenal wall may be seen, which is then punctured under EUS guidance to access and drain the pseudocyst.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Gastroenterological Association (AGA) Institute Guidelines 2018: Recommends endoscopic drainage for symptomatic pancreatic pseudocysts that are mature and in close proximity to the GI lumen.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Hyperparathyroidism | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Hyperthyroidism | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | The following factors are used to diagnose the severity of pancreatitis on  | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | White blood cell count | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: ?) Endoscopic cystogastrostomy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Competency 2500**\n"
