  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Hereditary pancreatitis: think Manchester, think ducts.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe question pertains to the Manchester criteria, which are diagnostic guidelines for hereditary pancreatitis. The verified answer, \"Anomalies of the duct,\" is a key component of these criteria, specifically referring to ductal changes seen in chronic pancreatitis associated with genetic predisposition.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe Manchester criteria are used to diagnose hereditary pancreatitis, a rare genetic disorder predisposing individuals to recurrent acute pancreatitis and chronic pancreatitis. These criteria incorporate clinical features, family history, and imaging findings, including ductal anomalies such as strictures, dilatations, or calculi, which are hallmarks of chronic pancreatitis. The presence of such anomalies, especially in conjunction with a family history or genetic mutations, strongly supports the diagnosis.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): This is a question about insulinoma treatment, not an answer to Manchester criteria. \nOption B (Incorrect): This is a surgical procedure for insulinoma, unrelated to Manchester criteria. \nOption C (Incorrect): This is a general surgical procedure, unrelated to Manchester criteria. \nOption D (Incorrect): This is a surgical procedure for pancreatic lesions, unrelated to Manchester criteria.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Criteria | Description | Key Features |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Manchester Criteria** | Diagnostic criteria for hereditary pancreatitis | Family history, recurrent acute pancreatitis, chronic pancreatitis, ductal anomalies, genetic mutations (e.g., PRSS1) |\n| **M-ANNHEIM Classification** | Comprehensive classification for chronic pancreatitis | Etiology, alcohol, nicotine, nutrition, heredity, efferent duct factors, immunology, metabolism, other factors |\n| **Cambridge Classification** | Radiologic classification for chronic pancreatitis | Based on ERCP findings: normal, equivocal, mild, moderate, severe changes in pancreatic duct |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Manchester criteria = hereditary pancreatitis + ductal anomalies.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn imaging (ERCP, MRCP, CT), ductal anomalies in hereditary pancreatitis often manifest as irregular dilatation and strictures of the main pancreatic duct, side branch ectasia, intraductal calculi, and pancreatic atrophy, consistent with chronic pancreatitis.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nThe European Pancreatic Club (EPC) and the American Pancreatic Association (APA) consensus guidelines on the diagnosis and management of chronic pancreatitis (2017) discuss the role of genetic testing and diagnostic criteria like Manchester criteria in hereditary forms.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | What is the surgical treatment of insulinoma? | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Enucleation of the tumor | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Wide excision of tumor | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Distal pancreatectomy | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: ?) Anomalies of the duct** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Competency 2500**\n"
