  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Drain that pseudocyst, but do it internally!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nCystojejunostomy is a surgical procedure involving the creation of an anastomosis between a pancreatic pseudocyst and the jejunum. This internal drainage technique is typically performed to relieve symptoms and prevent complications associated with large, symptomatic, or complicated pancreatic pseudocysts.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThis procedure provides effective internal drainage of a pancreatic pseudocyst into the small bowel, bypassing the need for external drainage which carries higher risks of infection and fistula formation. A Roux-en-Y limb of jejunum is often used to prevent reflux of intestinal contents into the pseudocyst, minimizing the risk of cholangitis or recurrent infection. The anatomical basis involves connecting the cyst wall, which is typically mature and thick, to the jejunal lumen, allowing continuous decompression.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nThe provided question and options are unrelated to the verified answer 'Cystojejunostomy'. Therefore, a debrief of the incorrect options in relation to the answer is not possible.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Cystojejunostomy | Cystogastrostomy | Percutaneous Drainage |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Type** | Internal drainage | Internal drainage | External drainage |\n| **Anastomosis** | Pseudocyst to Roux-en-Y jejunum | Pseudocyst to stomach | Catheter to skin |\n| **Indication** | Mature pseudocysts, often posterior/inferior, or when cystogastrostomy/duodenostomy is not feasible | Mature pseudocysts, anterior/medial to stomach | Immature/infected pseudocysts, high surgical risk patients |\n| **Advantages** | Low recurrence, prevents reflux, definitive | Minimally invasive (endoscopic), good drainage | Minimally invasive, good for infected cysts |\n| **Disadvantages** | More complex surgery than cystogastrostomy | Risk of reflux, bleeding, infection | High recurrence, fistula risk, catheter care |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Symptomatic pseudocysts need drainage; internal is generally preferred.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT or MRI, a well-defined, encapsulated fluid collection (pseudocyst) adjacent to the pancreas would be seen. Intraoperatively, a thick-walled cyst is identified, aspirated to confirm contents, and then anastomosed to a Roux-en-Y limb of jejunum.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Gastroenterological Association (AGA) Institute Guidelines on the Management of Acute Pancreatitis (2018) recommends drainage for symptomatic pancreatic pseudocysts, with internal drainage preferred for mature cysts.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | In which of the following conditions Grey–Turner’s sign is NOT seen? | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Acute pancreatitis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Rupture of abdominal aortic aneurysm | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Rupture of spleen | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: ?) Cystojejunostomy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Competency 2500**\n"
