  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When the duodenum looks like a '3', think pancreas, not me!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is C) Carcinoma head of pancreas. The \"antral pad sign,\" also known as Frostberg's inverted 3 sign, is a classic radiographic finding on an upper GI barium series indicative of extrinsic compression of the duodenal C-loop by a mass in the head of the pancreas.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nCarcinoma of the head of the pancreas frequently grows to a size that causes extrinsic compression of the adjacent second part of the duodenum. This compression is visualized on a barium meal study as a characteristic indentation on the medial wall of the duodenal C-loop, creating the 'inverted 3' appearance. This sign is highly suggestive of a pancreatic head mass, often malignant, due to its anatomical proximity and infiltrative nature. While barium studies are less common now, understanding this classic sign highlights the anatomical relationship between the pancreas and duodenum.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Carcinoma periampullary region is a broader term encompassing tumors of the ampulla, distal CBD, duodenum, and pancreatic head. While a pancreatic head carcinoma is periampullary, the specific 'antral pad sign' is most classically associated with the mass effect of a pancreatic head tumor.\nOption D (Incorrect): Carcinoma of the terminal end of common bile duct (distal cholangiocarcinoma) typically causes a 'rat-tail' stricture of the CBD and less commonly produces the distinct 'antral pad sign' of duodenal compression seen with a larger pancreatic head mass.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Tumor Type | Classic Barium Sign | Primary Symptom | Location |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Carcinoma Head of Pancreas | Antral Pad / Inverted 3 Sign | Painless Jaundice, Weight Loss | Pancreatic Head |\n| Ampullary Carcinoma | Irregular filling defect at ampulla | Painless Jaundice, GI Bleed | Ampulla of Vater |\n| Distal CBD Carcinoma | \"Rat-tail\" stricture of CBD | Painless Jaundice | Distal Common Bile Duct |\n| Duodenal Carcinoma | Annular stricture, mucosal irregularity | GI Bleed, Obstruction | Duodenum |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Antral pad sign = pancreatic head mass until proven otherwise.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn multiphasic CT, a pancreatic head mass typically appears as a hypodense or heterogeneously enhancing lesion, often with associated pancreatic duct and common bile duct dilatation (double duct sign). Intraoperatively, a firm, often ill-defined mass would be palpable in the head of the pancreas, compressing the duodenum.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for Pancreatic Adenocarcinoma (2023): Recommends multiphasic CT or MRI for diagnosis and staging, with EUS for further characterization and biopsy.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | In which condition barium series shows antral pad sign? | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Carcinoma periampullary region | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Carcinoma head of pancreas | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Carcinoma of terminal end of common bile duct | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: ?) C) Carcinoma head of pancreas** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Competency 2500**\n"
