  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When cancer goes rogue, chemotherapy is the systemic hero.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe statement 'Chemotherapy is the treatment of choice' indicates that for a specific disease, often a systemic malignancy, chemotherapy is considered the primary and most effective therapeutic modality. This decision is based on disease characteristics, stage, patient factors, and evidence-based guidelines.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nChemotherapy involves the use of cytotoxic drugs to destroy cancer cells or slow their growth. Its excellence lies in its systemic reach, making it effective for metastatic disease or cancers where local treatments (surgery, radiation) are insufficient. The mechanism often targets rapidly dividing cells, interfering with DNA replication, transcription, or protein synthesis, leading to apoptosis or cell cycle arrest. Its 'treatment of choice' status is earned when it offers the best chance for cure, significant palliation, or disease control, often in combination with other modalities.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): This option, 'Osmotic gradient,' is a physiological concept unrelated to chemotherapy as a treatment choice.\nOption B (Incorrect): This option, 'Seat belt syndrome is injury to the,' is an incomplete statement describing a traumatic injury, not relevant to chemotherapy.\nOption C (Incorrect): This option, 'Liver\tB. Small bowel,' lists anatomical structures and is not applicable to the verified answer regarding chemotherapy.\nOption D (Incorrect): This option, 'C. Large bowel\tD. Mesentery,' also lists anatomical structures and is not relevant to the verified answer.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Treatment Modality | Primary Indication | Mechanism of Action |\n| :----------------- | :----------------- | :------------------ |\n| Chemotherapy       | Systemic malignancy, adjuvant/neoadjuvant therapy | Cytotoxic drugs targeting rapidly dividing cells |\n| Radiation Therapy  | Localized tumors, palliation | High-energy particles/waves damaging DNA |\n| Surgery            | Resectable solid tumors, diagnosis | Physical removal of diseased tissue |\n| Immunotherapy      | Various advanced cancers (e.g., melanoma, lung) | Enhances body's immune response against cancer cells |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Chemotherapy is systemic; surgery/radiation are local. Choose wisely.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nImaging (CT, MRI, PET) often reveals the extent of disease (e.g., metastatic lesions) that necessitates systemic chemotherapy. Intraoperatively, unresectable disease or positive margins may prompt adjuvant chemotherapy.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Clinical Practice Guidelines in Oncology (various years): These guidelines provide comprehensive, evidence-based recommendations for the diagnosis and treatment of nearly all cancer types, often detailing when chemotherapy is the treatment of choice.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Osmotic gradient. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Seat belt syndrome is injury to the | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Liver\tB. Small bowel | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | C. Large bowel\tD. Mesentery | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: ?) Chemotherapy is the treatment of choice** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Competency 2500**\n"
