  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Lymphadenitis: When the nodes are inflamed, but the knife's not claimed.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is D: Bed rest. Acute non-specific ileocaecal mesenteric lymphadenitis is a self-limiting inflammatory condition, often viral, that typically resolves spontaneously with conservative management. Surgical intervention or antibiotics are generally not indicated unless complications arise or a specific bacterial etiology is identified.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nMesenteric lymphadenitis involves inflammation of the lymph nodes in the mesentery, particularly in the ileocaecal region. It often presents with right lower quadrant pain, mimicking appendicitis, but without the progressive signs of peritonitis or systemic toxicity. The body's immune system usually clears the infection or inflammation on its own, making supportive care, including bed rest and analgesia, the cornerstone of treatment.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Immediate laparotomy is an invasive surgical procedure reserved for acute surgical emergencies like appendicitis or peritonitis. It is not indicated for a self-limiting inflammatory condition like mesenteric lymphadenitis.\nOption B (Incorrect): Appendicectomy is the surgical removal of the appendix, indicated for acute appendicitis. While mesenteric lymphadenitis can mimic appendicitis, if appendicitis is ruled out (e.g., by imaging or observation), appendicectomy is unnecessary and exposes the patient to surgical risks.\nOption C (Incorrect): Antibiotics are typically used to treat bacterial infections. Acute non-specific mesenteric lymphadenitis is often viral in origin or self-limiting, and antibiotics are generally not effective or necessary unless a specific bacterial pathogen is identified.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Condition | Etiology | Key Features | Management |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Acute Appendicitis | Luminal obstruction (fecalith, lymphoid hyperplasia) | RLQ pain, anorexia, nausea, vomiting, fever, rebound tenderness | Appendicectomy |\n| Mesenteric Lymphadenitis | Viral (common), bacterial, inflammatory | RLQ pain, fever, often preceded by URI, self-limiting | Supportive care (bed rest, analgesia) |\n| Meckel's Diverticulitis | Inflammation of Meckel's diverticulum | Mimics appendicitis, often painless rectal bleeding in children | Surgical resection if symptomatic/complicated |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: RLQ pain? Rule out appendicitis, then consider self-limiting causes.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound or CT, enlarged mesenteric lymph nodes (>5-10mm in short axis) in the right lower quadrant, often clustered, with a normal appendix. Bowel wall thickening may also be present. Intraoperatively (if explored), a normal appendix with enlarged, inflamed mesenteric lymph nodes.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nWorld Society of Emergency Surgery (WSES) Guidelines for the Management of Acute Appendicitis (2020) recommend considering mesenteric lymphadenitis as a differential diagnosis in patients presenting with right lower quadrant pain, especially in children, and advocate for conservative management if appendicitis is ruled out.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Immediate laparotomy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Appendicectomy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Antibiotics | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Bed rest | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: ?) Peristaltic movement of bowel** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Competency 2500**\n"
