  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When RIF calcifications appear, think TB, not just stones or scars!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nACCEPT. The correct answer is Tuberculous mesenteric lymphadenitis. The combination of chronic systemic symptoms (weight loss, appetite loss), vague abdominal pain, and calcified shadows in the right iliac fossa in a child strongly points to this diagnosis.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nTuberculous mesenteric lymphadenitis is a common extrapulmonary manifestation of tuberculosis, particularly in endemic areas and in children. The characteristic calcified shadows seen on plain radiographs represent healed or chronic granulomatous inflammation within the mesenteric lymph nodes, a hallmark of the body's immune response to Mycobacterium tuberculosis. The insidious onset of weight loss, anorexia, and vague abdominal pain reflects the chronic inflammatory nature of the disease, often preceding significant acute symptoms. The right iliac fossa is a common location due to the rich lymphatic drainage of the ileocecal region, a frequent site of primary intestinal TB infection.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Ileocaecal nonspecific lymphadenitis) (Incorrect): This is typically an acute, self-limiting condition, often viral, and does not usually present with calcified lymph nodes or chronic systemic symptoms like significant weight loss.\nOption B (Ileocaecal malignancy) (Incorrect): While malignancy can cause weight loss, it is exceedingly rare in a 10-year-old, and calcification in this context is atypical for primary ileocecal malignancy.\nOption D (Chronic appendicitis) (Incorrect): Chronic appendicitis is a controversial diagnosis, and while it can cause vague RIF pain, it does not typically present with calcified mesenteric lymph nodes or significant systemic symptoms like weight loss and appetite loss.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Tuberculous Mesenteric Lymphadenitis | Acute Mesenteric Lymphadenitis | Chronic Appendicitis |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Etiology** | Mycobacterium tuberculosis | Viral (e.g., Yersinia, adenovirus) | Obstructive (fecalith, lymphoid hyperplasia) |\n| **Symptoms** | Chronic weight loss, anorexia, vague pain, fever | Acute RIF pain, fever, vomiting, diarrhea | Vague, intermittent RIF pain |\n| **Imaging** | Calcified mesenteric nodes, enlarged nodes (CT) | Enlarged, non-calcified nodes (US/CT) | Dilated appendix, appendicolith (CT) |\n| **Course** | Chronic, progressive if untreated | Self-limiting, acute | Intermittent, can lead to acute appendicitis |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Calcified RIF nodes + chronic systemic symptoms in a child = TB until proven otherwise.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn plain radiograph, calcified shadows in the RIF are highly suggestive. CT scan would confirm enlarged, often centrally necrotic or calcified mesenteric lymph nodes, sometimes with associated bowel wall thickening. Intraoperatively, one might find enlarged, firm, matted lymph nodes, possibly with caseous material upon incision, and occasionally peritoneal tubercles.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nWHO Guidelines for the programmatic management of drug-resistant tuberculosis (2020 Update) recommends diagnostic algorithms and treatment regimens for all forms of TB, including extrapulmonary manifestations like abdominal TB.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Ileocaecal nonspecific lymphadenitis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Ileocaecal malignancy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Tuberculous mesenteric lymphadenitis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Chronic appendicitis | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: ?) Mesentery** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Competency 2500**\n"
