  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Big adenoids block breathing, not rot teeth.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe question asks to identify the symptom *not* caused by enlarged adenoids. While enlarged adenoids are a common cause of upper airway obstruction and related issues in children, dental caries is a distinct pathology unrelated to adenoid size.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nEnlarged adenoids, located in the nasopharynx, can obstruct the posterior nasal airway. This obstruction is a primary cause of obstructive sleep apnea (OSA) in children, leading to mouth breathing and disturbed sleep. Chronic inflammation of the adenoids can also result in increased mucus production and postnasal discharge. In severe cases, very large adenoids can mechanically interfere with the soft palate or pharyngeal function, contributing to dysphagia. However, dental caries is a multifactorial disease primarily caused by bacterial fermentation of dietary sugars, leading to acid production and tooth demineralization, with no direct anatomical or physiological link to adenoid hypertrophy.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Obstructive sleep apnoea. Enlarged adenoids are a leading cause of OSA in children due to physical obstruction of the nasopharyngeal airway.\nOption C (Incorrect): Postnasal discharge. Chronic inflammation and increased mucus production associated with adenoid hypertrophy commonly lead to postnasal drip.\nOption D (Incorrect): Dysphagia. While less common than respiratory symptoms, significantly enlarged adenoids can mechanically impede swallowing or alter pharyngeal dynamics, causing dysphagia.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Symptom | Relation to Adenoid Hypertrophy | Mechanism |\n|---|---|---|\n| Obstructive Sleep Apnoea | Direct cause | Physical obstruction of nasopharynx |\n| Postnasal Discharge | Direct cause | Chronic inflammation, increased mucus production |\n| Dysphagia | Possible cause | Mechanical interference with swallowing, altered pharyngeal dynamics |\n| Dental Caries | No direct relation | Bacterial acid production, dietary factors |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Adenoid hypertrophy causes airway obstruction, not tooth decay.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn a lateral neck X-ray, enlarged adenoids appear as a soft tissue mass in the posterior nasopharynx, narrowing the airway. Flexible nasopharyngoscopy provides direct visualization of the hypertrophied lymphoid tissue obstructing the choanae. Intraoperatively, during adenoidectomy, the prominent lymphoid tissue is seen filling the nasopharyngeal vault.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Academy of Otolaryngology—Head and Neck Surgery (AAO-HNS) Clinical Practice Guideline: Tonsillectomy in Children (2019). This guideline discusses adenotonsillectomy as a primary treatment for pediatric obstructive sleep apnea, a key symptom of adenoid hypertrophy.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Enlargement of adenoids can cause the following except | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Obstructive sleep apnoea | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Postnasal discharge | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Dysphagia | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: ?) Dental caries** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Competency 2500**\n"
