  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Sjögren's: dry, dangerous, and decidedly female.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe question asks to identify the statement that is NOT true regarding secondary Sjögren’s syndrome. Sialectasis, while a finding in some salivary gland pathologies, is not a defining or universally true characteristic of secondary Sjögren's syndrome, unlike the other options which are classic features.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nSecondary Sjögren’s syndrome is an autoimmune exocrinopathy characterized by chronic lymphocytic infiltration and destruction of exocrine glands, primarily the lacrimal and salivary glands, leading to sicca symptoms. It is termed 'secondary' when it occurs in conjunction with another autoimmune connective tissue disease, such as rheumatoid arthritis or systemic lupus erythematosus. The immune-mediated glandular dysfunction and destruction are the core pathology, leading to the classic symptoms and increased lymphoma risk. Sialectasis, which is dilation of salivary ducts, can be seen in chronic inflammatory conditions of the salivary glands but is not a primary diagnostic criterion or a universal feature of Sjögren's syndrome itself.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Keratoconjunctivitis sicca (dry eyes) is a hallmark symptom of Sjögren’s syndrome due to immune-mediated destruction of the lacrimal glands.\nOption B (Incorrect): Xerostomia (dry mouth) is a hallmark symptom of Sjögren’s syndrome due to immune-mediated destruction of the salivary glands.\nOption C (Incorrect): Sjögren’s syndrome predominantly affects females, with a female-to-male ratio of approximately 9:1, making this a true statement.\nOption D (Incorrect): Patients with Sjögren’s syndrome have a significantly increased risk (15-20 times) of developing B-cell non-Hodgkin lymphoma, particularly MALT lymphoma, making this a true statement.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Primary Sjögren's Syndrome | Secondary Sjögren's Syndrome |\n|---|---|---|\n| Definition | Sicca symptoms without associated CTD | Sicca symptoms with associated CTD (e.g., RA, SLE) |\n| Autoantibodies | Anti-Ro/SSA, Anti-La/SSB | Anti-Ro/SSA, Anti-La/SSB (often higher titers) |\n| Lymphoma Risk | Increased | Increased (similar or slightly higher) |\n| Systemic Manifestations | Can occur (arthralgia, fatigue) | Often overshadowed by associated CTD |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Sjögren's: dry eyes, dry mouth, high lymphoma risk, mostly women.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn minor salivary gland biopsy (lip biopsy), you would see focal lymphocytic sialadenitis. Sialography or ultrasound might show ductal dilation (sialectasis) in chronic sialadenitis, but in Sjögren's, imaging often reveals glandular atrophy or fatty replacement.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Rheumatology (ACR) / European League Against Rheumatism (EULAR) Classification Criteria for Primary Sjögren’s Syndrome (2016). These criteria recommend diagnosis based on objective signs of sicca, serology (anti-Ro/SSA), and minor salivary gland biopsy.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | The patients have keratoconjunctivitis sicca | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | The have xerostomia | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Majority are females | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Higher risk of developing lymphomas | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: ?) Sialectasis** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Competency 2500**\n"
