  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Resuscitate early and aggressively; burns are a fluid drain.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe verdict is hypovolaemic shock. This is the primary cause of death in the immediate post-burn period (within 48 hours) due to massive fluid shifts and capillary leak.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nSevere burns cause widespread capillary permeability, leading to a rapid loss of plasma volume into the interstitial space, forming edema. This fluid shift, combined with evaporative losses from the denuded skin, results in profound hypovolemia. Without adequate fluid resuscitation, cardiac output falls, leading to organ hypoperfusion and ultimately hypovolemic shock and death.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Septic shock is a common cause of death in burns, but typically occurs later, usually after 48-72 hours, due to infection of the burn wound.\nOption C (Incorrect): Neurogenic shock results from spinal cord injury or severe neurological trauma, causing loss of sympathetic tone, and is not directly caused by burns.\nOption D (Incorrect): Vasovagal shock is a transient reflex response leading to bradycardia and hypotension, not the sustained, massive fluid loss seen in severe burns.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Cause of Death | Timeframe | Mechanism |\n|---|---|---|\n| Hypovolemic Shock | < 48 hours | Massive fluid loss from capillary leak and evaporation |\n| Septic Shock | > 48-72 hours | Infection of burn wound, systemic inflammatory response |\n| Multi-organ Failure | Late | Consequence of prolonged shock, sepsis, or inhalation injury |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Early burn death = hypovolemic shock. Late burn death = septic shock.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIn the OR, one would observe significant edema in burned tissues, potentially requiring escharotomies to relieve compartment syndrome, indicating massive fluid shifts.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Burn Association (ABA) Practice Guidelines for Burn Care (e.g., 2018). These guidelines emphasize aggressive fluid resuscitation using formulas like Parkland to prevent hypovolemic shock.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Septic shock | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | hypovolaemic shock | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Neurogenic shock | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Vasovagal shock | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: ?) 5–8 cm of saline** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Competency 2500**\n"
