  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Burns: Early fluid, late bugs, always vigilant.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer to the question, \"What is the cause of death in burns after 7–10 days?\" is C, Warm shock. After the initial hypovolemic phase, burn patients are highly susceptible to infection due to compromised skin barrier and immunosuppression, leading to sepsis and subsequent septic shock, often characterized by a hyperdynamic 'warm' phase.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nIn severe burns, the extensive loss of skin integrity creates a massive portal for bacterial entry. This, coupled with burn-induced immunosuppression, predisposes patients to systemic infection. Sepsis progresses to septic shock, which in its early, hyperdynamic phase, presents as 'warm shock' with vasodilation, increased cardiac output, and decreased systemic vascular resistance. This profound inflammatory response and organ dysfunction are the leading causes of mortality in the subacute phase (7-10 days post-burn).\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Hypovolaemic shock is the primary cause of death in the immediate post-burn period (first 24-48 hours) due to massive fluid shifts and plasma loss, not typically after 7-10 days.\nOption B (Incorrect): Cardiogenic shock is rare as a primary cause of death in burns unless there is pre-existing severe cardiac disease or direct myocardial injury from electrical burns. It's not a typical late complication.\nOption D (Incorrect): Neurogenic shock results from severe spinal cord injury or central nervous system damage, leading to loss of sympathetic tone. It is unrelated to the pathophysiology of burn injury mortality.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Type of Shock | Primary Cause in Burns | Timing Post-Burn | Key Features |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Hypovolemic Shock | Massive fluid/plasma loss | Early (0-48 hours) | Tachycardia, hypotension, low CVP, cool extremities |\n| Septic Shock (Warm Shock) | Infection, systemic inflammatory response | Late (7-10+ days) | Tachycardia, hypotension, high cardiac output, warm extremities (early) |\n| Cardiogenic Shock | Pre-existing cardiac disease, direct injury | Variable | Hypotension, low cardiac output, elevated CVP, pulmonary edema |\n| Neurogenic Shock | Spinal cord injury | N/A (not burn-related) | Bradycardia, hypotension, warm extremities |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Think 'fluid first, then bugs' for burn mortality timeline.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn imaging, a septic burn patient might show signs of pneumonia (infiltrates on CXR), abscess formation (CT), or osteomyelitis (MRI) if the infection has spread. Intraoperatively, one might see purulent exudate, necrotic tissue, or signs of fasciitis requiring aggressive debridement.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Burn Association (ABA) Practice Guidelines for Burn Care (e.g., 2018). These guidelines emphasize early excision and grafting, infection control, and aggressive resuscitation to prevent sepsis.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Hypovolaemic shock | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Cardiogenic shock | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Warm shock | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Neurogenic shock | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: ?) 12. <500 ml/day in adults** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Competency 2500**\n"
