  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 DKA: When sugar's high, acid's too, and pH says 'boo hoo!'**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe verified answer, Metabolic acidosis, is correct because diabetic ketoacidosis (DKA) is a severe and common complication of uncontrolled diabetes mellitus. DKA is characterized by a high anion gap metabolic acidosis due to the accumulation of ketone bodies.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nIn states of severe insulin deficiency, the body cannot utilize glucose for energy, leading to increased lipolysis and fatty acid oxidation. This process generates an excess of ketone bodies (beta-hydroxybutyrate and acetoacetate), which are strong acids. Their accumulation overwhelms the body's buffering systems, resulting in a significant decrease in blood pH and bicarbonate levels, defining a high anion gap metabolic acidosis.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Respiratory acidosis): Incorrect. This is caused by hypoventilation leading to CO2 retention, not a direct complication of diabetes.\nOption C (Respiratory alkalosis): Incorrect. This is caused by hyperventilation leading to excessive CO2 exhalation. While compensatory hyperventilation (Kussmaul breathing) can occur in metabolic acidosis, it is not the primary complication of diabetes itself.\nOption D (Metabolic alkalosis): Incorrect. This is caused by excessive loss of acid (e.g., vomiting) or gain of alkali, which is not a direct complication of diabetes.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Type                 | Primary Cause                                  | pH       | HCO3-    | pCO2     |\n| :------------------- | :--------------------------------------------- | :------- | :------- | :------- |\n| Metabolic Acidosis   | DKA, Lactic Acidosis, Renal Failure            | Decreased | Decreased | Decreased (compensatory) |\n| Respiratory Acidosis | Hypoventilation (e.g., COPD, opioid overdose)  | Decreased | Increased (compensatory) | Increased |\n| Metabolic Alkalosis  | Vomiting, Diuretic use, Hyperaldosteronism     | Increased | Increased | Increased (compensatory) |\n| Respiratory Alkalosis| Hyperventilation (e.g., anxiety, high altitude)| Increased | Decreased (compensatory) | Decreased |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: DKA = high anion gap metabolic acidosis.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nImaging is not directly diagnostic for metabolic acidosis; however, CT/X-ray may reveal precipitating factors like pneumonia or cerebral edema in severe DKA.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Diabetes Association (ADA) Standards of Medical Care in Diabetes - 2024. Recommends prompt recognition and management of DKA, including correction of acidosis.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Respiratory acidosis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Metabolic acidosis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Respiratory alkalosis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Metabolic alkalosis | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: ?) B) Metabolic acidosis** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Competency 2500**\n"
