  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Trigeminal nerve: The face's feeling, the jaw's force.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe provided question 'Upper end of tibia' and the given options are entirely incongruent with the verified answer 'Trigeminal nerve'. Assuming 'Trigeminal nerve' is the correct answer to an unstated question, it refers to the fifth cranial nerve, vital for facial sensation and mastication.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe trigeminal nerve (CN V) is the largest cranial nerve, responsible for sensory innervation of the face and motor innervation of the muscles of mastication. Its three main divisions—ophthalmic (V1), maxillary (V2), and mandibular (V3)—are crucial for facial sensation, corneal reflex, and chewing, making it a cornerstone of neurological assessment.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): 'Hemorrhagic shock' is a systemic circulatory condition, completely unrelated to the Trigeminal nerve.\nOption B (Incorrect): 'The complicatios of sebacious cyst are the following except' is an incomplete and irrelevant statement, bearing no relation to neuroanatomy.\nOption C (Incorrect): 'Infection' is a broad pathological process, not a specific anatomical structure like the Trigeminal nerve.\nOption D (Incorrect): 'Sebacious horn' is a dermatological lesion, entirely unrelated to cranial nerve anatomy.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Description | Clinical Relevance |\n|---|---|---|\n| Type | Mixed (Sensory & Motor) | Essential for facial sensation and chewing |\n| Divisions | Ophthalmic (V1), Maxillary (V2), Mandibular (V3) | Each division has distinct sensory and motor functions |\n| Sensory Function | Face, scalp, oral cavity, nasal cavity, dura mater | Trigeminal neuralgia, corneal reflex |\n| Motor Function | Muscles of mastication (e.g., temporalis, masseter) | Jaw clenching, chewing |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Trigeminal nerve: V1, V2, V3 for face sensation and mastication.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn MRI, the trigeminal nerve can be visualized emerging from the pons, traversing the Meckel's cave, and dividing into its three main branches, crucial for identifying pathologies like compression or tumors.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Academy of Neurology (AAN) 2014 Guideline: Recommends carbamazepine and oxcarbazepine as first-line treatments for trigeminal neuralgia.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Hemorrhagic shock | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | The complicatios of sebacious cyst are the following except | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Infection | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Sebacious horn | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: ?) Trigeminal nerve** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Competency 2500**\n"
