  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Slip sign: the tell-tale wiggle of a lipoma.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe verdict is that a Lipoma is the swelling that characteristically slips under the examining finger. This clinical finding, known as the 'slip sign' or 'couching sign,' is a hallmark of these benign fatty tumors due to their soft, mobile nature and lack of deep attachment.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe 'slip sign' is a classic diagnostic maneuver for lipomas. When the examiner's finger attempts to push the lipoma, it tends to 'slip' or 'couch' away from the pressure, moving freely within the subcutaneous tissue. This occurs because lipomas are typically well-encapsulated, composed of soft adipose tissue, and are not tethered to the overlying skin or underlying fascia. This mobility and the characteristic slipping sensation are crucial for differentiating lipomas from other subcutaneous masses during physical examination.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Cystic hygroma) (Incorrect): These are lymphatic malformations, often soft and compressible, but typically diffuse or more deeply seated, making a distinct 'slip sign' less common.\nOption B (Branchial cyst) (Incorrect): These congenital neck cysts are usually fluctuant but often fixed to deeper structures or overlying skin, limiting their mobility and preventing a slip sign.\nOption C (Dermoid cyst) (Incorrect): Dermoid cysts are developmental cysts, often firm and frequently fixed to underlying periosteum or skin, thus they do not typically exhibit the slip sign.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Swelling Type | Consistency | Mobility/Slip Sign | Key Differentiating Feature |\n| :------------ | :---------- | :----------------- | :-------------------------- |\n| Lipoma        | Soft, rubbery | Present (slips)    | Encapsulated fatty tissue   |\n| Sebaceous Cyst | Firm, fluctuant | Absent/Limited     | Punctum often present       |\n| Lymph Node    | Firm, rubbery | Mobile (rolls)     | Often multiple, tender if inflamed |\n| Dermoid Cyst  | Firm          | Absent/Fixed       | Often midline, fixed to bone |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Lipomas slip and slide, a fatty friend you can't hide.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound, a lipoma typically appears as a well-circumscribed, ovoid, hyperechoic mass with internal linear echoes parallel to the skin, and is compressible. Intraoperatively, it is a yellowish, lobulated, encapsulated mass that easily shells out from surrounding tissue.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Academy of Dermatology (AAD) Guidelines for the Management of Benign Skin Lesions (e.g., 2019). Recommends excision for symptomatic or cosmetically bothersome lipomas, with clinical diagnosis often sufficient.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Cystic hygroma | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Branchial cyst | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Dermoid cyst | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Lipoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: ?) Diabetes mellitus** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Competency 2500**\n"
