  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Keratin blocks the light, epidermoid's might!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Epidermoid cyst. This answer is correct because epidermoid cysts are filled with thick, keratinaceous debris, which is opaque and prevents the transmission of light during a transillumination test, resulting in a negative finding.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe transillumination test is a simple clinical maneuver used to differentiate fluid-filled cysts from solid masses or cysts with turbid contents. It relies on the principle that clear, serous fluid allows light to pass through, while solid tissue or thick, opaque fluid blocks light. Epidermoid cysts are benign lesions lined by stratified squamous epithelium that continuously desquamates keratin and cellular debris into the cyst lumen. This accumulation creates a thick, pasty, or cheesy material that is inherently opaque, thus blocking the light and yielding a negative transillumination result.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Thyroglossal cyst) (Incorrect): These cysts typically contain clear to mucoid fluid, which often allows for positive transillumination.\nOption C (Branchial cyst) (Incorrect): Branchial cleft cysts usually contain clear, serous, or mucoid fluid, making them typically positive for transillumination.\nOption D (Cystic hygroma) (Incorrect): Cystic hygromas (lymphatic malformations) are filled with clear lymphatic fluid and are characteristically strongly positive for transillumination.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Cyst Type | Typical Contents | Transillumination | Common Location |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Epidermoid Cyst | Keratin, cellular debris (thick, opaque) | Negative | Face, neck, scalp, trunk |\n| Thyroglossal Cyst | Mucoid fluid (clear to slightly turbid) | Positive (variable) | Midline neck, near hyoid bone |\n| Branchial Cyst | Serous/mucoid fluid (clear to yellowish) | Positive | Lateral neck, anterior to SCM |\n| Cystic Hygroma | Lymphatic fluid (clear) | Strongly Positive | Posterior triangle of neck, axilla |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Opaque contents block light; clear fluid transmits.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound, epidermoid cysts often appear as well-circumscribed, hypoechoic masses with internal echoes due to the keratin debris. Intraoperatively, they are typically filled with thick, white, 'cheesy' material.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Academy of Otolaryngology–Head and Neck Surgery (AAO-HNS) Clinical Practice Guideline: Evaluation of Neck Masses in Children (2019). This guideline emphasizes thorough clinical examination and imaging for neck masses, where transillumination can be a helpful adjunct.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Epidermoid cyst | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Thyroglossal cyst | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Branchial cyst | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Cystic hygroma | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: ?) Nape of neck** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Competency 2500**\n"
