  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Keratin's soft touch: the epidermoid's pseudofluctuation.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is A) Epidermoid cyst. Pseudofluctuation is a classic clinical sign associated with epidermoid cysts, distinguishing them from truly fluid-filled or solid masses.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nEpidermoid cysts are benign lesions lined by stratified squamous epithelium, filled with a cheesy, semi-solid mixture of keratin and desquamated epithelial cells. This unique content gives the cyst a soft, doughy, or yielding feel on palpation, mimicking the sensation of fluid (fluctuation) but without being truly liquid. This characteristic 'pseudofluctuation' is a key diagnostic clue, indicating the presence of this specific keratinous material rather than a simple serous or mucinous fluid.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Dermoid cysts are similar to epidermoid cysts but contain other dermal adnexal structures like hair follicles and sebaceous glands. While they can feel soft, pseudofluctuation is more classically described for the pure keratin content of epidermoids.\nOption C (Incorrect): Thyroglossal cysts are typically fluid-filled (mucinous) and would exhibit true fluctuation, not pseudofluctuation. They are also characterized by movement with tongue protrusion.\nOption D (Incorrect): Lipomas are benign fatty tumors. They are soft, mobile, and often lobulated, but they are solid masses of fat and do not exhibit fluctuation or pseudofluctuation.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Epidermoid Cyst | Dermoid Cyst | Lipoma | Thyroglossal Duct Cyst |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| Origin | Trapped epidermal cells | Congenital inclusion of ectoderm/mesoderm | Mature adipocytes | Remnant of thyroglossal duct |\n| Contents | Keratin, desquamated epithelium | Keratin, hair, sebaceous material, other adnexa | Mature fat | Mucinous fluid |\n| Palpation | Pseudofluctuant, doughy | Soft to firm, can be doughy | Soft, mobile, lobulated | Fluctuant |\n| Key Clinical Sign | Pseudofluctuation | Can be deeper, more complex | \"Slipping sign\" | Moves with tongue protrusion |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Pseudofluctuation = keratin-filled epidermoid cyst.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound, epidermoid cysts appear as well-circumscribed, often hypoechoic lesions with internal echoes from keratin. Intraoperatively, incision reveals a characteristic white, cheesy, often malodorous keratinous material.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Academy of Dermatology (AAD) Position Statement on the Management of Benign Cutaneous Lesions (2019). It recommends excision for symptomatic or cosmetically bothersome lesions, with complete removal of the cyst wall to prevent recurrence.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Epidermoid cyst | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Dermoid cyst | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Thyroglossal cyst | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Lipoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: ?) A) Epidermoid cyst** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Competency 2500**\n"
