  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 White patch, can't scrape? Biopsy it, don't wait!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nLeukoplakia is the correct answer for a nonulcerating epithelioma. This condition presents as a white patch or plaque on a mucous membrane that cannot be scraped off and is not attributable to any other definable disease. It represents an epithelial change, often dysplastic, and is considered a potentially malignant disorder.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nLeukoplakia is a clinical diagnosis of exclusion, meaning other white lesions must be ruled out first. Histologically, it is characterized by hyperkeratosis, acanthosis, and varying degrees of epithelial dysplasia, which are changes within the epithelial layer. The 'nonulcerating' aspect is key, as ulceration often signifies more advanced or invasive squamous cell carcinoma, making early detection of nonulcerating leukoplakia critical for preventing malignant transformation.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): \"What is the most common cause of Osler’s nodes in fingers?\" This is a question about a different clinical sign (Osler's nodes, associated with endocarditis) and is not an answer to \"Nonulcerating epithelioma.\" \nOption B (Incorrect): Systemic lupus erythematosus (SLE) is an autoimmune disease with diverse mucocutaneous manifestations, but it does not directly describe a \"nonulcerating epithelioma\" like leukoplakia. \nOption C (Incorrect): Subacute bacterial endocarditis (SBE) is an infection of the heart valves, presenting with systemic symptoms and peripheral stigmata, not a \"nonulcerating epithelioma.\" \nOption D (Incorrect): Enteric fever (Typhoid fever) is a systemic bacterial infection with characteristic symptoms like fever and rash, unrelated to a \"nonulcerating epithelioma.\"\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Condition | Description | Malignant Potential | Key Feature |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Leukoplakia | White patch, cannot be scraped off | Premalignant (up to 20% transform) | Clinical diagnosis of exclusion, biopsy essential |\n| Erythroplakia | Red patch, velvety | Higher (up to 90% transform) | Always considered severe dysplasia/carcinoma until proven otherwise |\n| Oral Lichen Planus | White lacy pattern (Wickham's striae) or erosions | Small (~1%) | Autoimmune, often bilateral, can be painful |\n| Oral Candidiasis | White patches, *can* be scraped off | None | Fungal infection, often associated with immunosuppression |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Leukoplakia: white patch, can't scrape, must biopsy to rule out cancer.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn intraoperative inspection or during biopsy, leukoplakia appears as a distinct white, often thickened, non-scrapable plaque on the mucosal surface. It may be homogenous or speckled, and its texture can range from smooth to verrucous. Imaging like CT/MRI is typically used for staging if malignancy is confirmed, not for initial diagnosis of leukoplakia itself.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nThe World Health Organization (WHO) Classification of Head and Neck Tumours (5th Edition, 2022) defines leukoplakia as a \"white plaque of questionable risk having excluded (other) known diseases or disorders that carry no increased risk for cancer.\" It recommends histological assessment for dysplasia to guide management.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | What is the most common cause of Osler’s nodes in fingers? | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Systemic lupus erthematosus | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Subacute bacterial endocarditis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Enteric fever | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: ?) Leukoplakia** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Competency 2500**\n"
