  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 UC: Chronic inflammation, cancer risk is real, not a myth!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe verdict is that \"Never leads to carcinoma colon\" is the incorrect statement regarding histopathological findings in ulcerative colitis. This is because ulcerative colitis is a well-established risk factor for colorectal cancer, making the statement false.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nUlcerative colitis (UC) is a chronic inflammatory condition primarily affecting the colon, characterized by continuous inflammation extending proximally from the rectum. The chronic inflammation and cycles of mucosal damage and regeneration in UC lead to dysplasia and an increased risk of developing colorectal carcinoma. This risk is proportional to the duration, extent, and severity of the disease, necessitating regular surveillance colonoscopies with biopsies.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Multiple minute ulcers in the colonic mucosa are a characteristic feature of active ulcerative colitis, reflecting the superficial nature of the inflammation.\nOption B (Incorrect): Pseudopolyps are common in chronic ulcerative colitis, forming as islands of regenerating mucosa surrounded by ulcerated areas.\nOption D (Incorrect): Crypt abscesses, which are collections of neutrophils within the crypt lumina, are a classic and diagnostically important histological finding in active ulcerative colitis.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Ulcerative Colitis | Crohn's Disease |\n|---|---|---|\n| Location | Continuous, rectum always involved, extends proximally | Skip lesions, any part of GI tract (mouth to anus), terminal ileum most common |\n| Inflammation | Mucosal and submucosal | Transmural |\n| Ulcers | Superficial, broad-based | Deep, knife-like, linear |\n| Granulomas | Absent | Present (non-caseating) in 50% |\n| Crypt Abscesses | Common | Less common |\n| Pseudopolyps | Common | Less common |\n| Cancer Risk | Increased | Increased (less than UC for colon cancer) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: UC: Continuous, Crypt abscesses, Cancer risk.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn endoscopy, active ulcerative colitis typically shows continuous erythema, granularity, friability, and loss of vascular pattern, often with mucopurulent exudate and superficial ulcerations. In chronic cases, pseudopolyps may be visible.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Gastroenterology (ACG) Clinical Guidelines: Ulcerative Colitis in Adults (2019). Recommends regular surveillance colonoscopy with biopsies for patients with long-standing UC to detect dysplasia and prevent colorectal cancer.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Multiple minute ulcers in the colonic mucosa | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Pseudopolyps may be seen in some cases | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Never leads to carcinoma colon | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Crypt abscess in lamina propria | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: ?) Primary resection and anastomosis** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Competency 2500**\n"
