  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Colostomy diarrhea: more proximal, more problems.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nACCEPT: \"Colostomy diarrhea\" refers to excessive liquid stool output from a colostomy, a significant post-operative complication. While the provided question \"Large bowel obstruction\" is a clinical condition, a colostomy can be a surgical intervention for LBO, making colostomy diarrhea a relevant sequela.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nColostomy diarrhea arises from altered colonic function, particularly when a significant portion of the colon responsible for water and electrolyte absorption is bypassed or removed. Proximal colostomies (e.g., ascending or transverse) are more prone to high output due to less remaining absorptive surface. Factors like rapid transit, bacterial overgrowth, or underlying inflammatory conditions can exacerbate it. Management involves dietary modifications, anti-motility agents, and vigilant fluid and electrolyte balance.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): This option asks about iron absorption, which primarily occurs in the duodenum, and is unrelated to colostomy complications or large bowel obstruction.\nOption B (Incorrect): This option incorrectly lists stomach and duodenum for iron absorption, and is irrelevant to colostomy diarrhea.\nOption C (Incorrect): This option incorrectly lists jejunum and ileum for iron absorption, and is irrelevant to colostomy diarrhea.\nOption D (Incorrect): This option asks about vitamin absorption in the colon (primarily Vitamin K and some B vitamins), which is unrelated to colostomy diarrhea.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Type of Ostomy | Location | Typical Output Consistency | Key Complications |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Ileostomy | Ileum | Liquid to pasty | High output, dehydration, electrolyte imbalance, skin irritation |\n| Ascending Colostomy | Ascending colon | Liquid to semi-liquid | High output, dehydration, electrolyte imbalance |\n| Transverse Colostomy | Transverse colon | Semi-liquid to soft | Moderate output, skin irritation |\n| Descending/Sigmoid Colostomy | Descending/Sigmoid colon | Soft to formed | Constipation, skin irritation (less common for diarrhea) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Proximal colostomies have higher output and greater risk of dehydration.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn physical exam, a patient with colostomy diarrhea will present with frequent, watery stool output from the stoma, potentially leading to perianal skin excoriation. Intraoperatively, the surgeon would ensure adequate stoma creation and assess the remaining bowel length, which directly impacts potential for diarrhea.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Society of Colon and Rectal Surgeons (ASCRS) Clinical Practice Guidelines for Ostomy Management (2020). These guidelines recommend comprehensive pre-operative counseling and post-operative management strategies to prevent and treat ostomy-related complications, including high output and diarrhea.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Iron is absorbed in which part of the gastrointestinal tract? | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Stomach\tB. Duodenum | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | C. Jejunum\tD. Ileum | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Which vitamins are absorbed in the colon? | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: ?) Colostomy diarrhea** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Competency 2500**\n"
