  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Adrenal masses: Beyond hormones, think infiltrates!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe question, while phrased as 'Injury to left adrenal gland', likely serves as a prompt to consider differential diagnoses for an adrenal mass or pathology. Lymphoma is a recognized, albeit rare, cause of adrenal enlargement or mass, making it a correct answer in the context of adrenal pathology.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nAdrenal glands can be involved in lymphoma, either as a primary site (very rare) or, more commonly, as a site of secondary involvement in disseminated non-Hodgkin lymphoma. Lymphomatous infiltration can present as unilateral or bilateral adrenal masses, which may mimic other adrenal tumors, metastases, or even hemorrhage on imaging. Therefore, lymphoma is an important consideration in the differential diagnosis of an adrenal lesion, especially in patients with a known history of lymphoma or systemic symptoms.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): \"Which is the most serious complication of splenectomy?\" - This is a question about splenectomy complications, not an answer related to adrenal pathology.\nOption B (Incorrect): \"Haemorragic shock if delay in treatment\" - While adrenal injury can lead to hemorrhage and shock, this describes a general complication of severe bleeding, not a specific adrenal pathology or differential diagnosis like lymphoma.\nOption C (Incorrect): \"pancreatic fistula\" - This is a known complication of pancreatic surgery or trauma, entirely unrelated to adrenal gland pathology.\nOption D (Incorrect): \"Pseudoaneurysm of splenic artery\" - This is a complication typically associated with splenic or pancreatic trauma or surgery, bearing no direct relevance to adrenal gland pathology or lymphoma.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Adrenal Mass Type | Key Characteristics | Imaging Clues (CT) | Management Approach |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Adrenal Adenoma | Most common benign, often non-functional | Homogeneous, low attenuation (<10 HU) on non-contrast CT, rapid washout | Observation, functional workup if indicated |\n| Adrenal Carcinoma | Rare, aggressive, often large (>6cm), functional or non-functional | Heterogeneous, irregular margins, high attenuation, delayed washout, local invasion | Surgical resection, adjuvant therapy |\n| Adrenal Metastasis | Common, from lung, breast, kidney, melanoma | Variable appearance, often >3cm, can be bilateral | Biopsy if primary unknown, systemic therapy |\n| Adrenal Lymphoma | Rare primary, more common secondary | Variable, often homogeneous, can be bilateral, difficult to distinguish from other masses | Biopsy for diagnosis, chemotherapy/radiation |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: \"Adrenal masses demand a broad differential, including infiltrative diseases like lymphoma.\"\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT, adrenal lymphoma typically appears as a unilateral or bilateral, often homogeneous, soft tissue mass. It can be challenging to differentiate from other adrenal tumors or metastases without biopsy, which is often required for definitive diagnosis.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Association of Endocrine Surgeons (AAES) Guidelines for the Management of Adrenal Incidentalomas (2016): These guidelines provide a framework for evaluating adrenal masses, recommending biochemical workup for all incidentalomas and guiding decisions for imaging follow-up or surgical resection based on size and imaging characteristics.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Which is the most serious complication of splenectomy? | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Haemorragic shock if delay in treatment | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | pancreatic fistula | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Pseudoaneurysm of splenic artery | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: ?) Lymphoma** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Competency 2500**\n"
