  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Duodenal atresia: double bubble, surgical solution.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe question asks for the treatment of choice for duodenal atresia in a child. The correct approach is surgical correction, typically a duodenoduodenostomy, to relieve the congenital obstruction and restore intestinal continuity.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nDuodenal atresia is a congenital anomaly resulting from failed recanalization of the duodenum during fetal development, often presenting with bilious emesis and a classic 'double bubble' sign on imaging. Surgical intervention is paramount to bypass the obstruction, prevent aspiration, and ensure adequate nutrition. The procedure involves creating an anastomosis between the dilated proximal duodenum and the distal duodenum, often using a diamond-shaped or side-to-side technique to minimize the risk of blind loop syndrome.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nThe provided options (Typhoid fever, The splenic artery passes through the which ligament?, Short gastric ligament, Lienorenal ligament) are entirely unrelated to the treatment of duodenal atresia. Therefore, they are all incorrect in this context as they do not offer a relevant treatment option or diagnostic consideration for this condition.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Condition | Presentation | X-ray Finding | Treatment |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Duodenal Atresia | Bilious emesis, polyhydramnios | Double Bubble Sign | Duodenoduodenostomy |\n| Jejunoileal Atresia | Bilious emesis, abdominal distension | Multiple dilated loops, air-fluid levels | Resection & Primary Anastomosis |\n| Pyloric Stenosis | Non-bilious projectile emesis | 'String sign' or 'shoulder sign' on US | Pyloromyotomy |\n| Annular Pancreas | Bilious emesis (variable) | Double Bubble Sign | Duodenoduodenostomy |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Double bubble, double trouble, surgical fix is the goal!\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn plain abdominal X-ray, the classic 'double bubble' sign (dilated stomach and proximal duodenum) is pathognomonic. Intraoperatively, the atresia can be a complete membrane, a fibrous cord, or a gap, often located distal to the ampulla of Vater.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Academy of Pediatrics (AAP) Clinical Report 2019: Management of Neonates with Congenital Duodenal Obstruction. Recommends surgical correction (duodenoduodenostomy or duodenojejunostomy) once the neonate is stable and optimized.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Typhoid fever | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | The splenic artery passes through the which ligament? | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Short gastric ligament | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Lienorenal ligament | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: ?) What is the treatment of choice for duodenal atresia in a child?** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Competency 2500**\n"
