  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Spot it early, save a life, simple as that!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe verdict is 'Early diagnosis'. While the options describe the definition of early gastric cancer, the most critical factor for improving patient outcomes in gastric cancer, regardless of its specific definition, is its early detection.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nEarly diagnosis of gastric cancer is paramount because it allows for detection when the tumor is confined to the mucosa or submucosa, before lymph node metastasis or deeper invasion. This early stage, often termed 'early gastric cancer,' is amenable to endoscopic resection or limited surgical intervention, preserving gastric function and significantly improving 5-year survival rates from less than 30% for advanced disease to over 90%.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): 'Early gastric cancer is defined as' is an incomplete statement and not a definition itself.\nOption B (Incorrect): This option accurately describes the definition of early gastric cancer (invasion limited to mucosa and submucosa), but the question implicitly asks for the most critical factor for prognosis, which is early diagnosis, not the definition itself.\nOption C (Incorrect): Involvement of the muscular coat or lymph nodes signifies advanced gastric cancer, not early disease.\nOption D (Incorrect): Involvement of the muscular and serosal layers indicates advanced gastric cancer with a poorer prognosis, not early disease.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Early Gastric Cancer | Advanced Gastric Cancer | Importance of Early Diagnosis |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Definition** | Invasion limited to mucosa or submucosa, regardless of lymph node status | Invasion beyond submucosa into muscularis propria or deeper | Allows for detection at EGC stage |\n| **Treatment** | Endoscopic resection (EMR/ESD) or limited gastrectomy | Subtotal/total gastrectomy with lymphadenectomy, chemotherapy, radiation | Enables less invasive, curative treatments |\n| **Prognosis** | Excellent (5-year survival >90%) | Poor (5-year survival <30% for advanced stages) | Drastically improves survival and quality of life |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Early diagnosis is the cornerstone of gastric cancer survival.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn endoscopy, early gastric cancer may appear as subtle mucosal changes, slight elevations, depressions, or discoloration, often requiring chromoendoscopy or NBI for detection. Intraoperatively, these early lesions might not be palpable or grossly visible without prior endoscopic marking.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nJapanese Gastric Cancer Association (JGCA) Guidelines 2018: These guidelines emphasize the importance of screening and early detection programs, particularly in high-risk populations, to improve overall survival rates.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Early gastric cancer is defined as | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Involving mucosa and submucosa without lymph nodes | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Involving the muscular coat only and lymph nodes | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Involving the muscular and serosal layer | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: ?) Early diagnosis** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Competency 2500**\n"
