  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Perforated ulcer: a surgical emergency, not an NG tube challenge.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe verified answer, \"Easy passage of nasogastric tube,\" is indeed the correct exception. Perforated duodenal ulcer presents with acute peritonitis, but the perforation itself does not typically impede the passage of an NG tube. The other options are classic signs of diffuse peritonitis.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nPerforated duodenal ulcer is a surgical emergency characterized by the sudden release of gastric or duodenal contents into the peritoneal cavity. This leads to an immediate chemical peritonitis, rapidly evolving into bacterial peritonitis. The intense inflammation irritates the parietal peritoneum and diaphragm, causing severe pain, involuntary guarding (board-like rigidity), and rebound tenderness. Free air escaping into the peritoneal cavity results in pneumoperitoneum, classically manifesting as the absence of liver dullness on percussion.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Rebound tenderness) (Incorrect): This is a cardinal sign of peritoneal irritation and inflammation, which is profoundly present in perforated duodenal ulcer.\nOption B (Absence of liver dullness) (Incorrect): This is a classic sign of pneumoperitoneum, where free air from the perforated viscus accumulates under the diaphragm, displacing the liver and causing tympany on percussion.\nOption C (Board like rigidity) (Incorrect): This is the hallmark physical exam finding of diffuse peritonitis, an involuntary and sustained contraction of the abdominal wall muscles in response to severe peritoneal inflammation.\nOption D (Restlessness) (Incorrect): Patients experiencing severe, excruciating pain and potentially developing hypovolemic shock from peritonitis are often restless and agitated.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Clinical Feature | Description | Significance in Perforated Duodenal Ulcer |\n|-------------------|---------------------------------------------------|---------------------------------------------------------------------------------|\n| Sudden, severe pain | Abrupt onset of excruciating epigastric pain | Initial symptom due to chemical peritonitis from spillage |\n| Board-like rigidity | Involuntary, generalized abdominal wall guarding | Classic sign of diffuse peritonitis, indicating severe inflammation |\n| Absent liver dullness | Tympany over the right upper quadrant | Suggests pneumoperitoneum from free air under the diaphragm |\n| Rebound tenderness | Pain upon rapid release of abdominal pressure | Indicates peritoneal irritation and inflammation |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Perforated ulcer: sudden pain, rigid belly, air on X-ray.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn an upright chest X-ray, subdiaphragmatic free air (pneumoperitoneum) is seen in 70-80% of cases. Intraoperatively, a visible perforation, typically on the anterior wall of the duodenum, with surrounding inflammation and free bilious or purulent fluid in the peritoneal cavity, confirms the diagnosis.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nWorld Society of Emergency Surgery (WSES) Guidelines for the Management of Perforated Peptic Ulcer (2020) recommend early diagnosis and prompt surgical intervention, typically laparoscopic or open primary repair with omental patch.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Rebound tenderness | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Absence of liver dullness | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Board like rigidity | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Restlessness | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: ?) Easy passage of nasogastric tube** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Competency 2500**\n"
