  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't just treat the ulcer, biopsy the beast!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe verified answer, \"Malignant gastric ulcer,\" is correct because it represents a critical diagnosis in upper gastrointestinal pathology, often requiring biopsy for definitive identification. Unlike benign ulcers, malignant ulcers necessitate oncologic management due to their potential for metastasis and poor prognosis if untreated. This diagnosis highlights the importance of thorough investigation of all gastric ulcers.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nMalignant gastric ulcers typically arise from adenocarcinoma, often presenting as an ulcerated mass. Their pathogenesis involves chronic inflammation, H. pylori infection, and genetic factors leading to dysplastic changes. Endoscopic biopsy is crucial for diagnosis, as visual differentiation from benign ulcers can be challenging, relying on features like irregular borders, nodularity, and non-healing despite medical therapy. The depth of invasion determines staging and surgical resectability, making early and accurate diagnosis paramount.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (C. Dieulafoy’s disease D. Carcinoma stomach) (Incorrect): Dieulafoy's disease is a vascular anomaly causing bleeding, not an ulcer type. While carcinoma stomach is a broad category, \"Malignant gastric ulcer\" is a specific presentation, and the option is fragmented.\nOption B (Which is the most common cause of duodenal obstruction in adults?) (Incorrect): This is a question about duodenal obstruction, not an answer related to gastric ulcers.\nOption C (Annular pancreas B. Duodenal atresia) (Incorrect): These are causes of duodenal obstruction, primarily congenital, and are unrelated to gastric ulcers.\nOption D (C. Carcinoma of duodenum D. Carcinoma of pancreas) (Incorrect): These are malignant conditions but are located in the duodenum and pancreas, not the stomach, and are not specifically \"gastric ulcer.\"\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Benign Gastric Ulcer | Malignant Gastric Ulcer |\n|---|---|---|\n| Etiology | H. pylori, NSAIDs, stress | Adenocarcinoma (often H. pylori related), lymphoma |\n| Appearance | Smooth, regular borders, flat base, radiating folds | Irregular, nodular, heaped-up margins, friable, non-healing |\n| Location | Lesser curvature, antrum | Any location, often greater curvature, fundus, cardia |\n| Biopsy | Inflammatory cells, no malignancy | Atypical cells, glandular dysplasia/carcinoma |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Always biopsy gastric ulcers; benign appearance can deceive.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn endoscopy, a malignant gastric ulcer may appear as an irregular, non-healing lesion with heaped-up margins, nodularity, and friability. Biopsies are essential from the base and margins. CT imaging may show gastric wall thickening, regional lymphadenopathy, or distant metastases.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for Gastric Cancer (2023). Recommends endoscopic evaluation with biopsy for all suspicious gastric lesions and staging with CT/PET for confirmed malignancy.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | C. Dieulafoy’s disease\tD. Carcinoma stomach | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Which is the most common cause of duodenal obstruction in adults? | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Annular pancreas\tB. Duodenal atresia | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | C. Carcinoma of duodenum\tD. Carcinoma of pancreas | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: ?) Malignant gastric ulcer** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Competency 2500**\n"
