  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Leprosy: Nerves are the primary target, not just skin deep.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe verified answer, 'Cutaneous and subcutaneous nerves,' correctly identifies the primary target tissues for *Mycobacterium leprae*, the causative agent of leprosy. This highlights the characteristic neurological involvement that defines the disease's clinical presentation.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\n*Mycobacterium leprae* has a unique tropism for Schwann cells, which myelinate peripheral nerves, particularly in cooler parts of the body. The bacteria replicate within these cells, leading to demyelination, inflammation, and granuloma formation, ultimately causing nerve damage and loss of function. This predilection for peripheral nerves, especially cutaneous and subcutaneous ones, explains the classic sensory and motor deficits, as well as the characteristic skin lesions, seen in leprosy.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): 'Immune response of the body' is a factor influencing disease progression, not a mode of infection or a primary affected structure. \nOption B (Incorrect): 'Age of patient' is a demographic factor, not a mode of infection or a primary affected structure. \nOption C (Incorrect): 'Which one of the following glands is affected in leprosy?' is a question, not an option, and the verified answer is nerves, not glands. \nOption D (Incorrect): 'Testis B. Pancreas' is a malformed option. While the testis can be affected in advanced lepromatous leprosy, it is not the primary or most characteristic target tissue compared to cutaneous and subcutaneous nerves. The pancreas is generally not a primary target of leprosy. The original question 'Mode of infection' is also incongruent with the verified answer, which describes affected tissues rather than transmission.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Tuberculoid Leprosy | Lepromatous Leprosy |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Immune Response** | Strong cell-mediated (Th1) | Weak cell-mediated (Th2) |\n| **Nerve Involvement** | Few, asymmetric, severe nerve damage; early loss of sensation | Many, symmetric, less severe nerve damage initially; widespread sensory loss |\n| **Skin Lesions** | Few, well-demarcated, anesthetic plaques | Numerous, poorly demarcated, diffuse nodules/macules; 'leonine facies' |\n| **Bacterial Load** | Low (paucibacillary) | High (multibacillary) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Leprosy targets peripheral nerves, especially in cooler body regions.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn clinical examination, thickened peripheral nerves (e.g., ulnar, great auricular, peroneal) may be palpable. Nerve biopsy would show granulomatous inflammation, acid-fast bacilli within Schwann cells, and nerve fiber destruction.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nWHO Guidelines for the Diagnosis, Treatment and Prevention of Leprosy (2018): Recommends multi-drug therapy (MDT) for all forms of leprosy and emphasizes early diagnosis to prevent nerve damage.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Immune response of the body | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Age of patient | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Which one of the following glands is affected in leprosy? | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Testis\tB. Pancreas | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: ?) Cutaneous and subcutaneous nerves** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Competency 2500**\n"
