  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Anthrax: Spores, skin, eschar, direct contact.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe question describes *Bacillus anthracis*, a Gram-positive, aerobic, spore-forming bacillus. The verified answer correctly identifies \"Spread by direct contact\" as a primary mode of transmission for this organism, particularly for cutaneous anthrax.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\n*Bacillus anthracis* is the causative agent of anthrax. Its defining characteristics include being a large, Gram-positive, non-motile, aerobic rod that forms highly resistant endospores. These spores are the infectious form and can survive in soil for decades. Cutaneous anthrax, the most common form, occurs when spores enter through breaks in the skin, typically via direct contact with infected animals or contaminated animal products like hides, wool, or meat. This direct contact transmission leads to the characteristic \"malignant pustule\" lesion.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Gram-negative, aerobic, spore-forming bacillus - *Bacillus anthracis* is Gram-positive, not Gram-negative.\nOption B (Incorrect): Gram-positive, anaerobic spore-forming bacillus - *Bacillus anthracis* is aerobic, not anaerobic. *Clostridium* species are Gram-positive, anaerobic, spore-forming bacilli.\nOption C (Incorrect): Gram-negative aerobic, non-spore forming bacillus - *Bacillus anthracis* is Gram-positive and spore-forming.\nOption D (Incorrect): What is ‘malignant pustule’? - This is a symptom of cutaneous anthrax, not a description of the bacterium itself, nor a mode of transmission. It is also phrased as a question.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | *Bacillus anthracis* | *Clostridium tetani* | *Escherichia coli* |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Gram Stain | Gram-positive | Gram-positive | Gram-negative |\n| Oxygen Req. | Aerobic | Anaerobic | Facultative Anaerobe |\n| Spore-forming | Yes | Yes | No |\n| Morphology | Rod | Rod | Rod |\n| Transmission | Direct contact (spores), inhalation, ingestion | Puncture wounds (spores) | Fecal-oral, contaminated food/water |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Anthrax spores are tough; direct contact is key for cutaneous infection.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nFor cutaneous anthrax, you might see a characteristic painless, pruritic papule that progresses to a vesicle, then a necrotic ulcer with a black eschar (malignant pustule). Imaging (CT) for inhalational anthrax would show mediastinal widening and pleural effusions.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nCDC Clinical Guidelines for the Management of Anthrax (2016). Recommends ciprofloxacin or doxycycline for treatment, and vaccination for high-risk individuals.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Gram-negative, aerobic, spore-forming bacillus | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Gram-positive, anaerobic spore-forming bacillus | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Gram-negative aerobic, non-spore forming bacillus | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | What is ‘malignant pustule’? | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: ?) Spread by direct contact** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Competency 2500**\n"
