  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Peritoneal spread: a surgical challenge, not just a diagnosis.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe verdict is Peritoneal malignancy. This refers to the spread of cancer cells to the peritoneum, the membrane lining the abdominal cavity, often originating from primary tumors within the abdomen or pelvis.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nPeritoneal malignancy, or carcinomatosis, is a common manifestation of advanced abdominal and pelvic cancers, particularly ovarian, colorectal, and gastric cancers. It often presents with ascites, abdominal distension, and bowel obstruction. The mechanism involves direct spread of tumor cells within the peritoneal fluid, lymphatic dissemination, or hematogenous spread to the peritoneal surface, leading to widespread tumor implants.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): \"Posterior horn cells of spinal cord\" are involved in sensory processing and are anatomically unrelated to peritoneal malignancy.\nOption B (Incorrect): \"At the cerebral cortex\" refers to the brain's outer layer, which is anatomically distinct from the abdominal cavity and peritoneal cancer.\nOption C (Incorrect): \"At the motor cortex\" is a brain region controlling voluntary movement, bearing no relevance to peritoneal malignancy.\nOption D (Incorrect): \"Tetanospasmin acts on which chemical?\" is a question about neurotoxins and neurotransmitters, entirely outside the scope of peritoneal malignancy.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Peritoneal Carcinomatosis | Pseudomyxoma Peritonei | Peritoneal Mesothelioma |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Primary Origin | Ovarian, Colorectal, Gastric | Appendix (most common) | Peritoneum (asbestos exposure) |\n| Histology | Adenocarcinoma (typically) | Mucinous adenocarcinoma | Epithelioid, sarcomatoid, biphasic |\n| Treatment | CRS + HIPEC, systemic chemo | CRS + HIPEC | CRS + HIPEC, systemic chemo, radiation |\n| Prognosis | Variable, often poor | Indolent, better prognosis | Poor |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Peritoneal carcinomatosis often dictates prognosis and treatment strategy.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT, look for ascites, omental caking, nodular peritoneal thickening, and bowel wall infiltration. Intraoperatively, diffuse white/yellow tumor implants are seen on the peritoneal surfaces, diaphragm, and bowel serosa.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for Ovarian Cancer (2023) recommend cytoreductive surgery (CRS) with hyperthermic intraperitoneal chemotherapy (HIPEC) for select patients with peritoneal carcinomatosis.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Posterior horn cells of spinal cord | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | At the cerebral cortex | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | At the motor cortex | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Tetanospasmin acts on which chemical? | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: ?) Peritoneal malignancy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Competency 2500**\n"
