  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Scrotal TB: Ultrasound is the initial eye on the prize.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe verified answer, \"Ultrasound scrotum,\" is correct. For suspected Tuberculous epididymo-orchitis, ultrasound is the essential initial diagnostic imaging modality to evaluate scrotal pathology and guide further management.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nUltrasound of the scrotum is a non-invasive, readily available, and highly effective tool for evaluating scrotal pain and swelling. In cases of Tuberculous epididymo-orchitis, it can reveal characteristic findings such as an enlarged, heterogeneous epididymis and testis, hypoechoic lesions, calcifications, and reactive hydrocele. It is crucial for differentiating this condition from other acute scrotal pathologies like bacterial epididymo-orchitis, testicular torsion, or neoplastic processes, thereby directing appropriate treatment pathways.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Testicular tumor) (Incorrect): A testicular tumor is a differential diagnosis for scrotal swelling, not a diagnostic tool. Ultrasound is used to identify and characterize testicular tumors.\nOption B (Trauma) (Incorrect): Trauma is a potential cause of scrotal pathology, not a diagnostic method. Ultrasound would be used to assess the extent of injury following trauma.\nOption C (Varicocele) (Incorrect): A varicocele is a distinct scrotal condition (dilated pampiniform plexus veins), not a diagnostic modality for epididymo-orchitis. Ultrasound is used to diagnose varicoceles.\nOption D (Which is the most important clinical feature of vaginal hydrocele?) (Incorrect): This is a question about a clinical feature of hydrocele, not a diagnostic option or a differential diagnosis for Tuberculous epididymo-orchitis. It is irrelevant to the primary question.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Condition | Key Ultrasound Findings |\n|---|---|\n| Tuberculous Epididymo-orchitis | Enlarged, heterogeneous epididymis/testis, hypoechoic lesions, calcifications, reactive hydrocele |\n| Acute Bacterial Epididymo-orchitis | Enlarged, hyperemic epididymis/testis, increased vascularity on Doppler, often diffuse |\n| Testicular Tumor | Solid, hypoechoic intratesticular mass, often heterogeneous, may have calcifications or cystic areas |\n| Varicocele | Dilated, tortuous veins (>2-3mm) in pampiniform plexus, increased flow with Valsalva maneuver |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Scrotal swelling? Ultrasound is your first diagnostic step.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn scrotal ultrasound, Tuberculous epididymo-orchitis typically manifests as an enlarged, heterogeneous epididymis and testis, often with hypoechoic areas, microabscesses, or calcifications. A reactive hydrocele is common, and Doppler imaging may show variable vascularity, sometimes less pronounced than in acute bacterial infections. Fistula tracts or scrotal wall thickening can also be observed.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Urological Association (AUA) Guidelines on the Evaluation and Management of Scrotal Mass (2020) recommends scrotal ultrasound as the primary imaging modality for evaluating scrotal masses and pain.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Testicular tumor | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Trauma | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Varicocele | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Which is the most important clinical feature of vaginal hydrocele? | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: ?) Ultrasound scrotum** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Competency 2500**\n"
