  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Testicular cancer: Inguinal approach, never scrotal, to save the day!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe verdict is Chevassu’s procedure, which refers to a radical inguinal orchiectomy. This procedure is the standard initial diagnostic and therapeutic step for suspected testicular cancer, a disease that can metastasize to retroperitoneal and, in advanced stages, mediastinal lymph nodes.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nChevassu’s procedure, or radical inguinal orchiectomy, is performed via an inguinal incision to ligate the spermatic cord structures high in the inguinal canal before removing the testis. This approach is crucial to prevent tumor cell dissemination into scrotal lymphatics and ensures complete removal of the primary tumor. The anatomical basis lies in the lymphatic drainage of the testis, which follows the gonadal vessels to the retroperitoneum, distinct from the superficial scrotal lymphatics.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Pulmonary lymph nodes are intrathoracic lymph nodes, distinct from the primary lymphatic drainage of the testis.\nOption B (Incorrect): While an inguinal incision is used, inguinal lymph nodes are not the primary drainage site for testicular cancer unless there is scrotal involvement or prior scrotal surgery.\nOption C (Incorrect): This is a question about diagnosis confirmation, not an anatomical location or a specific procedure related to the initial management of testicular cancer.\nOption D (Incorrect): Scrotal biopsy or wedge biopsy of the testis is contraindicated for suspected testicular cancer due to the high risk of tumor seeding into scrotal lymphatics, which would alter the metastatic pathway and prognosis.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Procedure | Indication | Key Principle |\n|---|---|---|\n| Radical Inguinal Orchiectomy (Chevassu's) | Suspected testicular cancer | Initial diagnosis & treatment; high cord ligation to prevent scrotal seeding |\n| Scrotal Biopsy | Contraindicated for suspected testicular cancer | Risk of tumor seeding to inguinal lymphatics, altering staging/prognosis |\n| Retroperitoneal Lymph Node Dissection (RPLND) | Staging/treatment for testicular cancer (non-seminoma) | Addresses primary lymphatic drainage of testis |\n| Mediastinal Lymph Node Biopsy | Diagnosis of advanced metastatic disease | Performed for distant metastases, not primary tumor |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Never biopsy a suspected testicular mass through the scrotum.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound, a solid, hypoechoic intratesticular mass is characteristic. CT imaging of the chest, abdomen, and pelvis would reveal retroperitoneal or mediastinal lymphadenopathy in metastatic disease. Intraoperatively, the affected testis often appears enlarged and firm.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for Testicular Cancer (2023): Recommends radical inguinal orchiectomy as the initial management for suspected testicular cancer.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Pulmonary lymph nodes | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Inguinal lymph nodes | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Diagnosis of testicular tumor on the operating table is confirmed? | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Biopsy through scrotum\tB. Wedge biopsy | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: ?) Chevassu’s procedure** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Competency 2500**\n"
