  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 High orchidectomy: High stakes, high ligation, high success.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe verified answer, D) High orchidectomy, is correct. This procedure is the standard surgical approach for suspected testicular tumors due to its oncologic principles and prevention of tumor dissemination.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nHigh orchidectomy, also known as radical inguinal orchidectomy, is performed via an inguinal incision. This approach allows for early and high ligation of the spermatic cord before the testis is manipulated, preventing potential tumor cell dissemination into the systemic circulation or lymphatic system. It also avoids violating the scrotal lymphatic drainage, which is distinct from the retroperitoneal drainage of the testis, thereby minimizing the risk of local recurrence or seeding.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): This is the question itself, not a viable answer option.\nOption B (Incorrect): Orchidectomy through the scrotum is contraindicated for suspected testicular tumors due to the high risk of tumor seeding into the scrotal lymphatic system and incomplete resection, which can compromise oncologic outcomes.\nOption C (Incorrect): While an orchidectomy through the inguinal canal is the correct approach, 'High orchidectomy' is the more precise and complete term, specifically emphasizing the crucial step of high ligation of the spermatic cord, which is fundamental to the oncologic principle.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Procedure | Indication | Approach | Key Feature |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Radical Inguinal Orchidectomy (High Orchidectomy) | Suspected testicular tumor | Inguinal | High ligation of spermatic cord, avoids scrotal violation |\n| Simple Orchidectomy (Scrotal) | Benign conditions (e.g., severe orchitis, atrophy), gender affirmation | Scrotal | Testis removed via scrotal incision |\n| Subcapsular Orchidectomy | Palliative hormonal therapy for prostate cancer | Scrotal | Testicular parenchyma removed, tunica albuginea left intact |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Never violate the scrotum for a suspected testicular tumor.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIntraoperatively, the spermatic cord is identified and clamped high in the inguinal canal before delivering the testis from the scrotum into the inguinal wound, ensuring no manipulation of the tumor before vascular control.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Urological Association (AUA) Guidelines for Testicular Cancer (2019) recommend radical inguinal orchiectomy for all patients with a solid testicular mass suspicious for malignancy.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | What is the surgery for testicular tumour? | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Orchidectomy through the scrotum | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Orchidectomy through inguinal canal | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | High orchidectomy | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: ?) D) High orchidectomy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Competency 2500**\n"
