  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't confuse a tear with a clot!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nPerianal haematoma is the correct answer. While both conditions cause acute perianal pain, an acute anal fissure is a linear tear in the anoderm, whereas a perianal haematoma is a thrombosed external hemorrhoid, making them distinct entities requiring different management strategies.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nAn acute anal fissure is a linear tear in the anoderm, most commonly in the posterior midline, characterized by severe pain during defecation and bright red bleeding. This pain often leads to internal anal sphincter spasm, perpetuating the fissure. In contrast, a perianal haematoma is a thrombosed external hemorrhoid, presenting as a sudden, exquisitely painful, tense, bluish lump at the anal verge due to rupture of a perianal vein. While both cause acute perianal pain, their distinct etiologies and physical findings are crucial for accurate diagnosis.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Chronic anal fissure) (Incorrect): A chronic anal fissure is a progression of an acute fissure, distinguished by duration (>6-8 weeks) and often associated with the 'fissure triad,' not a distinct differential diagnosis in the same way a haematoma is.\nOption B (Sentinel pile) (Incorrect): A sentinel pile is a skin tag often found at the distal end of a chronic anal fissure. It is a sign of chronicity, not a primary condition to be confused with an acute fissure.\nOption D (The mnemonic “pus, polyps, parasites, piles, psyche” refers what?) (Incorrect): This is a question about a mnemonic, not a clinical condition or a differential diagnosis for an acute anal fissure.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Condition | Key Feature | Pain | Bleeding | Initial Treatment |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| Acute Anal Fissure | Linear tear in anoderm | Severe cyclic with defecation | Bright red | Topical nitrates/CCBs, stool softeners |\n| Chronic Anal Fissure | Fissure triad (fissure, sentinel pile, hypertrophied papilla) | Persistent, often less severe than acute | Bright red | Surgery (Lateral Internal Sphincterotomy) |\n| Perianal Haematoma | Thrombosed external hemorrhoid | Sudden onset, severe, constant | Minimal/none unless ulcerated | Excision (if early/large) or conservative |\n| Perianal Abscess | Collection of pus | Constant, throbbing, fever | None (unless ruptured) | Incision and Drainage |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Acute perianal pain? Fissure vs. Haematoma vs. Abscess.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn physical exam, an acute anal fissure appears as a linear tear in the anoderm, typically at the posterior midline. A perianal haematoma presents as a distinct, tense, bluish, exquisitely tender lump at the anal verge, often without an open wound.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nASCRS Clinical Practice Guidelines for the Management of Anal Fissure (2017) recommend conservative management as first-line therapy for acute anal fissures, including dietary modification, stool softeners, and topical agents.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Chronic anal fissure | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Sentinel pile | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Perianal haematoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | The mnemonic “pus, polyps, parasites, piles, psyche” refers what? | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: ?) C) Perianal haematoma** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Competency 2500**\n"
