  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Not all rectal pain is infectious; consider the mechanics!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe verdict is that 'Obstetric injury' is the correct answer. This implies that the question, while mentioning 'Herpes proctitis', is likely probing the broader differential diagnosis of anorectal symptoms, where obstetric injury represents a significant non-infectious cause that must be distinguished from infectious etiologies.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nObstetric injury, particularly severe perineal tears (third- or fourth-degree), directly damages the anal sphincter complex and surrounding pelvic floor structures. This mechanical trauma can lead to chronic pain, fecal incontinence, and rectovaginal fistulae, mimicking or coexisting with symptoms of infectious proctitis. Understanding this non-infectious etiology is crucial for comprehensive patient assessment and appropriate management, distinguishing structural damage from microbial inflammation.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Gonococcal proctitis) (Incorrect): This is an infectious cause of proctitis, distinct from mechanical obstetric injury.\nOption B (What is the cause of condylomata lata?) (Incorrect): This is a question about a manifestation of syphilis, not an answer to a proctitis etiology or obstetric injury.\nOption C (Tuberculosis) (Incorrect): Tuberculous proctitis is an infectious cause, unrelated to mechanical obstetric trauma.\nOption D (Syphilis) (Incorrect): Syphilitic proctitis is an infectious cause, not an obstetric injury.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Herpes Proctitis | Gonococcal Proctitis | Obstetric Injury |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Etiology | HSV-1/2 infection | Neisseria gonorrhoeae | Perineal trauma during childbirth |\n| Symptoms | Pain, tenesmus, discharge, vesicles/ulcers | Pain, discharge, pruritus, tenesmus | Pain, incontinence, dyspareunia, fistulae |\n| Pathophysiology | Viral replication, inflammation | Bacterial infection, inflammation | Mechanical disruption of sphincter/perineum |\n| Treatment | Antivirals | Antibiotics | Surgical repair, physical therapy |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Differentiate infectious proctitis from non-infectious anorectal pathology.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn imaging (e.g., endoanal ultrasound or MRI), obstetric injury would show sphincter defects or scarring, distinct from mucosal inflammation seen in infectious proctitis.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Obstetricians and Gynecologists (ACOG) Practice Bulletin No. 198 (2018): Management of Obstetric Lacerations. It recommends systematic evaluation and repair of perineal tears.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Gonococcal proctitis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | What is the cause of condylomata lata? | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Tuberculosis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Syphilis | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: ?) Obstetric injury** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Competency 2500**\n"
