  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Lower midline: The express lane to the pelvis.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe verdict is 'Lower midline', which refers to a common vertical surgical incision. This incision provides excellent access to the pelvic and lower abdominal organs, making it a fundamental approach in various surgical specialties.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nA lower midline incision is made vertically through the skin, subcutaneous tissue, and then through the linea alba, a relatively avascular fibrous raphe between the rectus abdominis muscles. This approach offers rapid entry into the peritoneal cavity and can be easily extended superiorly around the umbilicus if more extensive exposure is required. Its primary advantage lies in the wide and versatile access it provides to structures such as the uterus, bladder, prostate, and rectum, making it ideal for gynecological, urological, and general surgical procedures involving the pelvis.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): 'Vegetable gum with petroleum gelly' describes a material composition, not a surgical incision type or location.\nOption B (Incorrect): 'Which type of surgery, gastrectomy is considered as?' is a question about surgical classification, not an answer related to an incision.\nOption C (Incorrect): 'Contaminated' is a classification of surgical wound, not a type of incision.\nOption D (Incorrect): 'Clean-contaminated' is also a classification of surgical wound, not an incision.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Incision Type | Description | Common Uses | Key Feature |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Lower Midline | Vertical incision from umbilicus to pubis | Pelvic surgery, C-section, bladder surgery | Rapid access, good for pelvic exposure |\n| Pfannenstiel | Transverse curvilinear incision above pubis | C-section, hysterectomy, hernia repair | Cosmetically superior, strong fascial closure |\n| Upper Midline | Vertical incision from xiphoid to umbilicus | Gastrectomy, liver surgery, splenectomy | Rapid access to upper abdomen, can be extended |\n| Kocher (Subcostal) | Oblique incision parallel to right costal margin | Cholecystectomy, liver resection | Excellent exposure to right upper quadrant |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Midline incisions offer rapid access but higher dehiscence risk.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIntraoperatively, a lower midline incision provides direct access to the uterus, bladder, and rectum, with the linea alba visible as a relatively avascular plane that is incised to enter the peritoneal cavity.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Obstetricians and Gynecologists (ACOG) Practice Bulletin No. 205 (2019) on Cesarean Delivery: Discusses various incision types, including lower midline, for C-sections, emphasizing patient safety and outcomes.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Vegetable gum with petroleum gelly | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Which type of surgery, gastrectomy is considered as? | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Contaminated | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Clean-contaminated | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: ?) Lower midline** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Competency 2500**\n"
