  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Wound dehiscence: A surgeon's nightmare, preventable with care.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe verdict is 'Dehiscence'. This term refers to the partial or complete separation of wound edges, a critical complication in surgical healing. While the provided question and options are unrelated to this specific complication, understanding dehiscence is paramount for any surgeon.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nDehiscence typically occurs due to a combination of factors including excessive tension on the wound, inadequate suture technique, infection, poor nutrition, or increased intra-abdominal pressure. It represents a failure of the healing process, often occurring in the early postoperative period, usually between postoperative days 5 and 8 when collagen synthesis is still immature and tensile strength is at its lowest. Recognizing its multifactorial etiology is crucial for effective prevention and management.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Digital block anesthesia is a regional anesthetic technique, not a surgical complication like dehiscence.\nOption B (Incorrect): 'The following facts are true regarding braided suture except' is an incomplete question stem and not a surgical complication.\nOption C (Incorrect): 'Better tensile strength' describes a property of a material, likely suture, and is not a surgical complication.\nOption D (Incorrect): 'Handling is easier' describes a property of a material, likely suture, and is not a surgical complication.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Complication | Description | Timing | Risk Factors |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Dehiscence | Partial or complete separation of wound layers | Post-op days 5-8 | Infection, poor nutrition, increased intra-abdominal pressure, inadequate closure |\n| Evisceration | Protrusion of internal organs through a dehiscence | Often follows dehiscence | Same as dehiscence, but more severe |\n| Incisional Hernia | Protrusion of tissue through a weakened abdominal wall scar | Months to years post-op | Obesity, infection, poor healing, excessive tension |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: \"Dehiscence: When the wound says 'nope' to healing.\"\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIntraoperatively, dehiscence is evident as a visible separation of fascial or skin edges, often with serosanguinous drainage. Imaging like CT may show fluid collections or bowel herniation through a fascial defect.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Surgeons (ACS) Statement on Surgical Site Infection Prevention (2016). Recommends meticulous surgical technique and appropriate suture choice to minimize wound complications like dehiscence.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Digital block anesthesia | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | The following facts are true regarding braided suture except | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Better tensile strength | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Handling is easier | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: ?) Dehiscence** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Competency 2500**\n"
