  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't confuse a disease with its cure!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe verdict is that \"Amoebic granuloma\" is the correct answer. This is because the implicit question asks to identify which of the given options is *not* a recommended procedure for complete rectal prolapse. Amoebic granuloma is a pathological condition, not a surgical procedure, making it the outlier.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe question tests the fundamental understanding of distinguishing between a disease entity and its treatment modalities. Complete rectal prolapse is a full-thickness protrusion of the rectal wall through the anus, requiring surgical correction. Procedures like Thiersch's operation (perineal cerclage) and various rectopexies (e.g., Wells/Ripstein, posterior mesh rectopexy) are established surgical interventions. Submucosal injection, while a procedure, is typically for hemorrhoids or mucosal prolapse, not full-thickness prolapse. Amoebic granuloma, however, is an inflammatory mass caused by *Entamoeba histolytica*, a condition that requires medical treatment, not a surgical procedure for prolapse.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Submucosal injection (e.g., sclerotherapy) is primarily used for internal hemorrhoids or very early mucosal prolapse, not full-thickness complete rectal prolapse.\nOption B (Incorrect): Thiersch's operation is a perineal procedure involving anal cerclage, used for rectal prolapse, particularly in frail patients or those with significant comorbidities.\nOption C (Incorrect): \"Well's operation\" is likely a misspelling or refers to a rectopexy procedure (e.g., Ripstein or Wells rectopexy), which is an abdominal approach for rectal prolapse.\nOption D (Question Stem): This option is the actual question stem, asking to identify the item that is *not* a recommended procedure for complete rectal prolapse.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Procedure Type | Example Procedures | Approach | Indication |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Perineal | Delorme procedure, Altemeier procedure (perineal rectosigmoidectomy), Thiersch cerclage | Perineal | Frail patients, high surgical risk, shorter operative time |\n| Abdominal | Ripstein procedure (anterior rectopexy), Wells procedure (posterior rectopexy), Laparoscopic ventral mesh rectopexy | Abdominal | Younger, fitter patients, lower recurrence rates |\n| Non-surgical | Digital reduction, conservative management | Manual/Medical | Temporary relief, very early/mild cases, or unfit for surgery |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Distinguish conditions from procedures, especially in 'except' questions.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIn the OR, complete rectal prolapse appears as concentric folds of full-thickness rectal wall protruding through the anus, often reducible manually.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Society of Colon and Rectal Surgeons (ASCRS) Clinical Practice Guidelines for the Treatment of Rectal Prolapse (2017) recommends surgical repair for most symptomatic full-thickness rectal prolapse.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Submucus injection | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Thiersch’s operation | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Well’s operation | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | In complete prolapse of the rectum the following procedures are recommended | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: ?) Amoebic granuloma** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Competency 2500**\n"
