  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Villous adenomas: the potassium pilferers of the colon!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Villous adenoma. These polyps are notorious for their ability to secrete large volumes of potassium-rich mucin, leading to significant electrolyte imbalances, most notably hypokalemia.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nVillous adenomas, particularly large ones, possess an extensive surface area composed of secretory epithelial cells. These cells actively secrete fluid and electrolytes, including potassium and bicarbonate, into the colonic lumen. The continuous loss of this potassium-rich fluid can deplete the body's potassium stores, resulting in profound hypokalemia, which can manifest with muscle weakness, cardiac arrhythmias, and other systemic effects. This secretory mechanism is a hallmark feature distinguishing them from other polyp types.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Juvenile polyp) (Incorrect): These are hamartomatous polyps, typically benign, and do not cause significant electrolyte disturbances like hypokalemia.\nOption B (Metaplastic polyp) (Incorrect): These are benign, non-neoplastic polyps with no known association with hypokalemia or significant fluid secretion.\nOption C (Familial adenomatous polyposis) (Incorrect): FAP is a genetic syndrome characterized by numerous adenomatous polyps, but the polyps themselves do not typically cause hypokalemia through excessive secretion.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Polyp Type | Malignant Potential | Electrolyte Disturbance | Key Feature |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Villous Adenoma | High | Hypokalemia, Hyponatremia | Large, frond-like, mucin-secreting |\n| Tubular Adenoma | Moderate | None | Pedunculated, smooth surface |\n| Tubulovillous Adenoma | Intermediate | Rare | Mixed features |\n| Juvenile Polyp | None | None | Hamartomatous, often in children |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Villous adenoma = copious mucus + hypokalemia.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn endoscopy, a villous adenoma appears as a broad-based, often sessile, velvety or cauliflower-like lesion with a frond-like surface, frequently covered in mucus. It can be quite large and friable.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Society for Gastrointestinal Endoscopy (ASGE) 2020 Guidelines for the Management of Colorectal Polyps. These guidelines recommend endoscopic removal for most adenomatous polyps, with surgical resection considered for large or complex villous adenomas, especially those with high-grade dysplasia or invasive cancer.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Juvenile polyp | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Metaplastic polyp | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Familial adenomatous polyposis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Villous adenoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: ?) Transanal endoscopic microsurgery** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Competency 2500**\n"
