  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Thymomas: MG's companion, but not always a cancer.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is \"A) All thymomas are malignant\". This statement is false because thymomas, while frequently associated with myasthenia gravis, exhibit a spectrum of behavior from benign to malignant, and not all are malignant.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThymomas are the most common primary tumor of the anterior mediastinum and are strongly associated with myasthenia gravis, occurring in 30-50% of patients with MG. However, their biological behavior is diverse. The WHO classification categorizes thymomas into types A, AB, B1, B2, B3, and thymic carcinoma (Type C), reflecting increasing degrees of atypia and invasiveness. Only thymic carcinoma is unequivocally malignant, while other types have varying malignant potential, with Type A being the most benign. Therefore, stating 'all thymomas are malignant' is incorrect.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Correct): 'All thymomas are malignant' is false. Thymomas range from benign (e.g., Type A) to malignant (thymic carcinoma), with varying degrees of invasiveness and metastatic potential.\nOption B (Incorrect): 'They can get calcified' is a true statement. Calcification can occur in thymomas, though it is not a specific diagnostic feature.\nOption C (Incorrect): 'All of the following are non-small cell carcinoma of lung' is irrelevant to thymomas or myasthenia gravis and is a distractor.\nOption D (Incorrect): 'except' is an incomplete option and not a statement.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Thymoma Type | Malignant Potential | Association with MG | Histology |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Type A | Low | Less common | Spindle/oval epithelial cells, few lymphocytes |\n| Type B1 | Low-Intermediate | Common | Lymphocyte-rich, resembling normal thymus |\n| Type B3 | High | Common | Predominantly epithelial cells, mild atypia |\n| Thymic Carcinoma (Type C) | High | Less common | Marked atypia, invasive growth |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Thymomas are diverse; malignancy is not universal, but MG association is strong.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT, thymomas appear as anterior mediastinal masses. Intraoperatively, they can range from well-encapsulated, easily resectable lesions to invasive masses adhering to or invading surrounding structures like the pericardium or great vessels.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for Thymomas and Thymic Carcinomas (2023). These guidelines provide comprehensive recommendations for staging, treatment, and surveillance based on the WHO classification and Masaoka-Koga staging system.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | All thymomas are malignant | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | They can get calcified | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | All of the following are non-small cell carcinoma of lung | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | except | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: ?) A) All thymomas are malignant** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Competency 2500**\n"
