  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Lymphoma: When lymphocytes go rogue, it's not a nerve-wracking tumor.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe verified answer, Non-Hodgkin’s lymphoma, is correct because it represents a diverse group of cancers originating from lymphocytes, which are a type of white blood cell. This distinguishes it from solid tumors of neural origin or other inflammatory conditions.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nNon-Hodgkin’s lymphoma arises from malignant transformation of B or T lymphocytes, primarily affecting lymph nodes but capable of involving any organ. Its diagnosis relies on tissue biopsy, often of an enlarged lymph node, demonstrating characteristic cellular morphology and immunophenotype. Staging is critical, typically involving PET-CT scans and bone marrow biopsy, to determine disease extent and guide treatment, which can range from chemotherapy and radiation to immunotherapy and stem cell transplantation.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nGanglioneuroma (Incorrect): This is a benign tumor originating from sympathetic ganglion cells, not a hematologic malignancy.\nGanglioneuroblastoma (Incorrect): This is an intermediate-grade tumor of the sympathetic nervous system, containing both mature ganglion cells and immature neuroblasts, not a lymphoma.\nNeuroblastoma (Incorrect): This is a highly malignant tumor of the sympathetic nervous system, primarily affecting children, and is not a lymphoma.\nNeurofibroma (Incorrect): This is a benign tumor of the peripheral nerve sheath, composed of Schwann cells, fibroblasts, and mast cells, distinct from a lymphoma.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Hodgkin Lymphoma | Non-Hodgkin Lymphoma | Neuroblastoma | Ganglioneuroma |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| **Origin** | B-lymphocytes (Reed-Sternberg cells) | B or T-lymphocytes | Neural crest cells (sympathetic nervous system) | Mature neural crest cells (sympathetic nervous system) |\n| **Age Group** | Bimodal (young adults, >55) | All ages (incidence increases with age) | Primarily children (<5 years) | Any age, often children/young adults |\n| **Malignancy** | Malignant (curable) | Malignant (variable prognosis) | Highly Malignant | Benign |\n| **Key Cell** | Reed-Sternberg cell | Diverse (e.g., centroblasts, immunoblasts) | Neuroblasts | Mature ganglion cells, Schwann cells |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Lymphoma is a cancer of lymphocytes, not nerve cells.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn imaging (CT/PET), Non-Hodgkin's lymphoma often presents as bulky lymphadenopathy or extranodal masses. Intraoperatively, affected lymph nodes may appear enlarged and firm, requiring excisional biopsy for definitive diagnosis.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for B-Cell Lymphomas (2024) recommend comprehensive staging, risk stratification, and tailored treatment approaches based on specific lymphoma subtype and patient factors.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | C. Neuroblastoma\tD. Neurofibroma | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Regarding Tietze syndrome the following are true except | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | It is due to costochondritis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Mistaken for cardiac disease if on left side | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: ?) Non-Hodgkin’s lymphoma** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Competency 2500**\n"
