  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Neuroblastoma: The chameleon of pediatric cancer, always suspect it!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Neuroblastoma. This is a common extracranial solid tumor of childhood, originating from neural crest cells, and is a critical diagnosis for pediatric surgeons due to its varied presentation and treatment strategies.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nNeuroblastoma arises from primitive sympathetic neuroblasts, often found in the adrenal medulla or paraspinal ganglia. Its clinical behavior is highly variable, ranging from spontaneous regression to aggressive metastatic disease. Key prognostic factors include age at diagnosis, MYCN amplification, and tumor stage, which guide surgical resection, chemotherapy, and radiation therapy decisions.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): 'A course of antibiotics is useful' is a general statement unrelated to the diagnosis or management of Neuroblastoma. \nOption B (Incorrect): 'Which of the following is NOT true regarding tension pneumothorax?' is a question about a different medical condition. \nOption C (Incorrect): 'Tympanitic percussion note on the affected side' describes a physical exam finding for conditions like pneumothorax, not Neuroblastoma. \nOption D (Incorrect): 'Absent breath sounds over the affected side' is another physical exam finding for conditions like pneumothorax, unrelated to Neuroblastoma.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Neuroblastoma | Wilms Tumor | Hepatoblastoma |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Origin | Neural crest cells | Metanephric blastema | Primitive hepatocytes |\n| Location | Adrenal, paraspinal | Kidney | Liver |\n| Age | <5 years (median 18mo) | 2-5 years | <3 years |\n| Markers | VMA/HVA in urine | None specific | AFP elevated |\n| Calcifications | Common | Rare | Rare |\n| Prognosis | Variable, MYCN | Good, stage-dependent | Variable, stage-dependent |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Neuroblastoma is the most common extracranial solid tumor in children.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT, Neuroblastoma often appears as an irregular, heterogeneous mass with calcifications, frequently crossing the midline and encasing vessels. Intraoperatively, it can be firm, nodular, and infiltrative, making complete resection challenging.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nChildren's Oncology Group (COG) Neuroblastoma Guidelines (e.g., ANBL00B1, ANBL1232). These guidelines provide risk stratification and treatment protocols based on age, stage, MYCN status, and histology.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | A course of antibiotics is useful | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Which of the following is NOT true regarding tension pneumothorax? | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Tympanitic percussion note on the affected side | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Absent breath sounds over the affected side | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: ?) Neuroblastoma** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Competency 2500**\n"
