  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When it comes to PE, the right inferior lobe is the prime real estate.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe question asks about the most common lung lobe for embolism. While the provided 'Verified Answer' points to 'Venous embolism' as the origin, the clinical context implies pulmonary embolism. Pulmonary emboli, typically arising from deep venous thrombosis, preferentially lodge in the right inferior lobe due to its larger size and greater blood flow.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nPulmonary emboli are typically thrombi originating from the deep venous system. Upon reaching the pulmonary circulation, they tend to follow the path of least resistance and highest blood flow. The lower lobes, particularly the right inferior lobe, receive a disproportionately higher percentage of pulmonary blood flow due to gravitational effects and anatomical considerations, making them the most common sites for embolus impaction. This physiological distribution explains the predilection for the right inferior lobe.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Right superior lobe: While part of the right lung, the superior lobes generally receive less blood flow compared to the inferior lobes, making them less common sites for initial PE impaction.\nOption B (Incorrect): Right middle lobe: This lobe is smaller and receives less blood flow than the inferior lobe, thus it is less frequently the primary site of a pulmonary embolism.\nOption D (Incorrect): Left superior lobe: The left lung as a whole is smaller than the right, and its superior lobe receives less blood flow than the inferior lobes, making it a less common site for PE.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Embolus Type | Common Origin | Common Site of Impaction |\n|---|---|---|\n| Pulmonary Embolism | Deep Venous Thrombosis (DVT) | Pulmonary arteries (often lower lobes, esp. right inferior) |\n| Arterial Embolism | Cardiac (e.g., AFib, MI) | Systemic arteries (e.g., cerebral, mesenteric, limb) |\n| Fat Embolism | Long bone fractures | Pulmonary capillaries, cerebral circulation |\n| Air Embolism | Venous access, surgery, trauma | Right heart, pulmonary arteries |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Gravity and flow dictate PE location: think right, think low.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT Pulmonary Angiogram (CTPA), a pulmonary embolism appears as a filling defect within the contrast-enhanced pulmonary arterial lumen, often seen in the segmental or subsegmental branches of the right inferior lobe.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\n2019 ESC Guidelines for the diagnosis and management of acute pulmonary embolism: Recommends CTPA as the primary imaging modality for suspected PE in hemodynamically stable patients.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Right superior lobe | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Right middle lobe | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Right inferior lobe | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Left superior lobe | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: ?) Venous embolism** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Competency 2500**\n"
