  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Silent lung cancer demands vigilance; screen high-risk patients.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe statement 'It is never asymptomatic' is false regarding lung carcinoma, making it the correct answer to the 'except' question. Lung cancer, particularly in its early stages, frequently presents without symptoms and is often discovered incidentally.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nLung carcinoma's asymptomatic nature stems from its ability to grow in the lung periphery without impinging on airways or nerves, or causing significant inflammation until advanced stages. This silent progression is a major reason for delayed diagnosis and highlights the importance of screening programs for high-risk individuals, as early detection significantly improves prognosis. The absence of symptoms does not preclude the presence of malignancy.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): May present as a coin lesion in the periphery of lung is true. Adenocarcinoma, a common type of lung cancer, frequently presents as a peripheral solitary pulmonary nodule or 'coin lesion'.\nOption C (Incorrect): Hemoptysis is common is true. Hemoptysis is a classic symptom of lung cancer, especially with central tumors or those invading blood vessels.\nOption D (Incorrect): Dry nonproductive cough may be the only symptom is true. A persistent cough, even if dry, can be an early and sometimes the only symptom of lung cancer, often due to bronchial irritation.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Lung Carcinoma | Granuloma |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Asymptomatic Presentation** | Common (especially early stages) | Very common |\n| **Coin Lesion** | Yes (e.g., adenocarcinoma) | Yes (e.g., histoplasmoma, tuberculoma) |\n| **Growth Pattern** | Progressive, infiltrative, often rapid | Stable or slow growth, often calcified |\n| **Management** | Resection, chemotherapy, radiation | Observation, anti-infectives if active infection |\n| **PET Avidity** | Typically high | Variable, can be high in active inflammation |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Early lung cancer often whispers, not shouts.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT, an asymptomatic lung carcinoma often appears as a non-calcified, spiculated, or lobulated solitary pulmonary nodule, frequently in the lung periphery, discovered incidentally on imaging for other reasons.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nUSPSTF Lung Cancer Screening Guidelines (2021): Recommends annual low-dose CT screening for adults aged 50 to 80 years with a 20 pack-year smoking history who currently smoke or have quit within the past 15 years.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | It is never asymtomatic | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | May present as a coin lesion in the periphery of lung | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Hemoptysis is common | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Dry nonproductive cough may be the only symptom | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: ?) granuloma** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Competency 2500**\n"
