  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Local spread can be cut, distant spread cannot.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is D. Extension to the adjacent lobe, while indicating advanced local disease (T3 or T4), does not inherently signify incurability as it may still be amenable to surgical resection. In contrast, the other options represent either distant metastatic disease or locally advanced disease that is generally considered unresectable for cure.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nLung cancer resectability is primarily determined by the TNM staging system. While T3 and some T4 tumors (e.g., separate nodules in an ipsilateral non-primary lobe) can be surgically managed, involvement of critical mediastinal structures (like the recurrent laryngeal nerve) or N3 nodal disease (like scalene nodes) typically precludes curative resection. Distant metastases (M1 disease, such as hepatic mets) unequivocally indicate systemic disease beyond surgical cure.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Recurrent laryngeal nerve paralysis indicates invasion of the nerve, often by mediastinal tumor or lymph nodes (T4 or N2/N3), making curative resection highly unlikely.\nOption B (Incorrect): Involvement of scalene nodes signifies N3 disease, which is considered regionally advanced and generally unresectable for cure.\nOption C (Incorrect): Hepatic metastasis represents M1b disease, indicating distant spread and thus incurable systemic disease.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Resectability for Cure | TNM Stage Implication |\n|---|---|---|\n| Extension to adjacent lobe (ipsilateral) | Potentially resectable | T3 or T4 |\n| Recurrent laryngeal nerve paralysis | Generally unresectable | T4 or N2/N3 |\n| Scalene node involvement | Generally unresectable | N3 |\n| Hepatic metastasis | Incurable | M1b |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Incurability in lung cancer often means N3, M1, or extensive T4 disease.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT, extension to an adjacent lobe might appear as a separate nodule or direct invasion across a fissure. Intraoperatively, this would be confirmed by visual inspection and palpation, potentially requiring a bilobectomy or pneumonectomy.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNational Comprehensive Cancer Network (NCCN) Guidelines for Non-Small Cell Lung Cancer (2023). These guidelines provide comprehensive recommendations for staging, treatment, and resectability criteria based on TNM staging.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Recurrent laryngeal nerve paralysis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Involvement of scalene nodes | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Hepatic metastasis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Extension to the adjacent lobe | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: ?) Thoracotomy and ligation of bleeding vessel** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Competency 2500**\n"
