  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Lymphoma: The mediastinum's most frequent uninvited guest.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nLymphoma is indeed the most common tumor of the mediastinum. It frequently presents in the anterior and middle mediastinal compartments, often as part of a systemic disease process, making it the most prevalent overall.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nLymphoma arises from lymphoid tissue, which is abundant throughout the mediastinum, particularly in the thymus and lymph nodes. Its prevalence across different age groups and its ability to involve multiple mediastinal compartments contribute to its status as the most common mediastinal malignancy. Understanding its varied presentations is crucial for timely diagnosis and appropriate management.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Neurogenic tumors are the most common tumors of the posterior mediastinum, but not the most common overall across all compartments.\nOption B (Incorrect): Teratodermoids (germ cell tumors) are common in the anterior mediastinum but are less frequent than lymphoma when considering all mediastinal compartments.\nOption D (Incorrect): Thymoma is the most common primary tumor of the anterior mediastinum, but lymphoma is more common when considering all mediastinal compartments and types of tumors.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Mediastinal Compartment | Most Common Tumor Type | Key Characteristics |\n|---|---|---|\n| Anterior | Thymoma, Lymphoma, Germ Cell Tumors (Teratoma), Thyroid | \"The 4 Ts\": Thymoma, Teratoma, Thyroid, (T-cell) Lymphoma |\n| Middle | Lymphoma, Bronchogenic Cysts, Pericardial Cysts | Often associated with lymphadenopathy or developmental cysts |\n| Posterior | Neurogenic Tumors (e.g., Schwannoma, Neurofibroma) | Arise from nerves, often benign, can cause spinal cord compression |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Think \"4 Ts\" for anterior mediastinum, but Lymphoma rules overall.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT, lymphoma often appears as a bulky, lobulated, enhancing mass, frequently with associated lymphadenopathy in multiple mediastinal stations. Biopsy (core needle or excisional) is essential for definitive diagnosis and subtyping.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for Hodgkin Lymphoma (2023) and Non-Hodgkin Lymphoma (2023). These guidelines provide comprehensive recommendations for diagnosis, staging, and treatment of mediastinal lymphoma.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Neurogenic | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Teratodermoids | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Lymphoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Thymoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: ?) Fresh lesion with positive sputum without any antituberculous treatment** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Competency 2500**\n"
