  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Breast cancer: Know your subtypes, save a life.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe verified answer is Breast cancer. This topic encompasses a broad range of clinical presentations, diagnostic modalities, and treatment strategies, making it a cornerstone of surgical oncology. Understanding its pathophysiology and management is crucial for surgical trainees.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nBreast cancer is a heterogeneous disease, classified by molecular subtypes (Luminal A, Luminal B, HER2-enriched, Triple-negative) which dictate prognosis and targeted therapies. Surgical management involves lumpectomy with radiation or mastectomy, often combined with sentinel lymph node biopsy or axillary lymph node dissection to assess nodal status. Adjuvant systemic therapies, including chemotherapy, hormone therapy, and HER2-targeted agents, are tailored based on tumor characteristics and stage, significantly improving outcomes.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): This option describes an anatomical relationship unrelated to breast cancer. \nOption B (Incorrect): This question pertains to respiratory anatomy and foreign body aspiration, not breast cancer. \nOption C (Incorrect): This statement describes a characteristic of the right bronchus, irrelevant to breast cancer. \nOption D (Incorrect): This statement describes a characteristic of the right bronchus, irrelevant to breast cancer.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Subtype | Characteristics | Treatment Implications |\n|---|---|---|\n| Luminal A | ER+/PR+, HER2-, low Ki-67 | Endocrine therapy, good prognosis |\n| Luminal B | ER+/PR+, HER2- or +, high Ki-67 | Endocrine therapy, chemotherapy often, worse prognosis than A |\n| HER2-enriched | HER2+, ER-/PR- or + | HER2-targeted therapy (e.g., trastuzumab), chemotherapy |\n| Triple-negative | ER-/PR-/HER2- | Chemotherapy, immunotherapy for some, aggressive |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Molecular subtype dictates breast cancer treatment and prognosis.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nMammography reveals suspicious masses, calcifications, or architectural distortion. On ultrasound, breast cancers often appear as irregular, hypoechoic masses with posterior shadowing. Intraoperatively, sentinel lymph node biopsy uses blue dye and/or radiotracer to identify the first draining lymph nodes.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Clinical Practice Guidelines in Oncology (2023) for Breast Cancer. Recommends multidisciplinary approach for diagnosis, staging, and treatment planning, emphasizing personalized care based on tumor biology.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | It lies anterior to the esophagus | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Why do inhaled foreign bodies more often lodge in the right bronchus? | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Right bronchus is narrower than left | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Right bronchus is longer than left | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: ?) Breast cancer** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Competency 2500**\n"
