  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 New kidney, new neighborhood: the iliac fossa!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is C. The donor kidney is most commonly placed in the right iliac fossa during transplantation. This heterotopic placement provides optimal surgical access and vascular connections.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe right iliac fossa is the preferred site due to its anatomical advantages. It offers readily accessible large vessels, specifically the external iliac artery and vein, for robust vascular anastomoses. Furthermore, its proximity to the bladder facilitates a tension-free ureteroneocystostomy, minimizing complications. This location also allows for easier palpation and ultrasound surveillance of the allograft post-operatively.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (In the place of recipients kidney) (Incorrect): Orthotopic placement is technically more challenging, requires extensive dissection, and is rarely performed due to higher morbidity and lack of space.\nOption B (In the pelvis) (Incorrect): While the iliac fossa is part of the pelvis, 'in the pelvis' is too broad and less precise. The specific location is the iliac fossa.\nOption D (Rutherford–Morrisons pouch) (Incorrect): Rutherford–Morrisons pouch is a peritoneal space located between the liver and the right kidney. It is not a site for kidney transplantation; it's more relevant in trauma or fluid collection scenarios.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Native Kidney | Transplanted Kidney |\n|---|---|---|\n| Location | Retroperitoneal, lumbar region | Heterotopic, right iliac fossa (extraperitoneal) |\n| Vascular Supply | Renal artery/vein from aorta/IVC | External iliac artery/vein |\n| Ureteral Anastomosis | Ureter to bladder | Ureteroneocystostomy |\n| Palpability | Deep, often not palpable | Superficial, often palpable |\n| Surgical Approach | Flank incision | Oblique lower abdominal incision |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Transplant kidneys go in the iliac fossa, not where the old ones were.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIntraoperatively, you would see the donor kidney positioned extraperitoneally in the right iliac fossa, with its renal artery anastomosed to the external iliac artery and the renal vein to the external iliac vein. On post-operative ultrasound, the transplanted kidney would be visible in the lower right quadrant, typically superficial to the psoas muscle.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Society of Transplant Surgeons (ASTS) Guidelines (Ongoing): These guidelines emphasize standardized surgical techniques for kidney transplantation, consistently recommending the iliac fossa for optimal outcomes.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | In the place of recipients kidney | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | In the pelvis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Right iliac fossa | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Rutherford–Morrisons pouch | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: ?) Combined organ transplant** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Competency 2500**\n"
