  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 FTSG: Small, beautiful, less shrink; STSG: Big, quick, more crinkle.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe question asks to identify which statement is NOT an advantage of free full thickness skin grafts (FTSG). The correct answer, 'Ideal for large raw areas,' is a disadvantage, as FTSGs are limited by donor site size and cannot be meshed, making them unsuitable for extensive defects.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nFull thickness skin grafts include the entire epidermis and dermis, offering superior cosmetic results, better color match, and reduced primary contracture compared to split-thickness skin grafts. Their thicker dermal component provides more robust tissue, leading to less secondary contracture and greater durability. However, this thickness also limits their donor site availability and makes them less viable for very large defects, as they require primary closure of the donor site and cannot be expanded by meshing.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Cosmetically better is an advantage of FTSG due to the inclusion of the full dermis, leading to better texture, color, and less pigmentary changes compared to STSG.\nOption C (Incorrect): Does not produce contracture is an advantage of FTSG, as the full dermal layer significantly reduces both primary and secondary wound contracture compared to STSG.\nOption D (Correct): Ideal for large raw areas is NOT an advantage. FTSGs are limited by donor site size and cannot be meshed, making them unsuitable for large defects.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Full Thickness Skin Graft (FTSG) | Split Thickness Skin Graft (STSG) |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Thickness** | Epidermis + entire dermis | Epidermis + partial dermis |\n| **Contracture** | Minimal primary & secondary | Significant primary & secondary |\n| **Cosmesis** | Excellent (color, texture) | Fair (pigment changes, shiny) |\n| **Donor Site** | Requires primary closure, limited size | Heals by re-epithelialization, larger areas |\n| **Take** | More demanding, less reliable | More reliable, especially on poor beds |\n| **Use for Large Areas** | No, limited by donor site | Yes, can be meshed & harvested from large areas |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: FTSG for quality, STSG for quantity.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIntraoperatively, FTSGs appear thicker and more opaque than STSGs. The donor site for an FTSG must be closed primarily, often requiring local flap advancement or undermining, whereas an STSG donor site will have a raw, bleeding surface that heals by re-epithelialization.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Society of Plastic Surgeons (ASPS) Clinical Practice Guideline for Skin Grafting (2018). Recommends FTSG for areas requiring minimal contracture and superior cosmesis, and STSG for large defects or less critical areas.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | except | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Cosmetically better | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Does not produce contracture | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Ideal for large raw areas | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: ?) Anaerobic streptococci** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Competency 2500**\n"
