  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Distal tibia: Small bone, big impact on mobility.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe lower end of the tibia is a critical weight-bearing structure forming the superior aspect of the ankle joint. Its complex anatomy and articulation with the talus make it prone to specific injury patterns and pathologies, particularly high-energy fractures.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe distal tibia, also known as the tibial plafond, is essential for ankle stability and function. It comprises the medial malleolus, the anterior and posterior tubercles, and the articular surface that forms the roof of the ankle mortise. The incisura fibularis accommodates the distal fibula, stabilized by the syndesmotic ligaments. Injuries to this region, such as pilon fractures, often involve significant articular damage and comminution, necessitating precise anatomical reduction and stable fixation to prevent post-traumatic arthritis.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): This option refers to a biopsy technique, which is unrelated to the anatomy or pathology of the lower end of the tibia. \nOption B (Incorrect): This option is a question about X-ray views for mandibular lesions, entirely unrelated to the lower end of the tibia. \nOption C (Incorrect): This option refers to an X-ray view, but in the context of mandibular lesions, not the lower end of the tibia. \nOption D (Incorrect): This option refers to an X-ray view, but in the context of mandibular lesions, not the lower end of the tibia.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Imaging View | Purpose | Key Structures Visualized |\n|---|---|---|\n| Anteroposterior (AP) | General overview, malleoli | Tibial plafond, medial malleolus, fibula |\n| Lateral | Sagittal view, posterior structures | Posterior malleolus, talar dome, calcaneus |\n| Mortise | Ankle mortise integrity | Tibiotalar clear space, syndesmosis |\n| CT Scan | Complex fractures, articular step-off | 3D reconstruction, pilon fractures |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Pilon fractures demand meticulous articular reduction for optimal outcomes.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT, pilon fractures often show comminution of the tibial plafond with articular impaction, requiring careful pre-operative planning for reduction and fixation. Intraoperatively, direct visualization of the articular surface is paramount to ensure anatomical alignment.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nOrthopaedic Trauma Association (OTA) Classification of Pilon Fractures (2018): Recommends CT for detailed assessment and guides surgical approach based on fracture pattern and soft tissue status.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Biopsy from the edge of ulcer | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Which view is the best X-ray investigation to diagnose mandibular lesions? | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Antero-posterior view | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Lateral view | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: ?) Lower end of tibia** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Competency 2500**\n"
