  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 BCC: It creeps, it doesn't leap.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe verified answer, \"Local infiltration,\" correctly identifies the primary and most characteristic mode of spread for basal cell carcinoma (BCC). While the question itself, \"Lower end of tibia,\" is anatomically distinct, the options and the correct answer clearly pertain to tumor dissemination. This answer highlights the localized growth pattern of BCC.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nBasal cell carcinoma is a slow-growing, locally invasive tumor originating from the basal layer of the epidermis. Its hallmark is direct extension into surrounding tissues, often forming a 'palisading' pattern on histology. This local infiltration can be highly destructive, eroding cartilage, bone, and other structures if left untreated, but it rarely metastasizes. Surgical excision with clear margins is the primary treatment, reflecting its localized nature and the importance of addressing its infiltrative growth.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Upper end of tibia) (Incorrect): This option is an anatomical location completely unrelated to the mechanism of tumor spread.\nOption B (How does basal cell carcinoma spreads?) (Incorrect): This is a question, not an answer describing a mechanism of spread.\nOption C (Lymphatic spread) (Incorrect): While some cancers spread via lymphatics, BCC rarely does, making this an incorrect primary mode of spread.\nOption D (Blood spread) (Incorrect): Hematogenous spread is extremely rare for BCC, typically reserved for highly aggressive or neglected cases, not its characteristic mode.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Cancer Type | Primary Spread Mechanism | Metastatic Potential |\n|---|---|---|\n| Basal Cell Carcinoma | Local Infiltration | Very Low |\n| Squamous Cell Carcinoma | Local Infiltration, Lymphatic | Low to Moderate |\n| Melanoma | Lymphatic, Hematogenous | High |\n| Adenocarcinoma (e.g., Colon) | Local Infiltration, Lymphatic, Hematogenous | Moderate to High |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: BCC: Local destruction, rare metastasis.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIntraoperatively, BCC often appears as a pearly nodule with telangiectasias, sometimes with central ulceration. During excision, the surgeon must ensure clear margins, often confirmed by frozen section, as the tumor can have subclinical extensions that are not grossly visible.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNational Comprehensive Cancer Network (NCCN) Guidelines for Basal Cell Skin Cancer (2023). These guidelines recommend complete surgical excision with clear margins as the primary treatment for BCC, emphasizing its local nature and infiltrative growth.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Upper end of tibia | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | How does basal cell carcinoma spreads? | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Lymphatic spread | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Blood spread | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: ?) Local infiltration** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Competency 2500**\n"
