  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't guess with glans lesions; biopsy for certainty.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe question asks for a differential diagnosis for carcinoma of the glans penis. The verified answer, \"Tuberculosis of skin,\" highlights a critical clinical mimic. Both conditions can present as chronic, ulcerative, or infiltrative lesions on the glans, making clinical differentiation challenging.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nPenile carcinoma typically manifests as a chronic, progressive lesion, often fungating or ulcerative, with potential for local invasion and inguinal lymphadenopathy. Penile tuberculosis, though rare, can present with remarkably similar features, including chronic ulceration, induration, and even regional lymph node involvement. This clinical overlap underscores the necessity of histological confirmation for any suspicious penile lesion, as clinical appearance alone is insufficient to distinguish between these serious conditions.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Cutaneous lesions in HIV infection) (Incorrect): This is a broad category of conditions associated with HIV, not a specific mimic for penile carcinoma in the same direct clinical presentation as tuberculosis.\nOption B (Ulcerated dermoid cyst) (Incorrect): Dermoid cysts are benign congenital lesions. While they can ulcerate if infected or traumatized, they are typically soft, mobile, and do not exhibit the infiltrative growth characteristic of carcinoma.\nOption C (Ulcerated epidermoid cyst) (Incorrect): Similar to dermoid cysts, epidermoid cysts are benign and usually well-circumscribed. Ulceration is typically secondary to infection or trauma, and they do not mimic the primary infiltrative nature of a carcinoma.\nOption D (Why do Marjolin’s ulcer not spread to lymph nodes?) (Incorrect): This is a question, not a differential diagnosis. Furthermore, Marjolin's ulcer, which is a squamous cell carcinoma arising in chronic wounds, is known to have a high propensity for aggressive local invasion and regional lymph node metastasis.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Penile Carcinoma | Penile Tuberculosis | Syphilitic Chancre | Chancroid |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| **Etiology** | HPV, phimosis, poor hygiene | *Mycobacterium tuberculosis* | *Treponema pallidum* | *Haemophilus ducreyi* |\n| **Appearance** | Chronic ulcer, fungating mass, indurated plaque | Chronic ulcer, nodule, sinus tract, induration | Painless, clean-based, indurated ulcer | Painful, ragged, undermined ulcer with purulent base |\n| **Lymphadenopathy** | Inguinal, often firm, non-tender | Inguinal, often firm, non-tender, sometimes suppurative | Inguinal, firm, non-tender (bubo) | Inguinal, painful, suppurative (bubo) |\n| **Diagnosis** | Biopsy (histopathology) | Biopsy (histopathology, AFB stain, culture) | Darkfield microscopy, serology | Gram stain, culture, PCR |\n| **Treatment** | Surgery, radiation, chemotherapy | Anti-tuberculous drugs | Penicillin | Azithromycin, ceftriaxone, ciprofloxacin, erythromycin |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Chronic penile ulcer? Biopsy is your best friend.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn MRI, penile carcinoma typically appears as an enhancing mass with local invasion into the corpora. Intraoperatively, carcinoma is firm, infiltrative, and may show extension into surrounding structures. Penile tuberculosis might show similar infiltrative patterns but often with granulomatous tissue and caseous necrosis.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nThe European Association of Urology (EAU) Guidelines on Penile Cancer (2023) recommend biopsy for any suspicious penile lesion to establish a definitive diagnosis and guide management.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Cutaneous lesions in HIV infection | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Ulcerated dermoid cyst | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Ulcerated epidermoid cyst | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Why do Marjolin’s ulcer not spread to lymph nodes? | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: ?) Tuberculosis of skin** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Competency 2500**\n"
