  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Verrucous carcinoma: Warty, slow, and rarely spreads.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe verdict is ACCEPT. Verrucous carcinoma is a distinct, well-differentiated variant of squamous cell carcinoma characterized by its slow growth, exophytic nature, and notably low metastatic potential. The statement that it 'spreads rapidly to lymph nodes' is false, making it the correct answer to an 'except' question.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nVerrucous carcinoma exhibits a unique pushing, rather than infiltrative, growth pattern, which is the primary reason for its indolent course and rarity of metastasis. Histologically, it is characterized by broad, bulbous rete ridges with extensive parakeratosis and minimal cellular atypia, indicating a high degree of differentiation. This lack of deep invasion and anaplastic features anatomically explains why lymph node involvement is exceedingly rare, typically only occurring if there's anaplastic transformation or invasion beyond its usual boundaries.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption C (Incorrect): Slow growing. This is a true characteristic of verrucous carcinoma, which is known for its indolent clinical course.\nOption D (Incorrect): Exophytic. This is also a true characteristic, describing its typical warty, cauliflower-like gross appearance.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Verrucous Carcinoma | Conventional SCC |\n|---|---|---|\n| Growth Pattern | Exophytic, pushing | Exophytic or infiltrative |\n| Metastatic Potential | Very low, rare | Moderate to high |\n| Differentiation | Well-differentiated | Variable (well to poorly) |\n| Treatment | Wide local excision | Wide local excision, +/- lymphadenectomy, radiation |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Verrucous carcinoma: locally aggressive, but rarely metastasizes.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn imaging (CT/MRI), verrucous carcinoma typically appears as a large, exophytic, fungating mass with a broad base, often with superficial erosion but without deep invasion into underlying structures or significant lymphadenopathy. Intraoperatively, it presents as a bulky, warty, often white or gray lesion with a firm, non-infiltrative base.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for Squamous Cell Carcinoma of the Skin (2023). These guidelines recognize verrucous carcinoma as a low-risk variant of SCC, recommending wide local excision with clear margins as the primary treatment, and generally not advocating for elective lymph node dissection due to its low metastatic potential.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | except | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Spreads rapidly to lymph nodes | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Slow growing | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Exophytic | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: ?) Spreads only if crosses boundary of scar** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Competency 2500**\n"
