  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Lung cancer: A silent killer, often linked to smoke, demanding early detection.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe provided 'Verified Answer' of 'Lung cancer' is critically mismatched with the question 'Tubulo-embryonic dermoids' and its options, which relate to pediatric neural tumors. Assuming 'Lung cancer' is the intended correct answer despite this discrepancy, this debrief will proceed with that premise, focusing on key aspects of lung cancer.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nLung cancer is a leading cause of cancer-related mortality worldwide, primarily categorized into non-small cell lung cancer (NSCLC) and small cell lung cancer (SCLC). NSCLC accounts for approximately 85% of cases and includes adenocarcinoma, squamous cell carcinoma, and large cell carcinoma. Its pathogenesis is strongly linked to smoking, though adenocarcinoma can occur in non-smokers. Early detection and accurate staging are crucial for determining prognosis and guiding treatment, which often involves surgery, chemotherapy, radiation, and targeted therapies or immunotherapy.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): 'What is the true neuroma that occur in young children called?' This is a question, not an answer, and is unrelated to lung cancer.\nOption B (Incorrect): 'Ganglioneuroma' is a benign tumor of the sympathetic nervous system, typically found in children, and is not lung cancer.\nOption C (Incorrect): 'Neuroblastoma' is a malignant tumor of the sympathetic nervous system, primarily affecting infants and young children, and is not lung cancer.\nOption D (Incorrect): 'Myelinic neuroma' is a term not commonly used in standard oncology; neuromas are generally benign nerve sheath tumors, distinct from lung cancer.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Non-Small Cell Lung Cancer (NSCLC) | Small Cell Lung Cancer (SCLC) |\n|---|---|---|\n| Incidence | ~85% of lung cancers | ~15% of lung cancers |\n| Histology | Adenocarcinoma, Squamous Cell Carcinoma, Large Cell Carcinoma | Small, round/oval cells with scant cytoplasm |\n| Growth Rate | Slower | Rapid |\n| Metastasis | Later, but common | Early and widespread |\n| Treatment | Surgery, radiation, chemotherapy, targeted therapy, immunotherapy | Chemotherapy, radiation (often concurrent), immunotherapy |\n| Prognosis | Generally better if localized | Poor, even with treatment, due to early metastasis |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Smoking is the primary risk factor for lung cancer, but adenocarcinoma can occur in non-smokers.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT, lung cancer often appears as a solitary pulmonary nodule or mass, sometimes with spiculation, lobulation, or cavitation. Intraoperatively, tumors can range from small, firm nodules to large, infiltrative masses, often requiring lobectomy or pneumonectomy with lymph node dissection.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNational Comprehensive Cancer Network (NCCN) Guidelines for Lung Cancer (2023). These guidelines provide comprehensive recommendations for screening, diagnosis, staging, and treatment of both NSCLC and SCLC.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | What is the true neuroma that occur in young children called? | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Ganglioneuroma | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Neuroblastoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Myelinic neuroma | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: ?) Lung cancer** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Competency 2500**\n"
