  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Cysts get infected or bleed; sternomastoid tumors are muscle, not cysts.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe verified answer, \"Sternomastoid tumor,\" is correct because it is not a complication of a true cyst. True cysts are epithelial-lined sacs that can develop various issues, but a sternomastoid tumor is a distinct fibrotic mass of the sternocleidomastoid muscle, typically seen in infants, unrelated to cyst complications.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nTrue cysts are pathological cavities lined by epithelium, which can undergo secondary changes. Common complications include infection due to bacterial colonization, hemorrhage from vascular compromise or trauma, and malignant transformation, particularly in certain types of cysts like ovarian, pancreatic, or choledochal cysts. A sternomastoid tumor, however, is a benign fibrous mass within the sternocleidomastoid muscle, often presenting as a neck mass in neonates and associated with congenital muscular torticollis, representing a distinct pathological entity entirely separate from cyst complications.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Infection is a common complication of true cysts, especially if they communicate with a surface or become secondarily contaminated.\nOption C (Incorrect): Haemorrhage can occur within a true cyst due to trauma, rupture of small vessels in the cyst wall, or intrinsic bleeding disorders.\nOption D (Incorrect): Malignancy is a known, albeit less common, complication of certain true cysts, such as some ovarian cysts, pancreatic cysts (e.g., mucinous cystic neoplasms), or choledochal cysts.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | True Cyst Complications | Sternomastoid Tumor |\n|---|---|---|\n| Etiology | Infection, hemorrhage, malignant transformation | Fibrosis of sternocleidomastoid muscle, often birth trauma/ischemia |\n| Pathology | Secondary changes within an epithelial-lined sac | Benign fibrous mass within muscle |\n| Clinical Presentation | Variable, depending on cyst location and complication | Firm, non-tender neck mass in infant, often with torticollis |\n| Management | Drainage, excision, specific cancer treatment | Physical therapy, rarely surgical release |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: A sternomastoid tumor is a muscle pathology, not a cyst complication.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound, a sternomastoid tumor appears as a fusiform, hypoechoic, or heterogeneous mass within the sternocleidomastoid muscle, without cystic components or vascular flow. Intraoperatively, it's a firm, fibrous enlargement of the muscle.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Academy of Orthopaedic Surgeons (AAOS) Clinical Practice Guideline (2018): Management of Congenital Muscular Torticollis. It recommends physical therapy as the primary treatment for sternomastoid tumors causing torticollis.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | The complication of true cysts include the following except | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Infection | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Haemorrhage | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Malignancy | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: ?) Sternomastoid tumor** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Competency 2500**\n"
