  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Unilateral is common, but bilateral cryptorchidism is no myth!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe verified answer \"Occurs unilaterally\" is correct because cryptorchidism, while predominantly unilateral, can also occur bilaterally in a significant minority of cases. Therefore, stating it *always* occurs unilaterally is false, making it the correct exception to the implied question \"Regarding cryptorchidism, all of the following are true EXCEPT:\".\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nCryptorchidism, or undescended testis, is a common congenital anomaly. While approximately 80-85% of cases involve only one testis, the condition is bilateral in 15-20% of affected individuals. This bilateral presentation is crucial to recognize as it carries implications for fertility and management. The statement that cryptorchidism \"Occurs unilaterally\" is thus an oversimplification and not universally true, making it the correct answer to an \"except\" question.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption C (Incorrect): Associated with inguinal hernia. This is a true statement. A patent processus vaginalis is often associated with cryptorchidism, predisposing to indirect inguinal hernias.\nOption D (Incorrect): Associated with torsion of spermatic cord. This is a true statement. Undescended testes are at a higher risk of spermatic cord torsion due to abnormal fixation and mobility.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Unilateral Cryptorchidism | Bilateral Cryptorchidism | Normal Testis |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Incidence | ~80-85% of cases | ~15-20% of cases | N/A |\n| Fertility Impact | Reduced, but often preserved | Significantly reduced or absent | Normal |\n| Malignancy Risk | Increased in both testes | Increased in both testes | Baseline |\n| Management | Orchiopexy of affected testis | Orchiopexy of both testes | N/A |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Cryptorchidism is usually unilateral, but don't forget bilateral cases.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound, an undescended testis may be visualized in the inguinal canal or abdomen, often smaller and less echogenic than a normally descended testis. Intraoperatively, the testis may be found anywhere along its normal path of descent, from the retroperitoneum to the superficial inguinal pouch.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Urological Association (AUA) Guideline 2014 (reaffirmed 2018): Recommends surgical correction (orchiopexy) for cryptorchidism between 6 and 18 months of age.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Regarding cryptorchidism all of the following are true | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | except | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Associated with inguinal hernia | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Associated with torsion of spermatic cord | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: ?) Occurs unilaterally** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Competency 2500**\n"
