  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't be fooled: even big stones bleed!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nACCEPT. The question asks for the statement that is *not* true regarding staghorn calculus. Hematuria is a common symptom of kidney stones, including staghorn calculi, making the statement 'Haematuria is rare' incorrect and thus the correct answer to the 'except' question.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nStaghorn calculi are large, branched stones that fill the renal collecting system, causing significant irritation and trauma to the urothelium. This mechanical irritation frequently leads to microscopic or gross hematuria. Furthermore, these stones are often associated with chronic infection, which can also contribute to inflammation and bleeding within the urinary tract, making hematuria a common finding.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Staghorn calculi are primarily composed of struvite (magnesium ammonium phosphate) and often contain calcium phosphate, making the description largely accurate.\nOption B (Incorrect): By definition, staghorn calculi are large, branched stones that occupy a significant portion of the renal pelvis and calyces, making them among the largest renal stones.\nOption C (Incorrect): These stones are typically infection stones, often caused by urease-producing bacteria, and are notorious for harboring bacteria, leading to persistent and recurrent urinary tract infections.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Staghorn Calculus | Calcium Oxalate Stone | Uric Acid Stone |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Composition | Struvite (MgNH4PO4), +/- Calcium Apatite | Calcium Oxalate Monohydrate/Dihydrate | Uric Acid |\n| Etiology | Infection (urease-producing bacteria) | Hypercalciuria, hyperoxaluria | Hyperuricosuria, low urine pH |\n| Radiopacity | Moderately radiopaque | Highly radiopaque | Radiolucent |\n| Associated Symptoms | Recurrent UTIs, hematuria, flank pain | Hematuria, renal colic | Hematuria, renal colic, gout |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Hematuria is common with all kidney stones, even large, asymptomatic ones.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT, staghorn calculi appear as large, branched, moderately radiopaque filling defects within the renal collecting system, often with associated hydronephrosis or perinephric stranding. Intraoperatively, they are firm, often friable, and conform to the collecting system's shape.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Urological Association (AUA) 2023 Guideline for the Management of Kidney Stones. Recommends percutaneous nephrolithotomy (PCNL) as the primary treatment for most staghorn calculi.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | It is made of calcium, ammonium and magnesium salt of phosphorus | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | It is one the largest stones occurring in renal pelvis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Produces recurrent infection | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Haematuria is rare | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: ?) Size of the prostate** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Competency 2500**\n"
