  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Hard testicle? Don't poke it, remove it (inguinally)!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe provided 'VERIFIED ANSWER' of 'Hypertension is rare' is incorrect and irrelevant to the question. The correct answer to the question 'All of the following can be done except' for a 50-year-old male with hard scrotal swelling is FNAC of testicular swelling. This procedure is generally contraindicated due to the significant risk of tumor seeding.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nSuspected testicular malignancy, presenting as a hard scrotal swelling, necessitates a careful diagnostic and therapeutic approach. Fine Needle Aspiration Cytology (FNAC) is avoided due to the high risk of tumor cell dissemination along the needle tract, potentially contaminating the scrotum and altering lymphatic drainage patterns. This could upstage the disease and complicate subsequent management, including the need for more extensive surgery or radiation to the scrotum. Instead, an inguinal approach for orchiectomy allows for high ligation of the spermatic cord, minimizing systemic tumor spread and providing definitive histopathological diagnosis.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Chest X-ray is a standard part of staging for suspected testicular cancer to detect pulmonary metastases.\nOption B (Incorrect): Inguinal exploration is the gold standard surgical approach for suspected testicular malignancy, allowing for high cord ligation and definitive diagnosis/treatment.\nOption D (Incorrect): CT abdomen is crucial for staging testicular cancer, primarily to identify retroperitoneal lymph node involvement.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Procedure | Indication | Contraindication/Caution |\n|---|---|---|\n| Scrotal Ultrasound | Initial imaging for any scrotal mass to differentiate solid from cystic, intra- from extra-testicular | None |\n| Inguinal Exploration/Orchiectomy | Suspected testicular malignancy | None (it's the treatment/definitive diagnosis) |\n| FNAC of Testicular Mass | Rarely indicated for testicular masses; sometimes for epididymal lesions or inflammatory processes | Suspected testicular malignancy due to seeding risk |\n| Tumor Markers (AFP, hCG, LDH) | Suspected testicular germ cell tumor (diagnostic and monitoring) | Not a standalone diagnostic for malignancy |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Never biopsy a suspected testicular tumor trans-scrotally; always perform inguinal orchiectomy.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn scrotal ultrasound, a solid, hypoechoic, often heterogeneous intratesticular mass is highly suspicious for malignancy. Intraoperatively during inguinal exploration, if a suspicious mass is found, a radical orchiectomy with high ligation of the spermatic cord is performed.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for Testicular Cancer (2023). Recommends inguinal orchiectomy for suspected malignancy and discourages trans-scrotal biopsy.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Chest X-ray | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Inguinal exploration | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | FNAC of testicular swelling | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | CT abdomen | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: ?) Hypertension is rare** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Competency 2500**\n"
