  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't cut what you can cure with meds.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nOrchidectomy is the surgical removal of one or both testicles. This question assesses the appropriate indications for orchidectomy across various clinical scenarios. The correct answer is Acute epididymo-orchitis, as orchidectomy is not a primary treatment for this inflammatory condition.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nOrchidectomy is a definitive surgical procedure with specific, often critical, indications. For advanced prostate cancer and hormone-sensitive male breast cancer, it serves as a form of androgen deprivation therapy, effectively reducing testosterone production to slow disease progression. In cases of late testicular torsion, orchidectomy is crucial to remove non-viable tissue, preventing severe complications like infection, intractable pain, and potential autoimmune damage to the contralateral testis. However, acute epididymo-orchitis is primarily an inflammatory process managed medically with antibiotics and anti-inflammatory drugs, making orchidectomy an inappropriate initial or routine intervention.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Prostate cancer. Bilateral orchidectomy is a well-established treatment for advanced prostate cancer, acting as surgical castration to reduce androgen levels and slow tumor growth.\nOption B (Incorrect): Male breast cancer. Orchidectomy can be indicated in hormone-sensitive male breast cancer to reduce androgen levels, which can be aromatized to estrogens, thus serving as an endocrine therapy.\nOption C (Incorrect): Late torsion testes. If testicular torsion is prolonged (e.g., >24 hours) and the testis is non-viable, orchidectomy is indicated to prevent infection, pain, and potential autoimmune damage to the contralateral testis.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Condition | Orchidectomy Indication | Primary Treatment | Rationale |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Prostate Cancer (advanced) | Yes (bilateral) | Androgen Deprivation Therapy | Reduces testosterone, slowing cancer growth |\n| Male Breast Cancer (hormone-sensitive) | Yes (bilateral) | Endocrine Therapy | Reduces androgens, which can be converted to estrogens |\n| Late Testicular Torsion | Yes (unilateral) | Surgical removal of non-viable testis | Prevents infection, pain, and systemic complications |\n| Acute Epididymo-orchitis | No (rarely for complications) | Antibiotics, anti-inflammatories | Inflammatory condition, usually resolves with medical management |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Orchidectomy is for cancer or non-viable tissue, not primary inflammation.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nFor acute epididymo-orchitis, ultrasound typically shows an enlarged, hyperemic epididymis and/or testis with increased blood flow on Doppler, differentiating it from torsion (absent flow). Intraoperatively, a torsed testis appears dark, necrotic, and non-viable, while an epididymo-orchitic testis would be inflamed but viable.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Urological Association (AUA) Guideline on Testicular Torsion (2017) recommends orchidectomy for non-viable testes. European Association of Urology (EAU) Guidelines on Prostate Cancer (2023) list surgical castration as an option for ADT.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Prostate cancer | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Male breast cancer | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Late torsion testes | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Acute epididymo-orchitis | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: ?) Transcrotal biopsy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Competency 2500**\n"
