  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Kidney masses stay on their side.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is that a renal mass typically does not cross the midline. This characteristic helps distinguish it from other abdominal masses and reflects its anatomical position within the retroperitoneum.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe kidneys are paired retroperitoneal organs situated in the lumbar region, lateral to the great vessels. Their normal anatomical confines mean that a mass originating from the kidney usually remains ipsilateral. While a very large renal tumor might extend medially, crossing the midline is not a defining characteristic, unlike masses originating from structures like the aorta, pancreas, or large bowel, which can more readily present as midline or contralateral masses. The retroperitoneal location also allows for respiratory movement and bimanual palpation/ballotability.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Renal masses move with respiration because the kidneys are retroperitoneal but are in contact with the diaphragm, which moves during breathing.\nOption B (Incorrect): Renal masses are often bimanually palpable, especially in slender patients or with larger tumors, due to their size and location between the anterior abdominal wall and the posterior lumbar muscles.\nOption C (Incorrect): Renal masses are ballotable, meaning they can be pushed away and rebound, due to their retroperitoneal position surrounded by perinephric fat and fascia, allowing for some mobility.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Characteristic | Renal Mass | Splenic Mass | Large Bowel Mass |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Moves with Respiration | Yes | Yes | Variable |\n| Bimanually Palpable | Yes | Yes | Yes |\n| Ballotable | Yes | No (often fixed) | No (often fixed) |\n| Crosses Midline | No (typically) | No (typically) | Yes (e.g., transverse colon) |\n| Location | Flank/Loin | Left upper quadrant | Variable (depends on segment) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Renal masses dance with breath, but rarely cross the midline.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT, a renal mass will be clearly delineated within the renal parenchyma, often displacing surrounding retroperitoneal fat. Intraoperatively, a renal mass is typically encapsulated within Gerota's fascia, allowing for mobilization and demonstrating its characteristic movement with respiration.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Urological Association (AUA) Guidelines on Renal Mass (2021). These guidelines provide recommendations for the evaluation and management of renal masses, emphasizing imaging characteristics and surgical approaches.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | It moves with respiration | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | It is bimanually palpable | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | It is ballotable | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | It crosses the midline | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: ?) High inguinal orchidectomy followed by radiotherapy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Competency 2500**\n"
