  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When it comes to stones, some waves are better than knives.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe verdict is ACCEPT. The correct answer, Extracorporeal shock-wave lithotripsy (ESWL), is indeed the technique among the options that is *not* an open surgical procedure for renal calculi. The other options describe various forms of open surgery.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nESWL is a non-invasive technique that utilizes focused high-energy sound waves generated outside the body to fragment kidney stones. These shock waves travel through soft tissues without causing significant damage, converging precisely on the stone. The repetitive impact of these waves causes the stone to break into smaller pieces, which can then be passed spontaneously in the urine. This method avoids the need for surgical incisions, reducing recovery time and surgical risks compared to open procedures.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Pyelolithotomy is an open surgical procedure involving an incision into the renal pelvis to directly remove stones.\nOption B (Incorrect): Nephrolithotomy is an open surgical procedure that involves an incision into the renal parenchyma (kidney tissue) to access and remove stones, typically for larger or more complex calculi.\nOption D (Incorrect): Extended pyelolithotomy is a variation of open pyelolithotomy, often implying a more extensive incision or dissection to remove larger or multiple stones from the renal pelvis and calyces.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Technique | Approach | Indication | Key Feature |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Pyelolithotomy | Open surgical | Renal pelvis stones | Incision into renal pelvis |\n| Nephrolithotomy | Open surgical | Large/complex renal stones | Incision into renal parenchyma |\n| ESWL | Non-invasive | Small to medium renal/ureteral stones | External shock waves |\n| Percutaneous Nephrolithotomy (PCNL) | Minimally invasive | Large/complex renal stones | Small skin incision, direct access to kidney |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Open surgery means a cut; ESWL is sound waves, not a scalpel.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nDuring an open pyelolithotomy, intraoperative fluoroscopy or ultrasound can be used to precisely localize the stone within the renal pelvis before incision and to confirm complete stone removal after extraction.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Urological Association (AUA) Guidelines 2023. They recommend ESWL as a first-line treatment option for many small to medium-sized renal and proximal ureteral stones.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Pyelolithotomy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Nephrolithotomy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Extracoporeal shock-wave lithotripsy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Extended pyelolithotomy | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: ?) Displacement of the ureters towards the midline** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Competency 2500**\n"
