  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Exstrophy: Think structural, not systemic.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Hypertension because it is not typically associated with Ectopia vesicae. Ectopia vesicae (bladder exstrophy) is a complex congenital anomaly primarily involving structural malformations of the lower abdominal wall and genitourinary tract, not systemic vascular issues.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nEctopia vesicae results from a failure of midline fusion during embryonic development, leading to an open bladder plate, pubic diastasis, and epispadias. The associated conditions like inguinal hernia and undescended testes are direct or indirect consequences of this developmental defect and the altered pelvic anatomy, reflecting a spectrum of structural abnormalities.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Epispadias) (Incorrect): Epispadias is an integral component of the exstrophy-epispadias complex and is almost universally present.\nOption C (Bilateral inguinal hernia) (Incorrect): The wide pubic diastasis and weakened abdominal wall musculature in bladder exstrophy patients significantly increase the risk of inguinal hernias.\nOption D (Undescended testes) (Incorrect): Cryptorchidism is frequently observed in males with bladder exstrophy due to the pelvic floor abnormalities and altered anatomy affecting testicular descent.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Anomaly | Key Features | Associated Conditions |\n|---|---|---|\n| Bladder Exstrophy (Ectopia Vesicae) | Open bladder plate, pubic diastasis, epispadias | Inguinal hernia, undescended testes, vesicoureteral reflux, wide symphysis |\n| Epispadias | Urethra opens on dorsal aspect of penis/clitoris | Often part of bladder exstrophy, urinary incontinence |\n| Cloacal Exstrophy | Bladder and bowel open to abdominal wall, omphalocele | Imperforate anus, spinal defects, short gut, ambiguous genitalia |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Exstrophy is a structural defect, not a systemic vascular one.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nPrenatal ultrasound may show absence of a visible bladder, a lower abdominal wall mass, and pubic diastasis. Intraoperatively, the open bladder plate, everted bladder mucosa, epispadias, and wide pubic symphysis are characteristic.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Academy of Pediatrics (AAP) Section on Urology, 2010 (reaffirmed 2015) - Clinical Practice Guideline for the Initial Management of Bladder Exstrophy. Recommends staged surgical repair for bladder closure, epispadias repair, and bladder neck reconstruction.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Ectopia vesicae is usually associated with the following except | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Epispadias | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Bilateral inguinal hernia | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Undescended testes | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: ?) Hypertension** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Competency 2500**\n"
