  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Atrophy needs imaging; suspicious masses need FNAC.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe verdict is that Fine Needle Aspiration Cytology (FNAC) is the correct answer. While seminal vesicle atrophy is primarily an imaging diagnosis, FNAC may be indicated if there is an associated suspicious mass or to rule out malignancy as a cause of atrophy or obstruction.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nFNAC is a valuable diagnostic procedure that obtains cellular material for cytological examination, allowing differentiation between inflammatory, benign, and malignant conditions. In the context of seminal vesicle pathology, it can provide a tissue diagnosis for suspicious lesions identified on imaging, guiding further management without the need for more invasive surgical exploration.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): This option describes a treatment for intraperitoneal bladder rupture, which is entirely unrelated to the diagnosis or management of an atrophic seminal vesicle.\nOption B (Incorrect): Nonoperative management is a treatment strategy, not a diagnostic procedure for seminal vesicle atrophy, nor is it relevant to the question's implied diagnostic nature.\nOption C (Incorrect): Perurethral catheterization of the bladder is a procedure for urinary drainage, completely unrelated to seminal vesicle pathology or its diagnosis.\nOption D (Incorrect): Suprapubic bladder drainage is a method of urinary diversion, entirely irrelevant to the diagnostic approach for an atrophic seminal vesicle.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Diagnostic Method | Indication for Seminal Vesicle | Advantages | Disadvantages |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Transrectal Ultrasound (TRUS) | Initial imaging for size, morphology, cysts, masses, ejaculatory duct obstruction | Non-invasive, real-time, widely available | Operator-dependent, limited tissue characterization |\n| MRI Pelvis | Detailed anatomical assessment, characterization of masses, staging of malignancy | Excellent soft tissue contrast, multiplanar imaging | Expensive, not always available, contraindications (e.g., pacemakers) |\n| FNAC | Suspicious seminal vesicle mass, guiding biopsy for tissue diagnosis | Minimally invasive, rapid results, avoids open surgery | Risk of bleeding/infection, sampling error, non-diagnostic rate |\n| Seminal Vesiculoscopy | Direct visualization, biopsy, stone removal for ejaculatory duct obstruction | Therapeutic and diagnostic, direct visualization | Invasive, requires specialized equipment and expertise |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: For seminal vesicle lesions, imaging guides diagnosis; FNAC confirms suspicious pathology.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn TRUS or MRI, an atrophic seminal vesicle would appear smaller than normal, potentially with thickened walls or associated with a mass. If FNAC is performed, it would typically be guided by TRUS to target any suspicious lesion within or adjacent to the seminal vesicle.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Urological Association (AUA) Guidelines on Male Infertility (2020): Recommends imaging (TRUS, MRI) for evaluation of seminal vesicles in specific infertility cases, particularly for ejaculatory duct obstruction or suspicious masses, which may warrant further diagnostic steps like FNAC if a lesion is identified.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | What is the recommended treatment for intraperitoneal rupture of bladder? | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Nonoperative managemet | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Perurethral catheterisationn of bladder | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Suprapubic bladder drainage | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: ?) FNAC** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Competency 2500**\n"
