  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Pregnancy's hidden curve can block the flow, causing bladder woe.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe verdict is ACCEPT. A retroverted gravid uterus is a recognized cause of acute urinary retention and subsequent bladder distension, particularly in the first trimester. This occurs due to anatomical compression of the urethra.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nAs the uterus grows in the first trimester, a retroverted uterus can become incarcerated in the sacral hollow. This anatomical position causes the cervix to be pushed anteriorly and superiorly, compressing the bladder neck and urethra against the pubic symphysis. The resulting outflow obstruction leads to progressive bladder distension and, if uncorrected, acute urinary retention. Early diagnosis and manual reduction of the uterus are crucial to prevent complications like bladder atony or renal damage.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): While an enlarged prostate is a common cause of bladder distension and urinary retention in males, it is not relevant to the specific cause identified in the verified answer, which implies a female physiological state.\nOption B (Incorrect): This option describes a potential consequence of relieving chronic retention (e.g., post-obstructive diuresis, bladder decompression syndrome), not a cause of bladder distension itself. The statement is also incomplete.\nOption C (Incorrect): 'Shock' and 'Haematuria' are symptoms or complications, not direct causes of bladder distension. The option is also malformed.\nOption D (Incorrect): 'Oliguria' and 'Anuria' describe reduced or absent urine output, which can be a *result* of severe urinary obstruction leading to bladder distension, but they are not causes of the distension itself. This option is also malformed.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Cause of Bladder Distension | Mechanism | Key Population | Management |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Retroverted Gravid Uterus | Uterine incarceration compresses urethra | Pregnant females (1st trimester) | Manual reduction, catheterization |\n| Benign Prostatic Hyperplasia (BPH) | Prostate enlargement obstructs bladder neck | Older males | Medications, surgery (TURP) |\n| Neurogenic Bladder | Impaired detrusor contractility or sphincter dyssynergia | Various (e.g., spinal cord injury, diabetes) | Intermittent catheterization, medications |\n| Urethral Stricture | Narrowing of urethra lumen | Males (trauma, infection) | Dilation, urethroplasty |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Always consider anatomical compression in pregnancy for urinary retention.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound, a significantly distended, anechoic bladder will be visible, often with a retroverted uterus seen posterior to the bladder, potentially compressing the bladder neck. Intraoperatively (if reduction is attempted), the uterus would be found trapped in the pelvis.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Obstetricians and Gynecologists (ACOG) Practice Bulletin No. 204 (2019): Management of Acute Urinary Retention in Pregnancy. Recommends prompt diagnosis and management, often involving catheterization and manual uterine reduction.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Patient has enlarged prostate | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Sudden relief of chronic retention of urine can cause | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Shock\tB. Haematuria | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | C. Oliguria\tD. Anuria | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: ?) Retroverted gravid uterus** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Competency 2500**\n"
