  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Empty your bladder, or stones will gather!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is D: Impaired bladder emptying. Primary bladder stones develop due to urine stasis, which is a direct consequence of the bladder not emptying completely. This stasis allows for crystal precipitation and aggregation over time.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe fundamental principle behind primary bladder stone formation is urinary stasis. When the bladder fails to empty efficiently, residual urine provides an environment where solutes can concentrate, leading to supersaturation and crystal nucleation. This process is exacerbated by prolonged contact time of urine with the bladder wall and the lack of washout. Conditions like benign prostatic hyperplasia, neurogenic bladder, urethral strictures, or even pelvic floor dysfunction (as hinted by the verified answer) are common causes of impaired bladder emptying, setting the stage for stone development.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Sterile urine does not inherently promote stone formation; in fact, infection can be a contributing factor to certain stone types (e.g., struvite).\nOption B (Incorrect): While infected urine can contribute to stone formation (e.g., urease-producing bacteria leading to struvite stones), it is often a secondary factor or a cause of secondary stones, not the primary driver for primary bladder stones which are fundamentally linked to stasis.\nOption C (Incorrect): Urinary retention is a severe form of impaired bladder emptying. While it certainly leads to primary stones, 'impaired bladder emptying' is a broader and more encompassing term that directly describes the underlying physiological problem leading to stasis.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Stone Type | Primary Cause | Common Composition | Imaging Appearance |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Primary Bladder Stone | Urinary stasis (impaired emptying) | Uric acid, Calcium oxalate | Single, large, smooth/faceted |\n| Secondary Bladder Stone | Migrated upper tract stone, foreign body | Variable (depends on origin) | Variable size/shape, often multiple |\n| Struvite Stone | Urease-producing UTI | Magnesium ammonium phosphate | Staghorn (renal), often multiple (bladder) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Stasis is the nemesis of a stone-free bladder.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn KUB/CT, bladder stones appear as radiopaque densities within the bladder lumen, though uric acid stones may be radiolucent. Cystoscopy reveals mobile or fixed calculi, often with associated inflammation or trabeculation of the bladder wall, and can identify underlying causes like prostatic enlargement.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Urological Association (AUA) Guideline on Ureteral and Bladder Stones (2020). Recommends addressing underlying causes of urinary stasis and metabolic abnormalities to prevent recurrence.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Sterile urine | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Infected urine | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Urinary retention | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Impaired bladder emptying | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: ?) Weakness of pelvic f loor musculature** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Competency 2500**\n"
