  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Bladder stones are urinary, pigment stones are biliary – know your systems!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe question asks to identify the type of calculus that is *not* typically found as a bladder stone. Pigment calculus, primarily associated with the biliary system, is the correct exception among the given choices.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nBladder stones are concretions formed in the urinary bladder, often due to urinary stasis, infection, or foreign bodies. Their composition reflects the metabolic environment of the urine. While oxalate, cystine, and triple phosphate (struvite) stones are common urinary calculi, pigment stones are predominantly found in the gallbladder as bilirubin stones, not in the bladder.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Oxalate calculus: Calcium oxalate stones are the most common type of urinary tract stones, frequently found in the bladder.\nOption B (Incorrect): Cystine calculus: Cystine stones are a rare type of urinary stone, formed due to a genetic defect in amino acid transport, and can occur in the bladder.\nOption D (Incorrect): Triple phosphate calculus: Also known as struvite stones, these are commonly found in the bladder, often associated with urinary tract infections by urea-splitting bacteria.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Stone Type | Common Location | Key Composition | Associated Factors |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Calcium Oxalate | Kidney, Bladder | Calcium oxalate monohydrate/dihydrate | Hypercalciuria, hyperoxaluria, low fluid intake |\n| Struvite (Triple Phosphate) | Bladder, Kidney | Magnesium ammonium phosphate | UTI with urea-splitting bacteria (e.g., Proteus) |\n| Cystine | Kidney, Bladder | Cystine | Genetic defect in amino acid transport (cystinuria) |\n| Pigment (Bilirubin) | Gallbladder | Unconjugated bilirubin | Hemolysis, biliary stasis, cirrhosis |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Bladder stones are urinary; pigment stones are biliary.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn imaging, bladder stones appear as echogenic foci with posterior shadowing on ultrasound, or as radiopaque densities on plain X-ray/CT, varying in density based on composition. Cystine stones can be less radiopaque. Intraoperatively, they are typically found free or adherent to the bladder wall.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Urological Association (AUA) Guideline for the Management of Ureteral Stones (2016, updated 2020). These guidelines detail the diagnosis, medical, and surgical management of urinary stones, including composition analysis.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Oxalate calculus | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Cystine calculus | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Pigment calculus | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Triple phosphate calculus | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: ?) Hperchloraemic acidosis** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Competency 2500**\n"
