  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Stones in the pipes? Ouch! Get a CT KUB.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nUreteric colic is a common and severe acute pain syndrome caused by obstruction of the ureter, most frequently by a calculus. The pain is typically flank pain radiating to the groin, often associated with nausea and vomiting.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe excruciating pain of ureteric colic arises from the acute distension of the renal capsule and the smooth muscle spasm of the ureter as it attempts to propel the obstructing object. This visceral pain is mediated by sympathetic afferent fibers, explaining its characteristic radiation patterns. The severity of pain often correlates with the acuteness of obstruction rather than the size of the calculus.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): This option is medically irrelevant to ureteric colic. \nOption B (Incorrect): This option is medically irrelevant to ureteric colic. \nOption C (Incorrect): This option is medically irrelevant to ureteric colic. \nOption D (Incorrect): This option is medically irrelevant to ureteric colic.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Ureteric Colic | Pyelonephritis | Acute Appendicitis |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Pain Character** | Excruciating, spasmodic, flank to groin | Dull ache, constant, flank/loin | Periumbilical to RIF, constant, worsening |\n| **Associated Symptoms** | Nausea, vomiting, hematuria | Fever, chills, dysuria, CVA tenderness | Nausea, vomiting, anorexia, fever |\n| **Urinalysis** | Hematuria common, +/- infection | Pyuria, bacteriuria, nitrites, leukocyte esterase | Usually normal, +/- mild pyuria |\n| **Imaging** | CT KUB (gold standard), US | CT abdomen/pelvis, US | CT abdomen/pelvis, US |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Acute flank pain radiating to groin = think ureteric colic until proven otherwise.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT KUB, you would see a hyperdense calculus within the ureter, often with associated hydronephrosis and hydroureter proximal to the obstruction. A 'rim sign' (edema around the stone) may be present. In the OR (e.g., during ureteroscopy), you would directly visualize the calculus and potentially signs of inflammation or edema around it.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Urological Association (AUA) Guideline on the Management of Ureteral Calculi (2023). Recommends non-contrast CT KUB as the preferred imaging modality for diagnosis and outlines treatment algorithms based on stone size, location, and patient factors.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Unilateral agenesis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | The term ‘lithotomy position’ was historically used in connec- tion with | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Delivery of a child | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Operations on the uterus and vagina | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: ?) Ureteric colic** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Competency 2500**\n"
