  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Stones in the bladder? CT's the scanner!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe verdict is that a CT scan is the correct diagnostic modality for bladder stones. This is because CT offers superior sensitivity and specificity for stone detection, characterization, and assessment of associated pathology, which is crucial before planning any removal procedure.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nNon-contrast CT is considered the gold standard for diagnosing bladder stones due to its ability to detect even small or radiolucent stones, differentiate them from other pelvic calcifications, and provide detailed anatomical information about the bladder, prostate, and surrounding structures. This comprehensive view helps identify the number, size, location, and potential underlying causes (like bladder outlet obstruction or diverticula), all of which are vital for effective surgical planning and management.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Treatment of haemorrhoids is a completely unrelated medical condition and procedure, bearing no relevance to the diagnosis or management of bladder stones.\nOption B (Incorrect): \"Which is the most common cause of bladder diverticulum?\" is a question, not a diagnostic modality or a direct answer to the topic of bladder stones, although bladder diverticula can be associated with stones.\nOption C (Incorrect): Bladder neck obstruction is a potential cause of bladder stones, but it is not a diagnostic tool itself, nor is it the primary answer to the topic of bladder stone diagnosis.\nOption D (Incorrect): \"Congenital\" refers to a condition present from birth and is not a diagnostic method or a direct answer to the topic of bladder stones.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Imaging Modality | Utility for Bladder Stones | Limitations |\n|---|---|---|\n| CT Scan (Non-contrast) | Gold standard, high sensitivity/specificity, detects all stone types, identifies associated pathology | Radiation exposure, cost |\n| Ultrasound | Good initial screening, no radiation, identifies larger stones, assesses bladder wall/post-void residual | Operator dependent, less sensitive for small/radiolucent stones, limited anatomical detail |\n| KUB X-ray | Detects radiopaque stones, inexpensive, low radiation | Misses radiolucent stones (e.g., uric acid), poor sensitivity, limited soft tissue detail |\n| Cystoscopy | Direct visualization, therapeutic potential (fragmentation/removal) | Invasive, requires anesthesia, not primary diagnostic for initial detection |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: CT is king for stones; don't miss the underlying cause.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn a non-contrast CT, bladder stones appear as hyperdense (bright white) foci within the bladder lumen, often layering dependently or associated with bladder wall thickening or diverticula. Intraoperatively, they are typically visualized as mobile or fixed concretions within the bladder.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Urological Association (AUA) Guideline for the Management of Ureteral Stones (2016, updated 2020) recommends non-contrast CT as the imaging modality of choice for suspected urolithiasis. This principle extends to bladder stones for definitive diagnosis.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Treatment of haemorrhoids | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Which is the most common cause of bladder diverticulum? | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Bladder neck obstruction | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Congenital | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: ?) CT scan** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Competency 2500**\n"
