  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Remove the stone, stop the infection, save the day.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe verdict is ACCEPT. Perineal lithotomy is a surgical procedure used to remove bladder stones, which are a known cause of recurrent urinary tract infections. By removing the calculus, the nidus for bacterial colonization is eliminated, thereby resolving the recurrent infections.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nPerineal lithotomy involves accessing the bladder through an incision in the perineum, typically between the anus and scrotum in males, or anus and vagina in females. This approach is particularly useful for large or impacted bladder stones that may be difficult to remove endoscopically. The direct surgical removal of the calculus eliminates the foreign body that acts as a persistent source of bacterial adherence and biofilm formation, which is crucial in preventing recurrent UTIs. This method avoids transurethral manipulation, which can sometimes be challenging or carry risks in certain patient populations.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Calculus in bladder) (Incorrect): While a calculus in the bladder is a cause of recurrent UTIs, the question asks for the answer which is a procedure. This option describes the pathology, not the intervention.\nOption B (The least common complication of bladder diverticulum is) (Incorrect): This is an incomplete statement and not directly related to the treatment of recurrent UTIs. It's a distractor.\nOption C (Recurrent urinary tract infection) (Incorrect): This option is the question itself, not an answer to it. It describes the clinical problem.\nOption D (Calculus formation) (Incorrect): This describes the process leading to a calculus, not the treatment for recurrent UTIs. It's related to the pathology but not the intervention.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Condition | Cause of RUTI | Treatment |\n|---|---|---|\n| Bladder Calculus | Nidus for bacterial colonization, incomplete bladder emptying | Perineal lithotomy, Cystolitholapaxy |\n| Bladder Diverticulum | Urine stasis, incomplete emptying | Diverticulectomy |\n| Vesicoureteral Reflux | Ascending infection | Ureteral reimplantation |\n| Urethral Stricture | Incomplete bladder emptying, stasis | Urethroplasty, Dilation |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Bladder stones causing RUTI often require surgical removal for definitive treatment.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn imaging (KUB X-ray, CT scan), bladder calculi appear as radiopaque densities within the bladder lumen. Intraoperatively during perineal lithotomy, the surgeon would identify the bladder, incise it, and directly visualize and extract the stone(s) from the bladder.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Urological Association (AUA) Guideline on Recurrent Uncomplicated Urinary Tract Infections in Women (2021). It recommends identifying and treating underlying anatomical or functional abnormalities, such as bladder stones, as part of RUTI management.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Calculus in bladder | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | The least common complication of bladder diverticulum is | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Recurrent urinary tract infection | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Calculus formation | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: ?) Perineal lithotomy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Competency 2500**\n"
