  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When bladder cancer gets deep, cut it out to keep it from spreading.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nRadical cystectomy is the gold standard treatment for muscle-invasive bladder cancer (MIBC). It is indicated for localized disease that has invaded the detrusor muscle (pT2) or perivesical fat (pT3), aiming for curative resection.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nBladder cancer invading the muscle layer (pT2) or beyond into perivesical fat (pT3) signifies a high risk of progression and metastasis, necessitating aggressive local control. Radical cystectomy involves en bloc removal of the bladder, prostate/seminal vesicles in men, and uterus/ovaries/anterior vaginal wall in women, along with pelvic lymph node dissection, to achieve clear surgical margins and remove regional lymphatic spread. This comprehensive approach offers the best chance for long-term survival in appropriately selected patients.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Large pelvic lymph nodes alone do not define the primary indication for radical cystectomy; rather, it's the T-stage of the primary tumor. While lymph node dissection is part of the procedure, extensive nodal disease might indicate systemic spread, altering the treatment strategy.\nOption C (Incorrect): Liver metastasis signifies distant metastatic disease (M1), which generally contraindicates curative radical cystectomy. Treatment shifts to systemic therapy, with palliative local measures if needed.\nOption D (Incorrect): Bone metastasis also indicates distant metastatic disease (M1), precluding curative radical cystectomy. Management focuses on systemic therapy and palliative care.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Indication for Radical Cystectomy | T-Stage | Description |\n|---|---|---|\n| Muscle-invasive bladder cancer | pT2, pT3 | Tumor invades detrusor muscle or perivesical fat |\n| High-risk non-muscle invasive bladder cancer (NMIBC) | CIS, TaG3, T1G3 | Recurrent, refractory, or multifocal high-grade disease |\n| Intractable symptoms | Any stage | Uncontrolled bleeding, pain, or fistula |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Muscle-invasive bladder cancer (pT2/pT3) equals radical cystectomy for cure.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT or MRI, muscle-invasive disease (pT2/pT3) may appear as a focal bladder wall thickening or mass with extension beyond the bladder wall. Intraoperatively, the surgeon would identify the tumor invading the muscle layer or extending into the perivesical fat, necessitating wide excision.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Urological Association (AUA) / Society of Urologic Oncology (SUO) Guideline on Bladder Cancer (2020). It recommends radical cystectomy with pelvic lymph node dissection as the standard of care for patients with muscle-invasive bladder cancer (T2-T4a, N0-N1, M0).\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Localised pT2 or pT3 disease | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Large pelvic lymph nodes | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Liver metastasis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Bone metastasis | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: ?) Cimetidine** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Competency 2500**\n"
