  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Median groove preservation: Urethral function's best friend.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe verdict is that preserving the median groove (or median raphe) is a critical principle in perineal urethrostomy. This is correct because maintaining the integrity of the median raphe and associated structures is vital for functional outcomes and minimizing complications like stricture recurrence or sexual dysfunction.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nPerineal urethrostomy, particularly techniques like the Kulkarni method for complex anterior urethral strictures, emphasizes preserving the median raphe. This raphe contains neurovascular bundles crucial for penile sensation and erectile function. Dissection lateral to the median raphe, rather than through it, helps maintain the integrity of the bulbospongiosus muscle, its innervation, and vascular supply, which are essential for preventing stricture recurrence and preserving sexual function.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nThe provided options (Ureterosigmoidostomy complications) are entirely unrelated to the question \"Perineal urethrostomy\" and the verified answer \"Median grove is preserved.\" Therefore, a specific debrief explaining why each option is incorrect in this context is not applicable.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Perineal Urethrostomy | Penile Urethrostomy | Scrotal Urethrostomy |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Indication** | Complex anterior urethral strictures, often bulbar | Distal penile strictures, often for palliation | Rarely performed, high complication rate |\n| **Key Principle** | Preserve median raphe/groove, bulbospongiosus muscle | Excision of stricture, primary anastomosis or graft | Creation of stoma in scrotum |\n| **Complications** | Stricture recurrence, sexual dysfunction, fistula | Stricture recurrence, meatal stenosis | Stricture, skin irritation, hair growth |\n| **Anatomy** | Bulbar urethra, perineum | Penile urethra, ventral penis | Scrotal skin, urethra |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Preserve the median raphe in perineal urethrostomy to protect neurovascular bundles.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIntraoperatively, the median raphe is identified as a distinct fibrous line in the perineum. Dissection proceeds lateral to this line, carefully mobilizing the bulbospongiosus muscle to expose the bulbar urethra, ensuring the neurovascular supply to the corpora is maintained.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Urological Association (AUA) Guideline on Urethral Stricture (2023). It recommends that for bulbar urethral strictures, excision and primary anastomosis (EPA) or augmentation urethroplasty are preferred, with careful attention to surgical technique to preserve function.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Ureterosigmoidostomy can lead to the following complica- tions except | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Hypokalemia | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Hyperchloraemic acidosis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Pyelonephritis | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: ?) Median grove is preserved** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Competency 2500**\n"
