  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Peri-prostatic nodes enlarged? Scope the bladder, don't delay!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe verdict is ACCEPT because Cystourethroscopy is a critical diagnostic procedure for evaluating the lower urinary tract, including the bladder, urethra, and prostatic urethra. In the context of peri-prostatic lymph node enlargement, which often suggests advanced prostate cancer, this procedure is essential for assessing local tumor extension and potential bladder involvement.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nCystourethroscopy offers direct visualization of the mucosal lining of the bladder and urethra, allowing for the identification of masses, strictures, or other abnormalities. For patients with peri-prostatic lymph node enlargement, this procedure is vital for local staging of prostate cancer, assessing for bladder invasion, and guiding subsequent treatment decisions. It also enables targeted biopsies of any suspicious lesions within the bladder or prostatic urethra, providing crucial histological information.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): \"Circumcision is indicated in the following situations in children, except\" is a question about pediatric penile conditions and not a diagnostic procedure for lymph node enlargement.\nOption B (Incorrect): Balanitis xerotica obliterans is a chronic inflammatory skin condition affecting the glans penis, not a diagnostic procedure.\nOption C (Incorrect): Paraphimosis is a urological emergency involving foreskin entrapment, not a diagnostic procedure.\nOption D (Incorrect): Glandular hypospadias is a congenital anomaly of the urethra, not a diagnostic procedure.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Procedure | Primary Indication | Relevance to Peri-prostatic Lymph Nodes |\n|---|---|---|\n| Cystourethroscopy | Hematuria, LUTS, suspected bladder/prostatic cancer | Assess bladder/urethral invasion from prostate cancer, rule out synchronous lesions |\n| Transrectal Ultrasound (TRUS) | Prostate cancer diagnosis, biopsy guidance | Evaluate prostate gland, seminal vesicles, local tumor extent |\n| MRI Pelvis | Prostate cancer staging, lymph node assessment | Detailed local staging, detection of nodal metastases |\n| CT Abdomen/Pelvis | Systemic staging for prostate cancer | Detect distant metastases and regional lymphadenopathy |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Cystoscopy visualizes the bladder and urethra; crucial for local staging of prostate cancer.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nDuring cystourethroscopy, one would look for prostatic urethral bulging or invasion, bladder neck involvement, and any synchronous bladder lesions. While enlarged peri-prostatic lymph nodes are not directly visualized, their impact on the bladder or urethra (e.g., extrinsic compression or invasion) might be inferred.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNational Comprehensive Cancer Network (NCCN) Guidelines for Prostate Cancer (2023). Recommends cystoscopy for patients with high-risk or very high-risk prostate cancer, or those with symptoms suggestive of bladder invasion.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Circumcision is indicated in the following situations in children, except | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Balanitis xerotica obliterans | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Paraphimosis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Glandular hypospadias | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: ?) Cystourethroscopy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Competency 2500**\n"
