  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Investigations are tools; diseases are targets.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe verdict is ACCEPT. The question asks to identify an item that is *not* an investigation performed in prostate cancer. \"End-stage renal failure\" is a clinical condition, not an investigative procedure, making it the correct answer.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nInvestigations are diagnostic or staging procedures designed to gather information about a patient's condition. End-stage renal failure (ESRF) represents a severe clinical outcome or comorbidity, not a method of inquiry. Understanding this fundamental distinction between a disease state and a diagnostic tool is crucial for accurate medical reasoning.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): X-ray of chest and pelvis are imaging investigations used to detect metastases in prostate cancer.\nOption B (Incorrect): Transurethral ultrasound is an imaging modality and thus an investigation, though transrectal ultrasound (TRUS) is more commonly used for prostate cancer.\nOption C (Incorrect): Bone scan is a standard nuclear medicine investigation for detecting bone metastases in prostate cancer.\nOption D (Incorrect): Lymphangiography is an imaging investigation, historically used for lymph node staging in prostate cancer, though now largely superseded.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Category | Item | Role in Prostate Cancer |\n|---|---|---|\n| Imaging Investigation | Bone Scan | Detects bone metastases |\n| Imaging Investigation | TRUS | Biopsy guidance, local staging |\n| Imaging Investigation | CT/MRI | Nodal/distant staging |\n| Clinical Condition | End-stage Renal Failure | A potential complication, not an investigation |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: An investigation gathers data; a condition is the data itself.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn a bone scan, metastatic prostate cancer typically presents as focal areas of increased radiotracer uptake, indicating osteoblastic activity.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for Prostate Cancer (2023). Recommends appropriate imaging (e.g., bone scan, CT/MRI) for staging based on risk stratification.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | X-ray of chest and pelvis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Transurethral ultrasound | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Bone scan | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Lymphangiography | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: ?) End-stage renal failure** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Competency 2500**\n"
