  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 E. coli: The gut's gift to your prostate's plight.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe verdict is Escherichia coli (Option C) is the most common organism responsible for acute prostatitis. This answer is correct because E. coli is a prevalent Gram-negative bacterium in the human gut flora and the leading cause of urinary tract infections, which often precede or directly cause acute bacterial prostatitis.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nAcute bacterial prostatitis typically arises from an ascending infection, where bacteria from the urethra or bladder reflux into the prostatic ducts. E. coli's high prevalence in the fecal flora, coupled with its virulence factors like fimbriae (for adhesion) and endotoxins, makes it exceptionally adept at colonizing the urinary tract and subsequently the prostate. The anatomical proximity of the rectum to the prostate also facilitates its entry, making it the primary pathogen in the majority of cases.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Streptococcus faecalis): Incorrect. While Enterococcus faecalis (formerly S. faecalis) can cause UTIs and prostatitis, it is significantly less common than E. coli as the primary causative agent.\nOption B (Neisseria gonorrhea): Incorrect. N. gonorrhea is a sexually transmitted pathogen primarily causing urethritis and epididymitis; while it can rarely lead to acute prostatitis, it is not the most common cause.\nOption D (Staphylococcus albicans): Incorrect. Staphylococcus species (e.g., S. aureus) can cause prostatitis, but 'Staphylococcus albicans' is not a recognized pathogen. Candida albicans is a fungus, and fungal prostatitis is rare.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Condition | Most Common Organism | Key Characteristics |\n|---|---|---|\n| Acute Bacterial Prostatitis | E. coli | Gram-negative rod, fecal flora, ascending infection, severe symptoms |\n| Chronic Bacterial Prostatitis | E. coli, other Gram-negatives | Recurrent UTIs, persistent infection, often asymptomatic between flares |\n| Non-bacterial Prostatitis (CPPS) | No organism identified | Chronic pelvic pain, inflammatory or non-inflammatory |\n| Fungal Prostatitis (Rare) | Candida species | Immunocompromised patients, often disseminated infection |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: E. coli is the undisputed king of acute bacterial prostatitis.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nImaging (transrectal ultrasound or CT) for acute prostatitis is typically reserved for suspected complications like prostatic abscess. On ultrasound, an abscess appears as a hypoechoic or anechoic collection within an enlarged, often heterogeneous prostate. CT may show diffuse prostatic enlargement with periprostatic fat stranding and a low-attenuation collection for an abscess.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nEuropean Association of Urology (EAU) Guidelines on Urological Infections (2023): Recommends empirical antibiotic therapy for acute bacterial prostatitis targeting Gram-negative enteric bacteria, with fluoroquinolones or trimethoprim-sulfamethoxazole as first-line choices.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Streptococcus faecalis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Neisseria gonorrhea | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Escherichia coli | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Staphylococcus albicans | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: ?) Transurethral prostatectomy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Competency 2500**\n"
