  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Biopsy for cancer, not prostatitis' inflammation.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe verdict is that prostatic biopsy is generally not performed for the diagnosis of chronic prostatitis. This invasive procedure is primarily reserved for the diagnosis of prostate cancer or other specific indications, not for routine evaluation of prostatic inflammation.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nChronic prostatitis is a clinical diagnosis often supported by laboratory findings. The diagnostic approach focuses on identifying inflammation and/or infection within the prostate gland, typically through non-invasive or minimally invasive means. Prostatic biopsy, while providing histological detail, carries risks of bleeding, infection, and pain, and its yield for diagnosing chronic inflammation is low compared to less invasive methods. The presence of inflammation on biopsy is often an incidental finding rather than a primary diagnostic goal for prostatitis.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Three-glass urine test is a cornerstone for diagnosing chronic prostatitis, helping to localize infection or inflammation to the prostate by comparing bacterial counts and leukocyte presence in different urine samples before and after prostatic massage.\nOption C (Incorrect): Urethroscopy is not a primary diagnostic test for chronic prostatitis itself, but it may be used to rule out other conditions that mimic or contribute to symptoms, such as urethral strictures or bladder neck obstruction. It does not directly diagnose prostatic inflammation.\nOption D (Incorrect): Prostatic fluid examination (e.g., expressed prostatic secretions or post-massage urine) is crucial for diagnosing chronic prostatitis, as it directly assesses the prostatic fluid for inflammatory cells (leukocytes) and bacteria, indicating prostatic inflammation or infection.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Diagnostic Test | Purpose in Prostatitis | Invasiveness | Primary Indication |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Three-glass urine test | Localize infection/inflammation to prostate | Non-invasive | Chronic Prostatitis |\n| Prostatic fluid exam | Assess prostatic inflammation/infection | Minimally invasive | Chronic Prostatitis |\n| Urethroscopy | Rule out structural abnormalities | Invasive | Urethral/Bladder pathology |\n| Prostatic biopsy | Histological diagnosis of prostate tissue | Invasive | Prostate Cancer |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Prostatic biopsy is for cancer, not routine prostatitis diagnosis.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nWhile not typically used for diagnosis, transrectal ultrasound (TRUS) might show prostatic calcifications or dilated ejaculatory ducts in chronic prostatitis, but it's not diagnostic. Biopsy involves TRUS guidance to sample prostate tissue.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Urological Association (AUA) Guideline on Chronic Prostatitis/Chronic Pelvic Pain Syndrome (2014, reaffirmed 2019). It recommends a thorough history, physical exam, and urine/expressed prostatic secretions analysis, but does not list prostatic biopsy as a diagnostic tool for prostatitis.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Prostatic biopsy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Three-glass urine test | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Urethroscopy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Prostatic fluid examination | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: ?) Predisposes to carcinoma penis** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Competency 2500**\n"
