  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Nodular seminal vesicles? Think T3b prostate cancer, not just a bump in the road.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe verified answer \"Needs removal of prostate\" correctly points to Carcinoma prostate as the diagnosis. Nodularity of the seminal vesicles is a classic sign of local invasion by prostate cancer, specifically T3b disease, which often necessitates radical prostatectomy as part of treatment.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nProstate cancer, when locally advanced, frequently invades adjacent structures due to its anatomical proximity. The seminal vesicles lie superior and posterior to the prostate, making them a common site for direct tumor extension, often via the ejaculatory ducts or through the prostatic capsule. This invasion manifests as nodularity or asymmetry on imaging or palpation, indicating a higher stage (T3b) of disease. Recognizing this finding is crucial for accurate staging, prognosis, and guiding appropriate treatment strategies, which may include radical prostatectomy, radiation, or multimodal therapy.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Genitourinary tuberculosis typically causes calcifications, strictures, or abscesses in the GU tract, but seminal vesicle nodularity is not its primary or most common presentation.\nOption B (Incorrect): Carcinoma bladder primarily affects the bladder wall; while advanced cases can invade adjacent organs, seminal vesicle nodularity is not a typical initial or primary diagnostic feature of bladder cancer.\nOption D (Incorrect): Prostatic calculi are benign calcifications within the prostate gland itself and do not cause nodularity or involvement of the seminal vesicles.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Condition | Seminal Vesicle Finding | Key Diagnostic Feature | Management |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Prostate Cancer (T3b) | Nodularity, asymmetry, loss of normal architecture | Elevated PSA, abnormal DRE, biopsy showing adenocarcinoma | Radical prostatectomy, radiation, hormone therapy, chemotherapy |\n| Seminal Vesiculitis | Enlargement, tenderness, inflammation, sometimes cysts | Painful ejaculation, hematospermia, fever, dysuria | Antibiotics, anti-inflammatory drugs |\n| Genitourinary Tuberculosis | Calcifications, strictures, abscesses, sometimes diffuse inflammation | Positive urine culture for acid-fast bacilli, systemic symptoms | Anti-tubercular therapy |\n| Benign Prostatic Hyperplasia | Normal seminal vesicles (unless very large prostate displaces them) | Obstructive voiding symptoms, enlarged prostate on DRE | Watchful waiting, alpha-blockers, 5-alpha-reductase inhibitors, surgery (TURP) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Seminal vesicle invasion on imaging or DRE indicates T3b prostate cancer.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn MRI, seminal vesicle invasion appears as low T2 signal intensity within the seminal vesicle, obliteration of the angle between the prostate and seminal vesicle, or direct tumor extension. Intraoperatively, direct visualization of tumor infiltration into the seminal vesicle tissue.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for Prostate Cancer (latest version). These guidelines define T3b disease as seminal vesicle invasion and recommend treatment strategies based on this staging, including radical prostatectomy, radiation therapy, and systemic therapies.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Genitourinary tuberculosis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Carcinoma bladder | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Carcinoma prostate | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Prostatic calculi | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: ?) Needs removal of prostate** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Competency 2500**\n"
