  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 PUV: Ablate the valve, save the kidney.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Transurethral resection (or fulguration/ablation) of the posterior urethral valves. This procedure directly addresses the anatomical obstruction caused by the valves, restoring normal urine flow and preventing further damage to the urinary tract.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nPosterior urethral valves are congenital obstructive membranes in the male posterior urethra, leading to bladder outlet obstruction. Transurethral fulguration or ablation involves cystoscopic identification and precise incision or coagulation of these valve leaflets. This minimally invasive endoscopic approach relieves the obstruction, allowing for improved bladder emptying and protecting the kidneys from hydronephrosis and renal damage. Early intervention is crucial to preserve renal function.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Meatoplasty) (Incorrect): This procedure addresses issues with the urethral meatus, such as stenosis or hypospadias, which are distinct from posterior urethral valves.\nOption C (Suprapubic cystostomy) (Incorrect): While a suprapubic cystostomy can provide temporary bladder drainage in severe cases of PUV, it is a diversion and not the definitive treatment to remove the obstruction.\nOption D (Perineal urethrostomy) (Incorrect): This involves creating an opening in the urethra through the perineum, typically for urethral strictures or as a form of urinary diversion, and is not indicated for the primary treatment of PUV.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Condition | Location of Obstruction | Primary Treatment | Key Complication if Untreated |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Posterior Urethral Valves | Posterior urethra (male infants) | Transurethral fulguration/ablation | Renal failure, bladder dysfunction |\n| Urethral Stricture | Any part of urethra | Urethroplasty, DVIU | Recurrent UTIs, urinary retention |\n| Meatal Stenosis | Urethral meatus | Meatoplasty | Dysuria, spraying of urine |\n| Benign Prostatic Hyperplasia | Prostatic urethra | TURP, medical therapy | Urinary retention, UTIs |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: PUV treatment is endoscopic ablation, not open surgery or diversion.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn voiding cystourethrogram (VCUG), one would see a dilated posterior urethra proximal to the valves, a thin radiolucent line representing the valves, and often vesicoureteral reflux and bladder trabeculation. Intraoperatively, during cystoscopy, the valves appear as sail-like membranes originating from the verumontanum, causing a constricted lumen.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Urological Association (AUA) Guideline on the Management of Posterior Urethral Valves (2019). It recommends prompt endoscopic ablation of the valves as the definitive treatment.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Meatoplasty | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Transurethral resection | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Suprapubic cystostomy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Perineal urethrostomy | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: ?) All prostatic cancers need resection** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Competency 2500**\n"
