  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Cancer is acquired, not a birth defect; know the difference!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe verified answer, Adenocarcinoma, is correct because it represents a malignant, acquired condition, fundamentally distinct from congenital anomalies. Congenital anomalies are structural or functional defects present at birth, whereas adenocarcinoma is a type of cancer that develops later in life.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nAdenocarcinoma is a malignancy arising from glandular epithelial cells, typically developing through a process of cellular mutation and uncontrolled growth over time. Unlike congenital anomalies, which result from errors in embryonic development, adenocarcinoma is an acquired disease, often influenced by genetic predispositions, environmental factors, or chronic inflammation. Its pathogenesis involves somatic mutations rather than germline developmental defects, making it an acquired condition and not a congenital anomaly of the male urethra.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Epispadias) (Incorrect): This is a congenital anomaly where the urethra opens on the dorsal surface of the penis, resulting from abnormal development of the genital tubercle.\nOption B (Posterior urethral valves) (Incorrect): These are congenital obstructive membranes within the posterior urethra, a significant cause of urinary obstruction in male infants.\nOption C (Chordee) (Incorrect): This is a congenital ventral curvature of the penis, often associated with hypospadias, indicating an underlying developmental defect of the penile shaft and urethra.\nOption D (Phimosis) (Incorrect): While physiological phimosis is a congenital condition where the foreskin is non-retractable, it is considered a congenital condition of the male genitalia, even if not directly a urethral anomaly itself, it affects urethral function.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Congenital Anomaly | Acquired Condition |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Onset** | Present at birth (developmental error) | Develops after birth (environmental, genetic, inflammatory) |\n| **Etiology** | Errors in embryogenesis/fetal development | Somatic mutations, infection, trauma, degeneration |\n| **Example (Urethra)** | Epispadias, PUV, Hypospadias | Urethral stricture (traumatic), Urethral adenocarcinoma |\n| **Management** | Often surgical correction early in life | Varies widely (medical, surgical, oncologic) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Congenital means 'born with it'; acquired means 'developed later'.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn cystoscopy, urethral adenocarcinoma may appear as an irregular, friable mass within the urethral lumen, often with associated bleeding or ulceration, distinct from the membranous folds of posterior urethral valves or the abnormal meatal position of epispadias.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Urological Association (AUA) Guidelines on Urethral Cancer (2020) recommend biopsy and staging for suspected urethral adenocarcinoma, highlighting its malignant and acquired nature.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Epispadias | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Posterior urethral valves | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Chordee | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Phimosis | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: ?) Adenocarcinoma** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Competency 2500**\n"
