  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Pelvic fractures pinch the fixed membranous, not the mobile penile.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is the membranous urethra. This segment of the urethra is most vulnerable to rupture in severe pelvic fractures due to its anatomical fixation within the urogenital diaphragm, making it susceptible to shearing forces when the pelvis is disrupted.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe membranous urethra is the shortest, narrowest, and least distensible portion of the male urethra, traversing the deep perineal pouch (urogenital diaphragm). It is firmly anchored by the puboprostatic ligaments anteriorly and the perineal membrane inferiorly. This fixed position makes it highly susceptible to avulsion or rupture when the surrounding bony pelvis undergoes significant displacement or fracture, particularly involving the pubic rami or symphysis. The shearing forces generated during such trauma can easily tear this delicate, immobile segment.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Penile urethra) (Incorrect): This part of the urethra is more mobile and typically injured by direct penile trauma (e.g., penile fracture) or iatrogenic causes, not commonly by severe pelvic fractures.\nOption B (Bulbar urethra) (Incorrect): While susceptible to straddle injuries, the bulbar urethra is more mobile than the membranous urethra and less commonly ruptured by the shearing forces of severe pelvic fractures.\nOption D (Prostatic urethra) (Incorrect): Located superior to the urogenital diaphragm within the prostate, this segment is relatively protected by the surrounding prostate gland and bony pelvis. Injury is rare and usually associated with extremely severe, comminuted pelvic fractures or complete prostate avulsion.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Urethral Segment | Location/Fixation | Common Injury Mechanism | Clinical Presentation |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Penile Urethra | Spongy tissue of penis, mobile | Direct trauma, penile fracture, iatrogenic | Urethral bleeding, hematoma, inability to void |\n| Bulbar Urethra | Proximal spongy urethra, perineum | Straddle injury, direct perineal trauma | Perineal hematoma (butterfly sign), urethral bleeding |\n| Membranous Urethra | Deep perineal pouch, fixed by urogenital diaphragm | Severe pelvic fracture (shear forces) | Blood at meatus, high-riding prostate, inability to void |\n| Prostatic Urethra | Within prostate gland, superior to diaphragm | Extremely severe pelvic fracture, prostate avulsion | Rare, severe pelvic trauma, often associated with bladder neck injury |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Membranous urethra: fixed, fragile, fractured pelvis.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn a Retrograde Urethrogram (RUG), extravasation of contrast material from the urethra into the perivesical or perineal space confirms urethral rupture. Intraoperatively, one might observe blood at the urethral meatus, a high-riding prostate on rectal exam, a large pelvic hematoma, and direct visualization of the urethral transection or avulsion.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Urological Association (AUA) Guideline on Urethral Trauma (2014, reaffirmed 2020). It recommends that a retrograde urethrogram (RUG) should be performed in all male patients with suspected urethral injury to define the location and extent of the injury.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Penile urethra | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Bulbar urethra | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Membranous urethra | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Prostatic urethra | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: ?) Pelvic bones** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Competency 2500**\n"
