  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Prostatectomy: Remove the problem, preserve the function.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe provided answer, Radical prostatectomy, is a definitive surgical treatment for localized prostate cancer. This procedure involves the complete removal of the prostate gland and seminal vesicles, aiming for curative intent.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nRadical prostatectomy is a complex surgical procedure that can be performed via open, laparoscopic, or robotic-assisted approaches. The goal is to achieve negative surgical margins while preserving critical structures like the neurovascular bundles, which are essential for erectile function, and the external urethral sphincter, vital for urinary continence. Careful dissection around these structures is paramount to minimize postoperative complications and optimize functional outcomes.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Enlargement of inguinal lymph nodes is not a direct treatment for prostate cancer and is more indicative of inflammatory or metastatic processes in the groin, unrelated to prostatectomy.\nOption B (Incorrect): Associated with proctitis describes an inflammatory condition of the rectum, which is not a treatment for prostate cancer.\nOption C (Incorrect): \"Which of the following is a risk factor for developing carcinoma penis?\" is a question, not an answer, and is unrelated to prostatectomy.\nOption D (Incorrect): Hypospadias is a congenital anomaly of the urethra, not a treatment for prostate cancer.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Treatment | Indication | Key Advantage | Key Disadvantage |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Radical Prostatectomy | Localized, clinically significant PCa | Curative intent, pathological staging | Surgical risks, urinary/erectile dysfunction |\n| External Beam Radiation | Localized PCa, unfit for surgery | Non-invasive, good local control | Bowel/bladder toxicity, erectile dysfunction |\n| Brachytherapy | Low/intermediate risk localized PCa | Minimally invasive, targeted radiation | Urinary symptoms, potential for rectal irritation |\n| Active Surveillance | Low-risk localized PCa | Avoids overtreatment, preserves QoL | Risk of progression, anxiety |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Radical prostatectomy: definitive treatment for localized prostate cancer.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nPreoperative MRI helps delineate prostate anatomy and potential extracapsular extension. Intraoperatively, surgeons identify and dissect the prostate from the rectum, preserve neurovascular bundles, and perform a meticulous vesicourethral anastomosis.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAUA Guideline for Clinically Localized Prostate Cancer (2022): Recommends radical prostatectomy as a primary treatment option for localized, intermediate- and high-risk prostate cancer.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Enlargement of inguinal lymph nodes | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Associated with proctitis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Which of the following is a risk factor for developing carcinoma penis? | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Hypospadias | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: ?) Radical prostatectomy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Competency 2500**\n"
