  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When inguinal nodes swell, consider TB's silent GU spell.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nGenito-urinary tuberculosis (GUTB) is the correct answer. This is because TB, including its extrapulmonary forms like GUTB, is known to spread via lymphatic channels, and involvement of the external genitalia or perineum can lead to regional lymphadenopathy, specifically in the inguinal lymph nodes.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nGenito-urinary tuberculosis is typically a secondary infection resulting from hematogenous dissemination of Mycobacterium tuberculosis from a primary pulmonary focus, often years prior. While renal involvement is most common, the infection can affect any part of the genitourinary tract, including the epididymis, testis, prostate, and seminal vesicles. When the infection involves the external genitalia (e.g., penile or scrotal TB) or the perineum, lymphatic drainage can lead to enlargement of the inguinal lymph nodes, making this a crucial diagnostic clue for extrapulmonary TB.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): \"It does not spread to distant organs\" is a general statement and factually incorrect for many diseases, including TB, which is known for its systemic spread.\nOption B (Incorrect): \"It is locally destructive\" is a non-specific characteristic that applies to many conditions, not uniquely to one that spreads to inguinal lymph nodes.\nOption C (Incorrect): \"What is the best time for orchidopexy in undescended testes?\" is a question, not a disease or a characteristic of a disease.\nOption D (Incorrect): \"Before going to school\" is an answer to the question posed in option C, not a disease or a characteristic.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Cause of Inguinal Lymphadenopathy | Common Presentation | Key Diagnostic Feature |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Genito-urinary TB** | Chronic epididymitis, sterile pyuria, scrotal mass | Often painless, firm inguinal nodes; systemic TB symptoms possible |\n| **Sexually Transmitted Infections (STIs)** | Genital ulcers, urethritis, discharge | Acute, often painful lymphadenopathy (e.g., syphilis, chancroid, LGV) |\n| **Lymphoma** | Painless, rubbery, matted lymph nodes | Systemic B symptoms (fever, night sweats, weight loss) |\n| **Metastatic Carcinoma** | Primary tumor (e.g., anal, penile, vulvar, melanoma) | Hard, fixed, often unilateral nodes; history of malignancy |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Inguinal lymphadenopathy with GU symptoms? Think TB or STI.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound, affected genitourinary organs may show heterogeneous echotexture, calcifications, or abscess formation. Intraoperatively, granulomatous inflammation, caseous necrosis, and fibrosis are characteristic findings.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nWorld Health Organization (WHO) Guidelines for the programmatic management of drug-resistant tuberculosis (2020). These guidelines provide comprehensive recommendations for the diagnosis and treatment of all forms of TB, including extrapulmonary manifestations like GUTB.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | It does not spread to distant organs | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | It is locally distructive | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | What is the best time for orchidopexy in undescended testes? | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Before going to school | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: ?) Genito-urinary tuberculosis** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Competency 2500**\n"
