  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Extraperitoneal rupture: Pelvic trauma's urinary foe, not orchitis's flow.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe verified answer, \"Orchitis,\" is correct because it is an inflammation of the testis, typically infectious or inflammatory in origin, and has no direct association with the mechanism or sequelae of an extraperitoneal bladder rupture. Extraperitoneal bladder ruptures are primarily traumatic injuries involving urine extravasation into the perivesical space.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nExtraperitoneal bladder ruptures most commonly result from blunt trauma, particularly in association with pelvic fractures. The sharp edges of fractured bone can directly lacerate the anterior or lateral bladder wall, leading to urine leakage into the perivesical space, including the space of Retzius. This extravasation can cause local inflammation, hematoma formation, and potential infection, but it does not directly cause orchitis, which is an inflammatory condition of the testicle itself, usually due to infection (e.g., mumps, bacterial) or systemic vasculitis.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Fracture pelvis (Incorrect for the question, meaning it IS associated): Pelvic fractures are the most common cause of extraperitoneal bladder rupture, with bony fragments directly injuring the bladder.\nOption B (Incorrect): Rupture of membranous urethra (Incorrect for the question, meaning it IS associated): Membranous urethral ruptures are also commonly associated with severe pelvic fractures and can occur concurrently with or contribute to the mechanism of extraperitoneal bladder injury.\nOption C (Incorrect): Floating prostate (Incorrect for the question, meaning it IS associated): A \"floating prostate\" is a classic sign of a complete urethral disruption, often seen with severe pelvic trauma, which can coexist with or predispose to extraperitoneal bladder rupture.\nOption D (Incorrect): Peritonitis (Incorrect for the question, meaning it IS associated): While extraperitoneal, significant urine extravasation can cause chemical irritation and inflammation of adjacent peritoneal surfaces, leading to localized peritonitis or, if the rupture extends, frank peritonitis.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Extraperitoneal Bladder Rupture | Intraperitoneal Bladder Rupture |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Cause** | Blunt trauma, pelvic fracture (most common) | Blunt trauma (full bladder), penetrating trauma |\n| **Location** | Anterior/lateral bladder wall, bladder neck | Bladder dome |\n| **Urine Extravasation** | Perivesical space, space of Retzius | Peritoneal cavity |\n| **Associated Injuries** | Pelvic fracture, urethral injury | Bowel injury (less common) |\n| **Clinical Signs** | Suprapubic pain, hematuria, inability to void, localized tenderness | Diffuse abdominal pain, ascites, peritonitis, shoulder pain (diaphragmatic irritation) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Pelvic fracture + gross hematuria = suspect bladder or urethral injury.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn a CT cystogram, extraperitoneal rupture shows contrast extravasation confined to the perivesical space, often outlining the bladder or extending into the anterior abdominal wall, but not free within the peritoneal cavity.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Urological Association (AUA) Guideline on Urotrauma (2020): Recommends CT cystography for diagnosis of bladder injury in patients with gross hematuria and pelvic fracture.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Fracture pelvis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Rupture of membranous urethra | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Floating prostate | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Peritonitis | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: ?) Orchitis** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Competency 2500**\n"
