  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Chronic drip, think fistula trip.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe verified answer, urethral fistulae, is correct because gleet refers to a chronic, often mucoid or purulent, urethral discharge. A urethral fistula creates an abnormal communication that can lead to persistent leakage and discharge, fitting the description of gleet.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nGleet, derived from an Old English term for 'slime' or 'mucus,' specifically denotes a chronic, non-gonococcal urethral discharge. Urethral fistulae, whether congenital or acquired from trauma, infection, or surgery, establish an abnormal tract that continuously drains urine, pus, or inflammatory exudates into the urethra or onto the skin. This persistent drainage manifests as gleet, often resistant to simple antibiotic courses and requiring surgical correction of the underlying fistula for resolution. The chronic nature and often sterile or polymicrobial origin distinguish it from acute infectious urethritis.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Tuberculosis of the bladder and pyelonephritis are infections of the bladder and kidney, respectively, and do not typically cause chronic urethral discharge (gleet). Their symptoms are more related to irritative voiding or systemic illness.\nOption B (Incorrect): Gonococcal urethritis causes acute, often profuse, purulent discharge, but 'gleet' specifically refers to chronic, often non-gonococcal, discharge. Hypospadias is a congenital anatomical anomaly of the urethra, not a cause of discharge.\nOption C (Malformed): This is not a valid option for the question 'Gleet is seen in which condition?' and appears to be part of a different question.\nOption D (Malformed): This is not a valid option for the question 'Gleet is seen in which condition?' and appears to be part of a different question.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Condition | Key Feature | Discharge Type | Chronicity |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Gleet (Chronic Urethritis)** | Persistent urethral inflammation | Mucoid, serous, or purulent | Chronic (>4 weeks) |\n| **Urethral Fistula** | Abnormal tract from urethra | Urine, pus, inflammatory exudate | Chronic, persistent |\n| **Gonococcal Urethritis** | *Neisseria gonorrhoeae* infection | Profuse, purulent | Acute |\n| **Non-gonococcal Urethritis** | *Chlamydia*, *Mycoplasma*, etc. | Mucoid, watery, scant | Acute to subacute |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Gleet = chronic urethral discharge; always consider a fistula or stricture.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn a retrograde urethrogram (RUG), a urethral fistula would appear as contrast extravasation from the urethra into surrounding tissues or onto the skin. During endoscopy, a visible opening or tract within the urethral lumen might be identified.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Urological Association (AUA) Guidelines on Urethral Stricture Disease (2023) recommend imaging studies like RUG for diagnosis and surgical repair for symptomatic fistulae.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Tuberculosis of bladder\tB. Pyelonephritis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | C. Gonococcal urethritis\tD. Hypospadias | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | The following facts are true regarding posterior urethral valve except | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Majority are females | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: ?) Urethral fistulae** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Competency 2500**\n"
