  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Ventral meatus, surgical fix, happy future.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Penoscrotal hypospadias. This option accurately identifies a specific and severe form of hypospadias, characterized by the urethral meatus opening at the junction of the penis and scrotum. It represents a more proximal displacement of the meatus compared to other types.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nHypospadias results from incomplete fusion of the urethral folds during embryological development, typically between weeks 8 and 12 of gestation. This failure leads to the urethral meatus opening ventrally along the shaft of the penis, rather than at the tip of the glans. Penoscrotal hypospadias signifies a significant arrest in this process, often associated with a more severe degree of chordee (ventral penile curvature) and a hooded prepuce, where the dorsal foreskin is present but ventral is deficient.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): \"Which one of the following conditions is common in a leukemic patient?\" is a completely unrelated question and does not pertain to penile anomalies.\nOption C (Incorrect): Chordee is a ventral curvature of the penis, which is a common associated anomaly with hypospadias, but it is not a type of hypospadias itself.\nOption D (Incorrect): Gleet is an archaic term for urethral discharge, typically associated with gonorrhea or other urethritis, and has no relation to hypospadias.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Type of Hypospadias | Meatus Location | Severity | Associated Features |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Glandular | On the glans, near the tip | Mildest | Often no chordee |\n| Coronal | At the coronal sulcus | Mild | Minimal chordee |\n| Penile (Distal/Mid/Proximal) | Along the penile shaft | Moderate | Variable chordee, hooded prepuce |\n| Penoscrotal | At the junction of penis and scrotum | Severe | Significant chordee, bifid scrotum |\n| Perineal | In the perineum, posterior to scrotum | Most Severe | Severe chordee, often ambiguous genitalia |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Hypospadias: ventral meatus, incomplete urethral fold fusion.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIn the operating room, hypospadias presents as a ventrally displaced urethral meatus, often with a hooded prepuce (dorsal hood, deficient ventral foreskin). Chordee, a ventral curvature of the penis, is frequently observed and may require degloving and sometimes corporal plication for correction.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Urological Association (AUA) Guideline on the Management of Hypospadias (2017). It recommends surgical correction for most forms of hypospadias, typically between 6-18 months of age, to achieve a straight penis, a terminally located meatus, and normal voiding and sexual function.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Penoscrotal hypospadias | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Which one of the following conditions is common in a leukemic patient? | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Chordee | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Gleet | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: ?) A) Hypospadias** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Competency 2500**\n"
