  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Fibrosis in one place often means fibrosis elsewhere.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe verified answer, Dupuytren’s contracture, is correct because both Peyronie's disease and Dupuytren's contracture are fibrotic disorders of unknown etiology that frequently co-occur. This association is a classic board exam fact highlighting a systemic predisposition to fibrosis.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nBoth Peyronie's disease and Dupuytren's contracture involve abnormal collagen deposition and fibrosis. Peyronie's disease affects the tunica albuginea of the penis, leading to plaque formation, penile curvature, and pain. Dupuytren's contracture affects the palmar fascia, causing nodules and contracture of the fingers. Their shared pathophysiology, often linked to genetic factors and microtrauma, suggests a systemic predisposition to fibrotic conditions, making their co-occurrence a significant clinical finding.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Priapism) (Incorrect): Priapism is a prolonged, often painful erection unrelated to the fibrotic plaques and curvature characteristic of Peyronie's disease.\nOption B (What should be avoided in a patient with suspected rupture urethra?) (Incorrect): This question pertains to the management of urethral trauma, which is entirely unrelated to the etiology or associated conditions of Peyronie's disease.\nOption C (X-ray pelvis) (Incorrect): While imaging can be used for Peyronie's (e.g., ultrasound), an X-ray pelvis is not the primary diagnostic tool for Peyronie's disease and is unrelated to its association with Dupuytren's contracture.\nOption D (Catheterization of urethra) (Incorrect): This is a medical procedure, not a condition associated with Peyronie's disease. It is irrelevant to the question of associated fibrotic disorders.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Condition | Affected Tissue | Key Feature | Associated Conditions |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Peyronie's Disease | Tunica Albuginea (penis) | Fibrotic plaques, penile curvature | Dupuytren's contracture, Plantar fibromatosis |\n| Dupuytren's Contracture | Palmar Fascia (hand) | Nodules, finger contracture | Peyronie's disease, Plantar fibromatosis |\n| Plantar Fibromatosis (Ledderhose) | Plantar Fascia (foot) | Nodules on sole of foot | Peyronie's disease, Dupuytren's contracture |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Peyronie's, Dupuytren's, and Plantar fibromatosis are fibrotic cousins.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn penile ultrasound for Peyronie's disease, hyperechoic plaques with or without calcification are seen within the tunica albuginea.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Urological Association (AUA) Guideline on Peyronie's Disease (2015, reaffirmed 2020). It recommends a thorough history and physical exam, including assessment for associated fibrotic disorders.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Priapism | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | What should be avoided in a patient with suspected rupture urethra? | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | X-ray pelvis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Catheterization of urethra | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: ?) Dupuytren’s contracture** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Competency 2500**\n"
