  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Lymphoma: The great masquerader of the retroperitoneum.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Lymphomas. This diagnosis is crucial in understanding systemic malignancies that can manifest with various symptoms, including those affecting the genitourinary system, often through retroperitoneal involvement causing obstructive uropathy or palpable masses.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nLymphomas are a diverse group of cancers originating from lymphocytes, primarily affecting lymph nodes but also extranodal sites. Retroperitoneal lymphadenopathy due to lymphoma can compress adjacent structures like the ureters, leading to hydronephrosis, or present as a palpable mass on examination. Their diagnosis relies on biopsy and immunohistochemistry to classify the specific subtype, which then guides appropriate chemotherapy or radiation therapy. Understanding their varied presentations is key for early diagnosis and management.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Suprapubic cystostomy) (Incorrect): This is a surgical procedure for bladder drainage, not a diagnosis or a finding related to lymphoma itself. It's a treatment, not a disease.\nOption B (Where is Blummer’s shelf felt on digital rectal examination?) (Incorrect): This is a question about a specific anatomical finding on DRE, not a diagnosis of lymphoma. Blummer's shelf refers to a peritoneal reflection involved in metastatic disease, but it is a sign, not the disease itself.\nOption C (Lateral wall of rectum) (Incorrect): This is an anatomical location, not a diagnosis of lymphoma. While lymphoma can involve the rectum, this option is too general and not a specific diagnosis.\nOption D (Over the prostate) (Incorrect): This is an anatomical location. While lymphoma can involve the prostate, this option is too general and not a specific diagnosis.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Lymphoma | Retroperitoneal Fibrosis | Metastatic Carcinoma |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Origin | Lymphocytes | Inflammatory/idiopathic | Epithelial cells |\n| Presentation | Often B symptoms, palpable mass, obstructive uropathy | Flank pain, renal failure, obstructive uropathy | Variable, depends on primary, obstructive uropathy |\n| Imaging | Homogeneous mass, encasing vessels/ureters, often multiple nodes | \"Mantle\" of soft tissue, encasing structures | Irregular mass, often with necrosis, variable enhancement |\n| Treatment | Chemotherapy, radiation | Steroids, ureteric stenting, surgery | Chemotherapy, radiation, surgery (palliative) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Consider lymphoma in unexplained retroperitoneal masses or obstructive uropathy.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT, lymphoma often appears as homogeneous, enhancing retroperitoneal lymphadenopathy, encasing but not typically invading vessels or ureters, leading to hydronephrosis. Biopsy is crucial for diagnosis.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNational Comprehensive Cancer Network (NCCN) Guidelines for Lymphoma (e.g., 2023). These guidelines provide comprehensive recommendations for diagnosis, staging, and treatment of various lymphoma subtypes.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Suprapubic cystostomy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Where is Blummer’s shelf felt on digital rectal examination? | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Lateral wall of rectum | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Over the prostate | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: ?) Lymphomas** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Competency 2500**\n"
