  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When it comes to GUTB, the epididymis is the 'prime' suspect.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe most common site for genitourinary tuberculosis (GUTB) in the male genital tract is the epididymis. This is due to the hematogenous spread of Mycobacterium tuberculosis, typically from a primary lung infection, with subsequent descending infection through the urinary tract.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nTuberculosis primarily affects the kidneys, then descends to the bladder, prostate, and seminal vesicles, before reaching the epididymis. The epididymis, with its rich vascular supply and convoluted tubular structure, provides an environment conducive to mycobacterial growth and inflammation. This often leads to granulomatous inflammation, caseation, and fibrosis, which can manifest as a palpable, often painless, scrotal mass.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Bladder) (Incorrect): While the bladder is frequently involved in GUTB, it is usually secondary to renal involvement and not the most common *genital* site. Bladder involvement often presents with irritative voiding symptoms.\nOption B (Seminal vesicles) (Incorrect): Seminal vesicles can be involved in GUTB, typically after prostate involvement, but less commonly than the epididymis. Involvement can lead to ejaculatory dysfunction or hematospermia.\nOption D (Testes) (Incorrect): Testicular involvement is usually secondary to epididymal tuberculosis, occurring in advanced stages. Primary testicular TB is rare, and the testes are generally more resistant to infection than the epididymis.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Site of GUTB | Clinical Presentation | Imaging Findings |\n|---|---|---|\n| Kidney | Flank pain, hematuria, sterile pyuria | Hydronephrosis, calyceal destruction, strictures |\n| Bladder | Frequency, urgency, dysuria, sterile pyuria | Contracted bladder, irregular wall, vesicoureteral reflux |\n| Epididymis | Painless scrotal mass, epididymitis | Enlarged, heterogeneous epididymis, calcifications |\n| Testes | Testicular mass, hydrocele | Hypoechoic, heterogeneous testis, abscess formation |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Epididymis is the most common male genital site for TB, often presenting as a painless mass.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn scrotal ultrasound, epididymal TB often appears as an enlarged, heterogeneous epididymis with hypoechoic areas, calcifications, and sometimes associated hydrocele or sinus tracts. Intraoperatively, one might find a firm, nodular epididymis with caseous material or abscesses.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nWHO Guidelines for the programmatic management of drug-resistant tuberculosis (2020 Update): Recommends standard anti-tuberculosis drug regimens for genitourinary TB, often for 6-9 months, with surgical intervention reserved for complications.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Bladder | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Seminal vesicles | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Epididymis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Testes | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: ?) Total amputation with inguinal block dissection** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Competency 2500**\n"
