  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Close the perforators, save the leg!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nIncompetent perforator veins allow blood to flow from the deep venous system into the superficial system, leading to venous hypertension and chronic venous insufficiency. Sodium tetradecyl sulphate is a sclerosing agent commonly used to chemically ablate these incompetent perforators, thereby correcting the abnormal flow.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nPerforator veins connect the superficial and deep venous systems. When their valves become incompetent, blood refluxes from the high-pressure deep system to the low-pressure superficial system, contributing to venous hypertension, skin changes, and ulceration. Sodium tetradecyl sulphate (STS) acts as a detergent sclerosing agent. When injected into an incompetent perforator, it damages the endothelial lining of the vein, leading to inflammation, thrombosis, and ultimately fibrosis and obliteration of the vein lumen. This effectively closes the incompetent perforator, preventing reflux and reducing venous hypertension.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Deep vein thrombosis is an acute thrombotic event in deep veins, distinct from the chronic valvular dysfunction of incompetent perforators.\nOption B (Incorrect): Venous ulcers are a *consequence* of chronic venous insufficiency caused by incompetent perforators, not a treatment or the primary pathology itself.\nOption C (Incorrect): This statement refers to DVT prevention, which is unrelated to the direct treatment of incompetent perforators.\nOption D (Incorrect): \"except\" is a logical operator used in question phrasing, not a medical entity or treatment option.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Treatment Modality | Mechanism of Action | Primary Indication | Key Complications |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Sclerotherapy (e.g., STS) | Chemical endothelial damage, fibrosis, obliteration | Small varicose veins, reticular veins, incompetent perforators | Skin staining, superficial thrombophlebitis, allergic reaction |\n| Endovenous Thermal Ablation (EVLA/RFA) | Thermal energy (laser/radiofrequency) causes vein wall collagen denaturation and contraction | Saphenous vein incompetence, large varicose veins | Pain, bruising, paresthesia, DVT |\n| Open Ligation/Stripping | Surgical removal or disconnection of incompetent vein segments | Large, tortuous varicose veins, saphenous incompetence | Bruising, pain, nerve injury, DVT, recurrence |\n| Phlebectomy | Surgical removal of individual varicose vein segments through small incisions | Symptomatic branch varicosities | Bruising, temporary paresthesia, infection |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Sclerotherapy uses chemical irritation to close incompetent veins.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nDuplex ultrasound is crucial for identifying incompetent perforators, mapping their location, and guiding precise injection during sclerotherapy or planning other ablative procedures.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\n2020 SVS/AVF Clinical Practice Guidelines for the Management of Varicose Veins and Associated Chronic Venous Diseases: These guidelines recommend endovenous thermal ablation or sclerotherapy for symptomatic superficial venous reflux, including perforator incompetence, to improve symptoms and prevent complications.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Deep vein thrombosis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Venous ulcers | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | All of the following can prevent acute deep vein thrombosis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | except | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: ?) Sodium tetradecyl sulphate** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Competency 2500**\n"
